<HEAD>Former Hostages Return Home to Kuwait</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with report hijackers flown to
Damascus, then went over land to Beirut. Picks up 2nd graf pvs,
`The emir ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hostages freed in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> from a hijacked <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jet came home Thursday to a tumultuous reception by thousands of people after being released by nine <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> gunmen, who slipped away. Western diplomatic sources said they had clear evidence the hijackers had reached <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> after Algerian officials allowed them to go free, ending the 15-day siege. In its Friday editions, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted unnamed Arab officials as saying the hijackers had been flown on a private Algerian jet to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and were believed to have then traveled over land to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The emir of <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sabah </PERSON>, and Crown Prince <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Saad </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Sabah </PERSON> led a group of government officials and relatives who were at the <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> airport to meet the former captives. Flocks of doves soared over the airport as the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 707 carrying the 22 passengers and seven crew members touched down Thursday night after a six-hour flight from <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. Two other hostages released early Wednesday were Saudi Arabian citizens and were flown home in a private executive jet. Bedouin men danced and clapped at the Kuwaiti airport, and children waved flags and sang, `` God bless our father, <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON>,'' referring to the emir. The Kuwaiti passengers traveled by motorcade to the city center. Thousands of people lining the route, tossing roses and confetti. Hundreds of others followed in cars and limousines, honking their horns and singing, `` We sacrifice blood and souls for you, O <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>.'' The gunmen, who killed two hostages while the hijacked jumbo jet was in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> last week, disappeared before dawn Wednesday after abandoning their attempt to force <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> to release 17 pro-Iranian terrorists jailed for bombing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French embassies in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> in 1983. Both slain captives were Kuwaitis. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> refused any concessions to the hijackers but <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> apparently promised them passage to a country of their choice if they freed the hostages unharmed. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, criticized by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> governments, has refused to acknowledge making a deal with the hijackers. There was no reference to them Thursday in any of the North African country's state-controlled media. Several of the returning Kuwaiti passengers accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of complicity in the hijacking, saying one gunman was replaced by two others when the craft landed in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. `` One of the two was obviously a military pilot. He was ordering other gunmen around and telling them lots of things about the aircraft and supervising the wiring of explosives to most parts of the plane,'' said passenger <PERSON> Khaled </PERSON> <PERSON> Nasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Zaferi </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>, a brief farewell was held at the <LOCATION> Houari </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boumedienne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> before the former hostages were flown to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. The former captives included three cousins of <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaber </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, ruler of the sheikdom. Compared with their tense, trembling appearance when they had emerged from the hijacked <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, the former captives looked rested and relaxed. <PERSON> Anware </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, second cousin of the emir, said the hijackers treated her and her sister `` with deference and without brutality.'' Their brother, <PERSON> Fadel </PERSON> <PERSON> Khaled </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabah </PERSON>, said he was `` psychologically fatigued'' when he made a statement by radio to the control tower asking that the gunmen's demands be met. After their release, the hostages spent 30 hours at the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> military hospital being examined. A Kuwaiti doctor said all were in good physical condition but the psychological effects of the long, terrifying confinement may be felt for weeks or months. Algerian authorities would not permit journalists to inspect the hijacked plane, which awaited a relief crew to return it to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. One <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> official said the hijackers deliberately damaged the radio equipment before leaving. A member of the airport cleanup crew said trash was strewn through the aircraft, ropes had been used to divide the seating area and a large world map had been pinned to the wall of the forward cabin. He said the stench of rotting fruit filled the plane. Other Arab countries, including <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, praised <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> for achieving freedom for the hostages without additional violence. Algerian media called it a `` victory'' but Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and other Western leaders criticized <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> for allowing the hijackers to get away. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will not rest until the terrorists, the murderers, the hijackers are brought to justice,'' said <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. She declined to say what steps might be taken but said officials are checking to see whether laws apply that allow charges against hijackers when a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen is involved. At least one passenger carried an American passport. An international convention calls for sanctions against any country allowing hijackers to escape unpunished, including an end to direct air service to the offending nation. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> is not a signatory. An Soviet-built Antonov transport of the Algerian air force was seen taking off before dawn Wednesday, shortly before the hostages left the hijacked plane. It was widely assumed the hijackers were aboard the Antonov, which can land on a grassy field.
