<HEAD>CANDIDATE CLOSE-UP: Jackson Left PUSH With Debts and Auditors'
Questions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also moved in advance for Thursday AMs as b0333. This is</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 one in an intermittent series of AP Candidate Close-up stories exploring the careers and backgrounds of the remaining presidential contenders. This story focuses on <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s record running Operation PUSH.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` I like everything you said,'' the old man told <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on the campaign trail, `` but ... wo n't the Republicans be able to clobber you and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on the basis of your lack of governmental experience?'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> looked around the hall. He was in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> suburb, addressing senior citizens who had just listened to a litany of legislative accomplishments from Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, one of his rivals for the presidential nomination. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was ready for this often asked question. In the first place, he said, the Reagan-Bush administration has experience and look what they've done _ a record trade deficit, a record debt, a mess in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and `` the most sleaze and corruption in ... American history.'' Then he launched into his own record of leadership in civil rights and labor strife. `` Of those of us who are running _ if you were about to lose your farm, had to face the banker _ which one would you choose to argue your case? ... If you needed a scholarship for your child who would you want to argue your case? If you had a relative in a foreign jail, who would you send to bring your relative back home?'' Now the punchline _ `` Some office holders are not leaders and some leaders are not office holders ... I am a leader.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has never been elected to office or run a business, but he has headed a nationwide organization, the Chicago-based Operation PUSH _ <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Serve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanity </ORGANIZATION> _ and its education-oriented affiliate, PUSH for Excellence, or PUSH-Excel. His handling of things at PUSH has come under scrutiny for signs of how he might run the government. Over the years, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has used PUSH to keep himself in the spotlight with his crowd-stirring oratory, media-wise instincts and ability to capitalize on the latest public issues. Although he stepped down as head of PUSH when he ran for president in 1984, he often returns to lead its Saturday morning meetings. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was the architect of PUSH's campaign to pressure corporations to expand hiring and business opportunities for minorities. However, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> left PUSH with a record of improper use of government money, high staff turnover and dwindling revenues. His supporters point to PUSH's achievements in strengthening black economic power as examples of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s ability and say he was a genius at keeping the organization afloat despite a chronic cash shortage. They dismiss administrative problems as mstakes made by well-meaning volunteers and low-paid staff members. `` I think he managed incredibly well given the resources he had. All civil rights organizations have always operated at a deficit,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Tidmore </PERSON>, a founding member of PUSH's board. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s critics maintain that PUSH operated like a personality cult, built around <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, rather than a well-managed organization. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> just does n't have the ability to keep things together,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Hosea </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a longtime civil rights activist and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> critic. `` When it comes to building and motivating people, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> is a genius. But he ca n't sustain an effort and that is evidenced by PUSH.'' In the past decade, PUSH has been beset by troubles: _ PUSH for Excellence either misspent or failed to account for $ 1.2 million out of an estimated $ 6.6 million in federal grants from the departments of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, Education, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, federal auditors found The government still is trying to collect the money without having to take PUSH to court. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> concluded in a 1980 audit that PUSH-Excel's `` accounting system and internal controls are not adequate to safeguard its assets,'' or ensure reliable accounting and operating efficiency _ PUSH-Excel and Operation PUSH were hit in the 1970s and early 1980s with more than a dozen lawsuits by businesses seeking payment of overdue bills for such things as telephone service, printing and paper supplies _ In <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 1984 campaign it was revealed the PUSH organizations had received a $ 10,000 donation from <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and $ 200,000 from the League of <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> The contributions were made after <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> toured the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in 1979 and was photographed embracing <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Clovis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>'s ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, said recently that the contribution was made because of `` a growing affinity between the Arab-American and black communities'' at that time. <PERSON> Maksoud </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> has not donated any money since then to the PUSH network.
</TEXT>
