<HEAD>CHICAGO: PUSH network.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 On the other side of the ledger, PUSH improved business opportunities for blacks by persuading corporations to sign `` covenants'' promising jobs and franchises to minorities _ often after PUSH threatened or carried out boycotts of a company's product From the start, on Christmas 1971, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> vowed the group would `` picket, vote and if necessary engage in civil disobedience'' to achieve its goals. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, now a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, recalled <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had quit as head of a similar group, Operation Breadbasket, an arm of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, after clashing with <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> leaders over expenditures and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s independent streak <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> built PUSH into a network with chapters in 32 cities, taking in $ 16.8 million from 1975 to 1986, the last year for which state financial records were filed. He also used the PUSH platform to take on the administrations of several presidents and the city hierarchy of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on a range of issues, from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to contracts for minority-owned businesses. PUSH's Saturday meetings are part of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s political landscape, mixing the gospel flavor of a Southern church revival with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s stirring speeches on the day's hot issues. From the PUSH pulpit, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> pressured companies, such as Burger King and <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>, to sign minority opportunity compacts. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> was instrumental in making a lot of opportunities available _ by that I mean distributorships, getting blacks placed in jobs in chain stores,'' said <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Travis </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> businessman and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporter. PUSH officials have long been secretive about the group's sources of money, other than to say it is supported by individual memberships that now cost $ 20 a person and donations from businesses Some of the corporations that signed covenants with PUSH also contributed money to help sponsor its annual convention or other activities. Coors Brewery, for example, gave $ 20,000 last year to a major PUSH scholarship fund-raising event in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. In 1977, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> broadened PUSH's mission by starting PUSH-Excel to get inner-city youths to study harder. He spoke in packed school gymnasiums nationwide, with students joining in his trademark chant: `` I am ... somebody!'' After <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> fired up the students, PUSH-Excel worked with local school officials to set up special clubs and programs to help keep the youths motivated. But federal auditors later contended that government money received from 1979 to 1982 went for such layouts as $ 211 for music and flowers for a 1979 press party in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>; `` $ 650 for Christmas cards purchased for a related organization''; $ 28 for funeral flowers, and $ 15 for a parking ticket. The government has referred PUSH-Excel's $ 1.2 million debt to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for collection. `` As of now, we have n't been able to resolve it,'' said Justice spokesman <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. PUSH-Excel dramatized <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s strengths, and weaknesses, said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, an education professor who has just finished writing a book about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and the student-motivation program. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> had a lot of very good ideas. He has trouble carrying them through _ that has been his problem,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, who is director of the policy studies laboratory at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>. `` They went through three or four directors, one right after the other, and this was part of his difficulty in administering the program,'' House said. By 1986, PUSH-Excel's revenues, which peaked at $ 2.6 million in 1980, had dropped to $ 209,071 and the group ended the year with a $ 1.5 million debt, including the money owed to the government. Operation PUSH was n't much better off. It started 1986 with a $ 339,056 deficit, but took in enough money to reduce the debt to $ 84,914 by the end of the year, according to its annual report filed with the state. The Rev. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrow </PERSON>, PUSH's national executive director, did not return repeated telephone calls asking for information about the organization's current financial status. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s longtime aide and spokesman, said he understood the group had succeeded this year in nearly erasing its deficit. Although <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was PUSH's driving force, his supporters say he should n't be blamed for organizational problems in areas delegated to subordinates. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> himself has said he did n't get involved in mechanical details. `` If there was anything sloppy about <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>'s management, it was that he could not afford paid, competent people to deal with the various functions of accounting and management of government programs,'' said <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> H.H </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bookins </PERSON>, a leader in the African Methodist Episcopal church and a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporter. `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>'s main thrust was at raising funds to keep the organization afloat. So it was impossible for him to be a hands-on manager of things,'' he said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters point to the success of his 1988 presidential campaign as evidence he can recruit able people to assist him. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who worked as PUSH's national executive director in 1972, said he sees a different <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> today. `` From the time I worked with <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON>, it seems to me he has grown tremendously and his campaign points out one thing _ he has delegated authority.
