<FIRST>r w PM-BicoastalEconomy Bjt   04-21 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bicoastal Economy, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Belt, Mountain States' Income Catching Up With Coastal States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government statistics may be signaling the beginning of the end of a mid-1980s trend that saw booming growth in coastal states outstrip the rest of the country, economists say. Residents of densely populated coastal states like <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachussets </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> continued to have the highest average incomes in the nation last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. States like <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> that are dependent on farming, mining or oil were at or near the bottom. <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> was the highest-income state in the nation, with an average of $ 20,980 earned for every man, woman and child in 1987. That was more than double the $ 10,204 income in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, the perennial last-place finisher. Also as in the recent past, income growth was strongest in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and weakest in energy and mining states. But, <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> DePass </PERSON>, an analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, says the figures show growth is accelerating in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> regions and slowing elsewhere. The national average in 1987 was $ 15,340, up 4.8 percent from a year earlier. Taking the 4.4 percent inflation rate into account, it was the worst gain since the recession year of 1982. That was reflected in even the healthiest regions. The growth of income in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> fell from 7.6 percent in 1986 to 6.7 percent last year. Income growth slipped from 6.5 percent to 6 percent in the <LOCATION> Mid-Atlantic </LOCATION> states. However, income growth in the tottering <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> increased from 0.9 percent to 2.2 percent. It improved in the Mountain states from 3.5 percent to 3.6 percent. `` I think it's signaling the end of the bicoastal economy,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Zandi </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a Philadelphia-area forecasting service. `` The bicoastal trend came to the forefront in 1984 and continued on through most of the first half of 1987. Since last summer ... the bicoastal phenomenon has been on the wane,'' <PERSON> Zandi </PERSON> said. `` As we move into 1989 and 1990, it will become a thing of the past, almost as the Sun Belt-Frost Belt phenomenon waned in the middle 1980s,'' he said. <PERSON> Zandi </PERSON> cited these reasons: _ The increase in exports, which are growing as the falling dollar makes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods cheaper overseas, will boost manufacturing in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and in parts of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> _ Oil and commodity prices are on the way up, brightening prospects for the Oil Patch, Farm Belt and mining states _ Growth in the economy's service sector _ which had benefited financial centers like <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> _ is slowing The effects of the October stock market collapse are more severe there than elsewhere. _ Eastern states and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which rode the growth of high technology firms, are running into a tight labor market, making it likely that companies will look to expand elsewhere `` We can expect to see slower growth in the bicoastal states and stronger growth in the states in the middle,'' <PERSON> Zandi </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, with income of $ 20,067, ranked second in 1987 and <LOCATION> Masschussetts </LOCATION>, with income of $ 18,926, was third. The District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, with income of $ 20,303, would have been second if it was included in the rankings. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, which took over the No. 1 spot from <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> at the start of the oil boom in 1973 and held it until 1985, fell to fifth in 1987 Its average income actually fell 0.7 percent last year to $ 17,886. Rounding out the top 10 were <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Seven of the 10 states with the lowest per capita income were in the South. In addition to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, they were <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> _ energy and mining states _ were also in the lowest 10. Other than <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> was the only state where average income declined in 1987, by 0.1 percent to $ 12,759. But the shrinkage was not as bad as the state's 1.1 percent decline in 1986.
</TEXT>
