<HEAD>Deadline Extension Clears First Of Three Hurdles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A measure extending the deadline for illegal aliens to apply for amnesty faces a difficult fight in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and a possible presidential veto after clearing the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by a narrow margin. The 213-201 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote Wednesday would move the deadline from May 4 to Nov. 30. The extension would represent the first change in the landmark immigration law signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in November 1986. But the Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> issued a warning late Wednesday to potential applicants that they should heed the current May 4 deadline. `` INS is concerned that this misguided legislation will create confusion among potential applicants and cause them to delay filing beyond the May 4 cutoff date,'' the service said in a statement. It said legalization offices will remain open on May 4 until midnight to process applications and that aliens should `` continue to expect that the last date'' to apply will be May 4. The immigration law enacted in 1986 was finely tuned legislation that carefully balanced a legalization program for illegal aliens with penalties for employers who knowingly hire undocumented workers. The narrow margin of Wednesday's vote demonstrated that amnesty for those who came to this country illegally remains an emotional issue. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the amnesty program as part of the immigration bill by only seven votes. The extension is opposed by Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>., the chief <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> author of the 1986 law, and other conservatives The immigration law is a delicately balanced bill that uses a carrot and stick approach to stop illegal aliens from pouring across <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders. Aliens who came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> illegally, but have lived here continuously since before Jan. 1, 1982, were given one year to apply for temporary residency as the first step toward permanent status. The 12-month deadline is May 4. On the enforcement side, the law established severe fines for employers who knowingly hire undocumented workers. Those favoring the extension argue the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reacted too slowly at the onset of the amnesty period, and did not get out the word to the immigrant communities to apply for temporary residency. In addition, many illegal aliens were thought to fear appearing at an office of the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, the agency that is also in the business of deporting those here illegally. In fact, the law prohibits the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> amnesty employees from sharing their records with enforcement agents. Those opposing the amnesty extension in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> were basically the same members who never liked the idea. They said that aliens who refused to come forward were simply procrastinators, and that the carefully structured bill should not be changed to accommodate them. With the deadline approaching, the chief <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> advocate of the extension, Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., plans to have a vote scheduled quickly in that chamber He is chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> and sponsored the chamber's extension proposal If the bill should get through the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, there could be additional problems at the White House. The commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, and Office of Management and Budget officials, have already said they would recommend a presidential veto if the bill reaches <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s desk. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> commented Wednesday, `` Our numbers are right on target with the projections we used when we passed the bill. I do not honestly see a need or justification for extending the signup period.'' During House debate, the chief sponsor of the extension, Rep. <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON>, D-Ky. said 1.2 million aliens have applied for the general amnesty program, and 729,000 have received temporary residency cards Another 400,000 have applied for a separate agricultural amnesty program that is not affected by the extension legislation. Before the final vote, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved by voice vote an amendment designed to cut down on fraud during any extension period. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also defeated 167-246 an amendment that would have only accepted applications after May 4 from aliens who could demonstrate `` good cause'' for missing the deadline.
</TEXT>
