<HEAD>UAW Wants Japanese-Style Pay For Japanese-Style Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> wants its workers to accept Japanese-style production, its executives should accept markedly lower, Japanese-style pay, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>' chief negotiator said Wednesday. The remarks by <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> came in the third day of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> contract talks and a day after <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> disclosed that Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> earned $ 17.9 million in 1987 in salary, cash and stock bonuses and money earned exercising stock options granted when <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> stock was a fraction of its present value. <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s 1987 earnings made him the highest-paid auto executive for the second year in a row. In 1986, when he earned $ 20.6 million, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> also was the nation's highest-paid executive. `` Executive compensations have gotten completely out of hand. ... It makes it extremely difficult for us to sit down in a rational manner and try to negotiate a decent contract,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said, adding that after hearing about <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s pay, workers called union officials demanding higher pay and other benefits. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, the company's chief negotiator, said Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has asked union leaders to support a company push for adoption of so-called Modern Operating Agreements at all plants. The Japanese-style MOA system organizes workers into teams, uses them for a variety of jobs instead of a single defined task and reduces the number of workers needed to fill in for absentees, inspect products and correct mistakes. `` We think it is only fair that since they ask us to go to a Japanese production system such as MOAs and team concept ... it is fair for them to go to the Japanese system in terms of compensation,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. Japanese managers earn six to eight times more than Japanese workers, while American managers earn about 18 times more than their workers, and in <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s case, 27 times, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers earn $ 14.43 an hour including cost-of-living adjustments, or gross base pay of about $ 30,000. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> also said that before Japanese workers are laid off or their pay is cut, Japanese managers take a pay cut. The Chrysler contract expires Sept. 14. It covers 59,000 active workers and 7,000 on layoff in 15 states and 65,000 retirees. Negotiators return to the table Monday prepared to bargain continuously until a contract is reached, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said.
