<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Notches Best Fund-Raising Month Ever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is moving up to the fund-raising league of Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has consistently outpaced all other Democratic presidential candidates, new financial reports show. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> last month raised a total of $ 3.4 million, including $ 621,098 in federal matching funds. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> reported raising $ 2.8 million, including $ 330,189 from the federal matching account. It was <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s biggest ever fund-raising month. In money that came directly from contributors, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> took in $ 2 million, to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' $ 2.4 million. Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who was expected to suspend his campaign today, ran up a debt of $ 1.6 million during March. He took out $ 1.5 million in loans, including $ 40,000 in a personal loan to the campaign. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> borrowed the money to spend on the March 8 Super Tuesday series of 20 primaries, on which he had pinned his hopes. He then borrowed another $ 100,000 more this month before Tuesday's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary, where he pulled a disappointing 10 percent of the vote, trailing far behind <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has taken no loans. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> borrowed $ 250,000 during March. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s overall receipts for March were $ 3.4 million, of which $ 336,312 was matching funds, his report showed. Because he received less than 10 percent of the vote in two previous successive primaries, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> lost his eligibility for federal matching funds under election law. He would have to get an unlikely 20 percent of the vote in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s primary next week in order to re-establish his eligibility. Among Republicans, former TV evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> borrowed $ 410,000 to keep his campaign afloat during March, including a $ 25,000 loan from himself to the campaign. He has had to lay off most of his staff and almost totally eliminate other campaign expenditures because he was up against the maximum $ 27 million spending cap that the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> imposes on candidates who receive federal matching funds. He ended March with $ 1.4 million in debts and only $ 61,890 in cash on hand. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> spent $ 7.8 million during March repaying some of his previous bank loans. He has conceded that Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will win the nomination but <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> technically remains a candidate. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s fund-raising crew has closed up shop, having raised the maximum $ 27 million that primary candidates can spend. During March, he raised $ 1.7 million, of which $ 247,118 was in the form of federal matching funds. He ended the month with $ 3.6 million in the bank to cover close to $ 1 million in outstanding obligations. At the end of March he had spent $ 18.9 million against the base spending cap of $ 23 million, plus the maximum $ 4.6 million allowed for fund-raising expenses. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s treasurer, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, said earlier this month that overall fund raising for the campaign had hit $ 30 million. That included $ 3 million for legal and accounting costs, which are not subject to the spending limit. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> reported raising $ 2.3 million during March, of which $ 896,551 was federal matching funds, and $ 873,444 was money from contributors. With the expensive June 7 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> contest still down the road and a handful of others before it, the remaining Democrats will be refocusing on fund-raising efforts. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ended March with $ 1.7 million in cash on hand to cover $ 697,162 in bills. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had $ 865,946 in the bank and $ 678,973 in debts. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> ended the month with a debt of $ 1.6 million, and $ 416,603 in cash on hand. <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> contender <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, the congressman from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> who dropped out of the race during March, was left with a debt. He ended the month $ 672,826 in the red, but was anticipating more than $ 500,000 in federal matching funds to help retire that. He had only $ 57,741 in the bank, after raising $ 604,586 during the month.
