<FIRST>u i PM-Chile-Crusade Bjt   04-21 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Crusade, Bjt,0940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church-Backed Project Prepares Chile For First Election In 15
Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA DE TRALCA, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A volunteer program backed by the local <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> has been launched to prepare Chileans for their first election in 15 years and, organizers hope, calm the country's stormy political waters. However, the effort already has stirred up controversy of its own, drawing fire from backers of the right-wing military government which charges that it favors the opposition. Leaders of the program, called the Crusade for Citizen Participation, say they hope to recruit 200,000 volunteers across the country for a door-to-door campaign starting in July. They say the aim is to promote voter registration and to provide electors with non-partisan information about their options. `` Most people want a peaceful transition to democracy,'' the crusade's director, <PERSON> Monica </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>, said in an interview. `` It's our task to see that this happens. She said the crusade's participants also will monitor the election's outcome to ensure that it is `` respectable and respected.'' The government plans a yes-or-no ballot later this year on a single presidential candidate to be picked by the chiefs of the armed forces and national police. No date has been set. President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the right-wing army commander who seized power in a 1973 coup, is seen as the most likely candidate. In order to win, the candidate must garner 50 percent of the yes vote plus one. If the candidate wins, he will begin an eight-year term in March 1989. If he loses, an open election will be held in early 1990 and <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> will remain in power in the meantime, according to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 1980 Constitution The country's last election was in March 1973. The military government has held, and won, two referendums on political or constitutional questions. Mrs. <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON>, a university professor and social worker active in church affairs, said she came up with the idea for the crusade a year ago. Under the auspices of a church-run foundation, she studied similar projects in other countries. They included <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, which have returned to civilian rule in recent years, as well as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I had trouble crystallizing the idea, so it helped a great deal to visit and study similar programs elsewhere,'' she said. She obtained a $ 1 million grant from the <ORGANIZATION> Inter-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, to print educational material, train volunteers and pay for television and radio publicity. The training manuals for volunteers quickly prompted charges of bias from pro-government sectors for instructing that, in part, a `` yes'' vote means `` giving support to the operation of a presidentialist, authoritarian regime characterized by ... a regime of limited citizen participation.'' A `` no'' vote means `` re-establishing a balance of powers'' and `` eliminating the control by the armed forces over civilian authorities,'' the instructions say. Citing the material, a commentary in the government-run newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nacion </ORGANIZATION> complained of the crusade's `` slanted, tendentious and partisan spirit.'' `` Its leaders do n't even bother to disguise their opposition tendencies,'' the commentary said. Mrs. <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> responded: `` Because we live in such a polarized atmosphere, to talk of democracy is to already take a side. This is the difficulty we are facing.'' She said describing the <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> government as authoritarian `` is a fact, not a value judgement. I'm not using it in the pejorative sense.'' The crusade appears highly organized. Several supervisors said they took part in organizing Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s April 1987 tour of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and were drawing on that experience. At a Roman Catholic retreat in <LOCATION> Punta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tralca </LOCATION>, a coastal community 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, hundreds of `` first-level'' volunteers from across the country receive intensive training in three-day sessions. They are required to recruit other volunteers in their regions, who in turn will seek out more participants in each community. When the voting takes place, the crusade will be out to try to ensure `` that there is no undue pressure from any sector,'' she said. The Punta de Tralca training sessions have a distinct Catholic, missionary flavor. Upon graduation, the trainees sing a religious hymn and are given neckerchiefs of yellow and white, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> colors. The crusade's logo, of the same colors, is in the shape of a cross. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, like other <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> countries, is overwhelmingly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. At the end of one recent training session, a <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> priest, the Rev. <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Arregui </PERSON>, told the volunteers they were `` like lights, small and fragile, that are going to light up <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> from end to end.'' `` You are carriers of a great message, a message that should change this nation,'' he said. Above him a broad banner quoted Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II: `` <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> has a vocation of comprehension, not confrontation.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> said a central goal of the crusade is to inject some reason into <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s highly impassioned political arena, where pro- and anti-government sectors wildly sling charges at each other. For the opposition, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> is a bloodstained tyrant, while he calls opposition leaders the selfish pawns of international communism. `` An important number of people have already decided whether to vote yes or no,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> said. `` But when you talk to them, you realize that often they are decisions of an emotional, not rational, basis.'' The more rational the political debate, the less likely it is that turmoil will break out when the election is decided, she said. `` We are trying to promote proper civic behavior.''
</TEXT>
