<HEAD>POW-MIA Groups Debate Need To Release Secret Government Data</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Relatives of some American servicemen missing in the Vietnam War say the government is hiding information that may show some prisoners are still alive, and they want <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to approve a bill declassifying the data. But the administration and the official organization representing POW-MIA families say there is no truth to the charges, and they oppose the measure as harmful to the American effort to account for all the missing personnel. The two sides squared off on the sensitive issue Wednesday before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee, which is considering the measure. Dozens of family members, many wearing buttons supporting the bill, jammed a hearing room. The House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> affairs took no action on the measure, which would require declassification of more data about so-called `` live sightings.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> still lists 2,404 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel as unaccounted for 13 years after the war ended. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said an accounting is of `` the highest national priority.'' The official <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position is that the administration can not rule out the possibility that some Americans are still held against their will, although <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> all say they have no prisoners. Some remains have periodically been returned from the area. Those who believe the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government is purposefully withholding information about POWs have cited a variety of reasons. Those include the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wish for better relations with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, and the government's refusal to admit it had left some prisoners behind after the official prisoner exchange in 1973 when 591 American POWs were set free. In recent years, a number of Americans have privately searched for Americans they believe are still being held in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, but have found nothing. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has opposed those efforts. Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, R-Ill., a co-sponsor of the bill, said, `` I am convinced of the possibility that there are prisoners of war from the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War still alive in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, and I believe that the bill is a critical step in raising the awareness necessary to find an answer and know for certain. Retired Army Col. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, father of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> flier shot down 20 years ago, said he and other families have been misled by government officials about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> knowledge on the POW-MIA issue. `` It is because of those experiences and the fact that we have seen evidence in the form of <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> documents proving our men were abandoned and never negotiated for, coupled with the lack of a competent intelligence capability focused on securing information on our live POWs, that we support'' the bill, he said. `` We are suspicious of everything government officials, including those in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration,'' said <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON>, who said he is chairman of an organization called `` The Live <ORGANIZATION> POW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>,'' which he said represents 1,500 POW-MIA family members. But <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffiths </PERSON>, executive director the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> POW-MIA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Families </ORGANIZATION>, noted that similar charges in 1983 led to a similar bill, which was rejected by a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee. She added that `` two congressional investigations, two internal <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> audits and a special study by Lt. <PERSON> Gen </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Tighe </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> USAF </ORGANIZATION> retired, former director of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, have completely discredited those unfounded allegations.'' `` We have total confidence in the president's commitment and determination to fulfill his pledge to act decisively on confirmed information,'' she said. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of defense, and <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Col. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlatter </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s special POW-MIA office, said publication of information would make it more difficult for them to gather information.
