<HEAD>Soviet Leader's Popularity Growing Among Top US Allies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is increasingly popular in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, but only about half of those polled there by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> believe he has done much to improve human rights in his country. `` A majority of those in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- 59 percent -RRB- maintain that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> does not promote human rights in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The West Germans are almost evenly divided on this issue. Only the British -LRB- 54 percent -RRB- say <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> does at least a ` fairly good job' of promoting human rights in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' according to an agency survey in those three nations. General attitudes about the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> followed the same pattern, with 40 percent of the French having a favorable opinion and 50 percent unfavorable, 70 percent of the Germans favorable and 22 percent unfavorable, and 58 percent of the British favorable and 28 percent unfavorable. The remainder were undecided. While <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s popularity has climbed, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s ratings have remained fairly constant over the past six months, according to the poll `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> enjoys an overwhelmingly favorable opinion in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -LRB- 90 percent -RRB- and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> -LRB- 88 percent -RRB-, and a substantially favorable image in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> -LRB- 70 percent -RRB-,'' according to agency analysis of a telephone survey conducted in those three countries March 19-23. `` In the past half year, thos