ION> has balked at negotiations to reduce battlefield nuclear weapons, which many Western military analysts view as necessary to deter a potential attack by Soviet conventional forces. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> leaders want to reduce what they call a 2-1 Soviet advantage in conventional forces. Soviet officials argue that while they have the edge in some weapons, such as tanks, they trail in others, such as anti-tank weapons. The survey found high support for the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces pact signed at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit last December: 93 percent in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 80 percent in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and 74 percent in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.
