<FIRST>r w PM-Superfund     04-21 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Superfund,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says EPA Playing `Merry-Go-Round' With Hazardous Wastes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional study says the `` Superfund'' program remains a hazardous waste `` merry-go-round'' posing long-term problems for the nation despite improvements ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. Dangerous chemicals that should be destroyed are instead still being shifted from one waste dump to another or covered with caps that could allow toxics to leak into water supplies, according to the congressional Office of Technology Assessment. That is the major finding from an ongoing <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> review of the 1986 law <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed to strengthen the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s frequently criticized Superfund cleanup efforts. `` Superfund is not working,'' <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hirschhorn </PERSON>, a senior associate of the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> oversight and investigations subcommittee on Wednesday. `` Public expectations are not being met by the current -LRB- cleanup -RRB- program.'' In an assessment disputed by <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials, <PERSON> Hirschhorn </PERSON> said, `` In too many cases little protection of public health and the environment is being obtained'' by the $ 1.6 billion Superfund is spending each year. One of the basic directives that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 was to permanently destroy `` to the maximum extent practicable'' the contaminated waste found at the worst of the nation's tens of thousands of chemical dumps. <PERSON> Hirschhorn </PERSON> said, however, that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has opted for destruction, usually by costly but effective incineration, in only 20 percent of the cleanup plans approved since the 1986 law took effect. More often, he said, waste is still being switched to other sites, covered by caps or treated through new but unproven technological processes. `` Off-site land disposal means that the hazardous waste problem rides a merry-go-round,'' <PERSON> Hirschhorn </PERSON> testified. `` The problem will keep growing faster than the solution. ... We are going to have hundreds, if not thousands, of sites around the country where the best technologies are not chosen for the cleanup.'' He also had an ominous financial warning, saying the <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION>'s 1985 estimate that the nation evenutally would have to spend $ 300 billion to clean up the mess `` may prove low.'' <PERSON> Hirschhorn </PERSON>, who offered no new cost estimate, said the <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION>'s studies of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup plans show some environmental problems are ignored in order to avoid destruction of waste <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> decided to put a cap on the Compass Industries site in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> but made no commitment to treat contaminated groundwater flowing into the <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, according to OTA. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s cleanup plan said, however, `` the potential for future fires and continued off-site migration of contaminants pose adverse human health and environmental impacts.'' <PERSON> Hirschhorn </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> also found instances where inaccurately high cost estimates for incineration led <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to select cheaper but untested methods to destroy wastes. He said <PERSON> OTA </PERSON> believes that in these cases, incineration would have cost about the same. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said the agency is aiming at permanent treatment of wastes and that a majority of the cleanups involve such treatment of at least a portion of the chemicals found at a site. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s solid waste program, said the agency has not yet settled on a definition of `` permanent.'' He said that if all hazardous waste at a site were destroyed, only six or eight cleanups could be financed each year. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is under <ORGANIZATION> congressional </ORGANIZATION> order to have 175 underway by this October.
