<HEAD>A Year Later, Families, Survivors Struggle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A year after a partially built apartment building collapsed, families, workers and rescuers who toiled for nine days in the fruitless search for survivors remain tormented by the loss of 28 lives. `` In all of my 22 years as an attorney and in all of the hundreds, if not thousands of cases I have been involved in, never have I seen the emotional effect lingering as long as I have in this case,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieder </PERSON>, lead counsel for the victims' families `` To what do I attribute that? I guess I would have to say to the enormity of the loss and the fact that the loss seemed so purposeless,'' <PERSON> Bieder </PERSON> said. One survivor, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelkey </PERSON>, 44, of Prospect, was standing 20 feet away when the L'Ambiance Plaza apartment complex fell in a thundering roar on April 23, 1987. His employer, the <ORGANIZATION> Waterbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, lost 11 workers. <PERSON> Pelkey </PERSON> stayed in construction work, but says he's more cautious and is disturbed by noise. `` I never talk about it,'' he said. `` None of us do.'' June Page of <LOCATION> Hamden </LOCATION> said she struggles daily with the memory of her son <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s death. Page, 30, was married but had no children. `` The hard thing is where do you go now? ... They murdered him as far as I'm concerned,'' Mrs. Page said quietly. L'Ambiance Plaza collapsed in less than 10 seconds on a Thursday at 1:37 p.m., not long after workers had returned from lunch. Within hours, an army of volunteers, many of them workers from construction jobs around booming <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, gathered at the site of what was to have been a 16-story apartment building near downtown. Floodlights were set up for the round-the-clock rescue effort, the families of missing men waited in a nearby school, and the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN