hearings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that examined the work of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is considering a request by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that criminal charges be brought against one contractor. In <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, prosecutors decided not to press criminal charges. The Pages and other victims' families have filed lawsuits against the city, the owners of the project and a subcontractor that performed the lift-slab construction technique. More lawsuits are expected. Page's father, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, was silent during a recent interview in the family's home. He sat staring at lottery tickets in his hand, but when talk turned to the collapse, tears welled up in his eyes. Page's brother <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, also a construction worker, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> did not feel comfortable at the site. `` He was pulled off another job to go there because they had to meet their quotas, to make sure so much work was done so they could get paid,'' the brother said. `` He was just a gentle boy,'' Mrs. Page said. `` I wish he'd never gone into construction.
