<HEAD>Army Plans To Fire 2,600 Civilians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Army will soon begin firing up to 2,600 civilian workers around the country, but remains optimistic <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will help avoid furloughs for up to 150,000 more, a top general says. Maj. Gen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCall </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s budget director, said Wednesday in an interview the service would have to reduce its civilian workforce from 412,000 to 400,000 by Oct. 1, the start of the 1989 fiscal year. That reduction is part of a cut in strength ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> to meet the terms of a deficit-reduction agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last fall. `` You ca n't get those 12,000 people down solely by way of hiring freezes, reductions -LRB- in temporary workers -RRB- and early outs,'' the two-star general said. Although the number of layoffs needed is still subject to change, the current estimate `` is about 2,500 to 2,600 reductions-in-force ... to get 12,000 people off the rolls,'' <PERSON> McCall </PERSON> said. The Pentagon disclosed in its fiscal 1989 budget plan last February that all the services would face reductions in civilian employment and that all but the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> would see actual cuts in military strength as well. The Army has said it will slash 8,600 active-duty positions this year to reach a new level of 772,300. <PERSON> McCall </PERSON>'s comments are the first to detail the precise impact on the civilian side. The general indicated it would be premature to discuss the number of layoffs being planned at individual Army facilities, but said there were 25 to 30 bases around the country that would face civilian cuts. He said the dismissals were designed to meet the spending target set for the next fiscal year. They must be implemented soon because the service must start fiscal 1989 on Oct. 1 at the reduced employment level. Cuts to this year's budget, however, are equally severe and furloughs of civilian workers will be required this summer if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> does n't approve a legislative proposal submitted within the past month. That bill would provide the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> with expanded authority to transfer funds among different accounts and to carry certain funds over from year to year, <PERSON> McCall </PERSON> said. `` We have had indications from at least five -LRB- Army -RRB- commands that without any relief, they would need to furlough to maintain their level of readiness,'' the general said. `` That furlough, in its worst case, -LRB- would be -RRB- as high as 150,000 people ... for varying lengths of time from three to 15 days.'' <PERSON> McCall </PERSON> said he is optimistic <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will grant the flexibility to avoid furloughs because the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> is not asking for an extra appropriation. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must act by June, however, if the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is to avoid the huge furloughs that would be needed to help make up for a $ 2.8 billion cut to its original request of $ 21.3 billion for operations and maintenance spending this year. Roughly 70 percent of all the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s civilian workers are paid from that account, which also holds the money for readiness training for the active force, <PERSON> McCall </PERSON> said.
