<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Engen </PERSON> says the agency must be given more independence, saying needed safety rules were bogged down in the bureaucracy during his tenure. Getting some regulations approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> was like `` a maddening shell and pea'' game <PERSON> Engen </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> aviation subcommittee Wednesday. Some safety rules could be tied up for months because of the slowness of the department, he said. The answer is to remove the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> from the department, he said, as the presidential <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> recommended Monday. `` Rules for a technical field such as aviation must be timely,'' he told lawmakers. `` Safety is often at issue and additional DOT requirements in the laborious rulemaking process can subvert the goal of safety from a timeliness as well as a technical accuracy standpoint.'' <PERSON> Engen </PERSON>'s comments clashed with <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> <PERSON> IV </PERSON>, who told the same subcommittee last month that to get regulations out of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> `` it has been necessary to use the bureaucratic equivalent of a cattle prod.'' Although <PERSON> Engen </PERSON> has been critical before of the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s handling of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> proposals, he has not been as expansive, nor has he previously directly clashed with a department official. <ORGANIZATION> T