<SECOND>PM-Stealth Bomber,600</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Air Force Makes Public First Drawing of `Flying Wing'
^By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Imagine two huge wings from an airplane bolted together without any fuselage in the center. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> says that's the general shape of the new Stealth bomber. Piercing a decade of official secrecy, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday released an artist's drawing of its newest strategic bomber and announced the plane would make its maiden flight later this fall. The service also acknowledged the program was suffering some cost overruns and that a new estimate would have to be released later this year. `` Some cost growth is to be expected in any development program that is on the leading edge of technology like the B-2,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said, using the bomber's official military designation. `` But the acquisition of the B-2 ensures our capability to effectively penetrate Soviet defenses well into the 21st century.'' The Stealth bomber is so named because it is designed to fly without showing up on radar. While the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> has flatly refused to discuss the bomber since design work began in the 1970s, its general shape has actually been known since 1985 when former <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwater </PERSON> disclosed its resemblance to a `` flying wing.'' The drawing distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday shows an airplane that to some extent resembles a boomerang. A small cockpit rises in the middle on top and inlets for the jet engines are placed to each side of the cockpit, also on top of the wing. The design allows the aircraft to be made without any sharp or right angles. According to <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> sources, the plane also relies on the use of radar-absorbing coatings on its exterior surfaces and composite materials for construction. The design has long been the object of experimentation by the <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is building the B-2 for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The company flew a propeller-driven version of such a plane, known as the XB-35, in 1946. A jet-powered version, the YB-49, first flew in late 1947 and was tested by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. But the service never purchased any of the planes, and experimentation with the prototypes ended by the early 1950s. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> declined Wednesday to give a precise date for the maiden flight, saying only that it would occur `` this fall'' and involve a short hop from the manufacturing plant at <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` As the first flight approaches, many actions associated with preparations for that flight can best be accomplished in the open, without compromising program security,'' the service said in explaining its relaxation of secrecy. Details of such things as performance characteristics, crew size and maximum payload remain classified, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said. Indeed, some of the details about the plane's design _ for example, the placement of the engine exhaust outlets _ have been deliberately masked in the artist's rendering, service sources said. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> did acknowledge, however, the plane is going to cost more than originally projected. `` While the acquisition of 132 B-2 bombers was originally estimated to cost $ 36.6 billion in 1981 dollars, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is re-evaluating cost estimates for the program as a result of current and projected fiscal constraints,'' the service said. Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, lauded the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> for releasing more information about the plane, saying the public needs to learn about `` a revolutionary addition to our nuclear deterrent. He predicted the bomber `` will render obsolete billions of dollars of Soviet investment in their current air defense.''
