<HEAD>Environmentalists Call For `Aquafund' To Clean Up US Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A coalition of local environmental groups wants <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to create an `` Aquafund'' to clean up harbors and waterways that are toxic `` hot spots.'' A report released Wednesday by dozens of organizations from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> said the program should be modeled on the government's `` Superfund'' program, which is designed to locate and clean up toxic waste sites on land. `` Our waterways can only be as clean as their container,'' the coalition said in the report issued to lawmakers. The Aquafund proposal and other recommendations came out of an October conference to set a national agenda for the clean up of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s bays, sounds and the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Trudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Coxe </PERSON>, executive director of Save the Bay of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and head of the national conference. `` We're trying to tell you that our bays are worth protecting and fighting for,'' Ms. <PERSON> Coxe </PERSON> told a dozen lawmakers gathered at a conference to discuss the report. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s coastal waters are dying, and we need to take action now, or lose a critical economic resource,'' she said. `` We refuse to endure another summer of coastal horror stories, where dolphins and diseased fish and shellfish are pulled from our marine waters.'' Environmentalists called the October conference, sponsored in part by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the first of its kind for coastal activists and the report the first national coastal agenda. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lakes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, said the problem of toxic sediments has become `` enormous.'' He said polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, found in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, and heavy metals in the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and Puget Sound, have contaminated fish and limit public use. The proposed Aquafund would create a national priority list to identify the toxic `` hot spots'' and fund their clean up. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> now only regulates water quality, not the sediments on the floors of bays and waterways, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Coxe </PERSON> did not put a price tag on the program, saying only it would be a `` multi-multi-million dollar project.'' The report also called for limiting or eliminating federal subsidies that environmentalists say encourage pollution. The group targeted the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, saying it promotes development of fragile coastal areas. The report also called for tougher environmental laws and more stringent enforcement, and a program to protect surviving wetlands and restore at least 10 percent of the wetlands already lost. `` Preventing the pollution of our coastal waters and cleaning up the damage that has already been done are ambitious but absolutely essential goals,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION> `` The recommendations put forth deserve widespread circulation and consideration.''
