<HEAD>Students Rally Around AIDS Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Junior high school students rallied around a student who has tested positive for the AIDS virus, shouting down a small group protesting his admission to the school. `` Go home!'' students yelled at the eight people protesting 12-year-old <PERSON> DeWayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Mowery </PERSON>'s attendance at <ORGANIZATION> Clinton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Police twice had to separate the eight protesters from about 200 angry students and parents. <PERSON> Wanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON>, whose son is a ninth-grader, slammed on her brakes and got out of her car to deride the protesters as `` disgusting.'' Members of the group `` do not know what they are talking about,'' she said. `` They are shaming the town. They are shaming this community. They are showing the whole world how ignorant they are. `` Ignorance and petty fear, that scares me more than AIDS,'' she said. <PERSON> DeWayne </PERSON> was the center of protests last year when he tried to enter <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> School </LOCATION>, an incident that led to his testimony before the presidential AIDS commission earlier this year in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>. Health officials have said that <PERSON> DeWayne </PERSON>, who has shown no symptoms of the syndrome, apparently contracted the virus from a clotting factor he uses in treatment for hemophilia. The substance is made from a blood component. The school's staff members, students and parents have attended special classes organized by the principal, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>, to learn about AIDS and hemophilia, which is characterized by uncontrolled bleeding. The students `` are probably the most informed group of 7th-8th-and 9th-graders in the country on what this boy has, what it can do and how it can be transmitted,'' <PERSON> Heath </PERSON> said. `` Our science teachers have done a fantastic job,'' he said. `` These kids are equipped with a lot of information.'' During lunch Tuesday, several students erected signs on the school grounds saying, `` <PERSON> DeWayne </PERSON> is not hurting us. You are,'' `` Parents get educated,'' `` Innocence ca n't kill: ignorance can. Welcome to CJHS, <PERSON> DeWayne </PERSON>,'' and `` Do n't be ignorant. Get the facts.'' Another sign said, `` Fight with facts. Rumors spread faster than AIDS.'' Near the end of the school day, students gathered to yell `` go home'' at the protesters. Last fall, <PERSON> DeWayne </PERSON>'s parents pulled him out of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> School </LOCATION> after they said they had received threats. After removing him, he had been taking classes alone at a special school. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring. As of April 11, 33,060 people have died of AIDS in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
