<HEAD>Defendants Say Judge Makes `Mockery' of Their Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three defendants in the Iran-Contra case say the judge made `` a mockery'' of their rights by devising `` woefully inadequate'' procedures to determinine if prosecutors illegally used their congressional testimony. In an unusually harsh attack, defense attorneys challenged the procedures <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> adopted for a hearing on whether prosecutors took evidence from the compelled congressional testimony of Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexer </PERSON> and businessman <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>. The lawyers asked <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> to reconsider his denial of their requests to question individual grand jurors and witnesses to determine if independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s investigation was tainted by exposure to the congressional testimony of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>. The procedure for next Monday's hearing `` makes a mockery of the orders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> for the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> compelling defendants' testimony'' before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the defense said in a brief filed Wednesday. Defense attorneys threatened to file an appeal. They also asked <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> to postpone the hearing while he reconsiders how to conduct it. `` The procedures established by the order for determining whether or not there has been or will be any direct or indirect use of defendants' immunized testimony are woefully inadequate,'' the defense said. The three defendants are charged with conspiring to illegally divert to Nicaraguan rebels some of the profits from the sale of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. A fourth defendant, retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, gave congressional testimony without the so-called `` use immunity.'' At a hearing last week, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> rejected defense requests for a wide-ranging inquiry into <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>'s investigative methods and procedures. But the judge ordered <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> to tell the court what steps he took to insulate his staff and the grand jury from the extensive publicity surrounding the defendants' testimony on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> also invited the defense, if it could, to produce a grand jury witness who changed his story after hearing congressional testimony. `` We think we can draw blood fairly quickly,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers, told <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> at the hearing. The latest motion was filed a day before today's deadline for the defense to give <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> the name of the witness it plans to call at next Monday's proceeding. Lawyers for the three defendants contend that publicity of last year's congressional hearings made it impossible for <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> to shield his staff and grand jurors from the testimony, some of which was given under the condition that it could not be used against them in criminal prosecution. `` Certainly common sense tells us that there is vitually no prospective witness in this case who has not been exposed to, and to some degree influenced, by defendants' immunized testimony,'' the joint defense motion said. `` This case is an omelet from which the tainted immunized testimony can never be unscrambled,'' attorneys <PERSON> Brendan </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beckler </PERSON> and <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> said in the motion. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> has said he would dismiss the case if <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> fails to prove he did n't use evidence from the defendants' congressional testimony. But the defense said the judge's methods for making that finding `` appear designed to ensure that any dismissal of the indictment will only follow a protracted trial with its grave risks to our national security and its inherent financial and emotional trauma both for the defendants and for the nation.'' The judge has indicated he would like to start the trial in July, while the defense wants to delay the proceeding until next year.
