<FIRST>r a PM-FetusReduction     04-21 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetus Reduction,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Destroying Fetuses in Some Pregnancies Saves Babies, Raises
Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors believe they can ultimately save babies' lives by selectively destroying some fetuses while sparing others in the same womb, but one ethics expert calls it `` a tragic practice. The procedure has been performed in women who are pregnant with several fetuses, often as a result of fertility drugs or test-tube fertilizations. The chances are slim that four or more fetuses would survive and be healthy. So the strategy is to terminate all but two of them in a procedure called `` selective reduction.'' The two remaining fetuses face reasonably good odds of growing to be healthy, normal infants. `` In patients who choose to undergo selective reduction during the first trimester, the procedure may offer an option to save the lives of a number of desperately wanted infants,'' wrote Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkowitz </PERSON> and colleagues from <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Their report, published in today's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, describes the use of the procedure in 12 pregnancies. Seven of the women had healthy twins, while one had a healthy single baby. Four others had no live-born infants. They also acknowledged, however, that selective reduction raises important ethical questions. Others agreed. In an editorial in the journal, Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hobbins </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> said that even those who think abortion is sometimes justified `` must wrestle with the concept of sacrificing some fetuses so that others can survive.'' The Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priest who teaches moral theology at Notre Dame, said in an interview that `` in the vast majority of cases, that is morally wrong.'' <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said the procedure is morally acceptable only after accidents, such as inadvertant overdoses of fertility drugs, that result in so many fetuses that none is likely to survive. `` A case can be made for doing it when it's the only life-saving alternative available,'' <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON> said. `` Even then, everybody feels chilly about it.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON>, a medical ethics expert at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>, called it `` a tragic practice'' and `` a very sad intervention.'' Doctors who perform test-tube fertilizations often implant several embryos in hopes that one will survive, but sometimes more may grow. <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> said doctors who perform these fertilizations should implant no more than four embryos so that they minimize the risk of multiple fetuses, and physicians also should be careful to prescribe the minimum effective dose of fertility drugs. `` Once you are stuck in a situation, it's morally defensible to do it,'' he said of selective reduction. `` But you should do everything you can to avoid that situation.'' In his report, <PERSON> Berkowitz </PERSON> noted that in the past, couples have had only two choices: take their chances on a successful outcome or abort the entire pregnancy. However, he said the decision to have selective reduction is also hard for parents anxious to have babies. It should only be done if they are prepared to lose the entire pregnancy. In the 12 cases described, the doctors selectively destroyed all but two fetuses in each woman. In most cases, this was done by injecting potassium chloride into the fetal hearts. Of those who received the procedure, two of the women had each conceived six fetuses, one had five, five had four and four were carrying triplets. <PERSON> Berkowitz </PERSON> said that women who carry four or more fetuses are ideal candidates for the approach because of the high risk of complications. However, triplets `` are in a gray area and present an enormous dilemma for both the patients and their physicians.'' He said it should not be done with twins, since chances are good that both will develop to be healthy babies.
</TEXT>
