<FIRST>r p PM-Networks-Projections     04-21 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Projections,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC News President Disenchanted in Projections Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Come November, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> might not abide by its handshake agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> not to project a winner in the presidential election until all polls have closed. NBC News President <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> said Wednesday he is `` uncomfortable'' with the agreement, which was elicited by sponsors of legislation to establish a nationwide uniform poll closing time. `` We're very concerned about it and we'll re-evaluate it before the election in November if there's no progress made -LRB- on the poll closing bill -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s decision could put pressure on the two other networks to abandon the policy, stated in an informal agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as part of a push for a uniform national poll closing time. Meantime, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> is abiding by the policy, although `` NBC Nightly News'' anchor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> said Tuesday night during coverage of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary almost two hours before polls closed that <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` may well be headed for victory.'' `` Nightly News'' has been making similar statements about trends in races throughout the primary season. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> and CBS' Dan Rather both said Tuesday night during their broadcasts that they could not predict the election because polls were still open in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The polls closed at 9 p.m. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s report followed a local <ORGANIZATION> WNBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> newscast predicting <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as the winner statewide and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as carrying <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON> insisted the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> report did not violate the agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> because it was n't technically a `` projection.'' In a 1985 letter to Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, D-Wash., <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON>, like his counterparts at <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, vowed <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> would `` not use the exit poll data we gather to suggest the probable winner in any state until polls in that state have closed. The letter was part of an agreement sought by <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., to help their legislation proposing a uniform poll closing time in presidential election years <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> criticized <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s Tuesday evening report for not being true to the `` spirit'' of network policy. `` However, one might argue the letter of it,'' <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said in a statement. He praised <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and CBS for explicitly stating that they would not make a prediction until the polls closed. `` It is my hope that this is just an error and that NBC News will reaffirm its policy and that the other news operations will not see this incident as cause to abandon their policy or practice,'' <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said. `` It's a very frustrating situation,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bettag </PERSON>, executive producer of the `` CBS Evening News.'' `` I think somebody's got to seriously rethink how this all works. It is very frustrating to be in the position we were in last night, knowing that your opposition has for weeks been characterizing elections. It's a very uncomfortable position to be in.'' By the time the networks go on the air, they usually have exit polling data upon which they could accurately predict the outcome of the election. Release of such information theoretically disenfranchises voters still waiting to cast votes. In a presidential election, polls in Western states are still open after polls on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> have closed. Ironically, it was not the networks but then-President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> who sparked the most controversy when in 1980, he conceded the presidential election to <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> before polls on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> had closed.
