<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSVaccine     04-21 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Vaccine,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Booster Shots Prolong Effect of Experimental AIDS Vaccine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A researcher who gave himself an experimental AIDS vaccine still showed immune system defenses against the AIDS virus a year later, thanks to booster treatments, scientists reported today. But the booster procedure must be simplified before it could be used in large-scale tests to see if the vaccine can actually prevent AIDS virus infection, they said. `` We are in the process of finding an easier way,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON> of the <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Marie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Curie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, who made headlines in March 1987 by reporting that he and some volunteers had been given the vaccine. It was the first reported human test of a vaccine against acquired immune deficiency syndrome. There have been no side effects, he said. The vaccine was essentially a vaccinia virus genetically modified to produce an AIDS virus protein called gp160. The idea was that the immune system would react to the protein, raising defenses that also might fight the AIDS virus. In last year's report, <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON> and co-authors said the vaccine made his immune system produce two kinds of defenses: proteins called antibodies and special blood cells. Evidence of defenses appeared up to 370 days after the initial vaccination, he and his colleagues wrote in today's British journal Nature. But there is no proof that the Zagury could have resisted infection by the AIDS virus, he and 16 scientists from <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, wrote. <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON> received three booster treatments. About three months after the vaccination, blood cells were drawn from him and infected with more modified vaccinia virus. Then the cells were re-injected through a slow-drip intravenous line, a process that took about 3 -LCB- hours, <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. The second and third boosters were injections of the AIDS virus protein, given 299 days and 350 days after the initial vaccine. Two unvaccinated volunteers who received only the protein shots showed no immune system response. <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON> showed antibodies against the AIDS virus protein 13 days after the first booster, a reaction lasting three months. Nine days after second treatment, more antibodies against the AIDS virus protein and against a viral protein made from it, called gp120, appeared. Those levels rose after the third booster. Tests at various times showed that under certain conditions, immune system factors in Zagury's blood inhibited two dissimilar strains of the AIDS virus from infecting cells in the test tube. Each booster treatment also markedly increased the ability of <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON>'s immune system cells to proliferate when exposed to either strain in the test tube. In addition, his immune system cells could destroy virus-infected cells for a time after each booster treatment. In another test, doses of AIDS virus protein were injected just under the surface of <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON>'s skin before the second booster and 20 days after the third. His immune system reacted each time, showing it was still primed. The process of removing, treating and re-injecting immune system cells would be too cumbersome to use in a large-scale experiment, as would be required to test the vaccine's effectiveness, <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>, an American AIDS vaccine expert, said the fact that <PERSON> Zagury </PERSON>'s immune system acted against quite different strains of the AIDS virus is significant. Many previous studies suggested that a vaccine using one strain might not work against other strains of the highly variable AIDS virus, said <PERSON> Moss </PERSON>, chief of the laboratory of viral diseases at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases.
</TEXT>
