<HEAD>Mysteries of Texas Highways Probed in New Travel Book</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The 288-page ...' to delete extraneous coma
after word `wife.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a state where thousands of empty miles promise little more than highway hypnosis, and today's culinary special may be a bowl of truck-stop chili, relief is in sight for the culturally bereft. A new guidebook takes some of the mystery out of the seemingly endless ribbons of roadway in the Lone Star state by detailing motels, restaurants, gas stations, convenience stores and bank machines at every <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> freeway exit. `` Just gathering the information was a monumental effort,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cima </PERSON>, who probed the delights of 2,400 exits during a four-month, 7,000-mile jaunt to assemble `` Sunset Highway Services Directory, Exit-By-Exit.'' His Baedeker of the beaten track is a must, for example, at exit 761-761A in west <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, where finicky tourists must decide whether they want to get gas at the <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Conoco </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> or Exxon stations. Hungry motorists can eat at Platters or Steak & amp; Ale or perhaps pick up something at the 24-hour Stop N Go. <ORGANIZATION> Sunbelt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> bank also is at the exit. The 288-page soft-cover book also includes <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Cima </PERSON> and his wife eventually want to write a 10-book series covering the entire country. But mostly, except for about 50 pages, the guide concerns <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which <PERSON> Cima </PERSON> said `` has its own character and personality.'' Shortly after drivers reach Exit 0 at the <LOCATION> Texas-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> border, he points out, there's an anti-littering sign: `` Do n't Mess with <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.'' `` That says it all,'' <PERSON> Cima </PERSON> said. `` It's very clear when you enter <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, you've entered the Lone Star State.'' The Cimas' inaugural effort two years ago was a similar book about <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cima </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Saundra </PERSON>, an airline flight attendant, came up with the idea after repeatedly driving home to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and worrying about where to pull off the freeway if her car broke down. <PERSON> Cima </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> test pilot, cruised every <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> freeway and many other highways with three other drivers, getting off at each exit to make note of the services available to motorists. `` That was the only way to get complete information,'' <PERSON> Cima </PERSON> said recently from his base in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. Besides restaurants, motels and service stations, the listings include shopping centers, hospitals and police stations. A second driver later retraced most of the routes to verify the information. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> really seemed like a pretty good idea,'' he said. `` With all the RV -LRB- recreational vehicle -RRB- traffic and all the people coming to <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> from the North, it seemed like a logical extension of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.'' `` As it turns out, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has more exits than <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> had 2,800. But obviously there are more miles of driving in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The exits come a little closer in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, so that makes the book a little more valuable commodity in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>.'' About 50,000 copies of the book, priced at $ 12.95, are being distributed to bookstores in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` We hope to sell a lot more than that,'' said <PERSON> Cima </PERSON>. `` The book should be good for about two years. Things are n't changing all that rapidly. What you see is a few more businesses will pop up. Everything we have listed is going to be there in a few years.''
