<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says preliminary results from new tests show that a controversial chemical used to regulate the growth of apples does cause tumors in mice. But <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Assistant Administrator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, in an Arpil 8 letter to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency does not yet have enough information to make a decision on what to do. However <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said in the letter, obtained by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday, that a decision could be announced as early as fall on whether to ban use of the chemical. The chemical, daminozide had been used on about 40 percent of the nation's apple crop. Applied in the summer, it slows growth, makes apples ripen together, deepens color and lengthens storage life. The agency began studying daminozide in 1980 and proposed to ban it in 1985, but decided to order new studies when its own scientific advisers said it had not proved its case. It did lower the permissible residues in apples and the amount that may be used in orchards. `` I hope that it is clear from the information provided in this letter that we do not yet have enough information'' to decide what to do about daminozide, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> wrote. <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, which manufactures daminozide has told apple growers it remains confident that the chemical, sold under the trade name Alar, eventually will be cleared.
