<HEAD>House Panel OKs Torture Victim Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House Foreign Affairs subcommittee has unanimously approved a bill that would allow <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> residents who are victims of torture overseas to seek civil damages in federal court. All torture victims, either foreign aliens or <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens, living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be covered once they had exhausted all legal remedies in the country where the torture occurred. The families of victims of political killings also would be entitled to seek damages under the bill. Persons who actually committed or ordered torture or political killings could be sued if they visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The measure, sponsored chiefly by Reps. <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Yatron </PERSON>, D-Pa., <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, has been endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>, which told a March 23 subcommittee hearing the bill would help deter the `` human rights epidemic'' of torture which is practiced systematically in 30 countries
