<HEAD>Alarms And Tension As U.S. Awaits Possible Iranian Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS JACK WILLIAMS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Occasional alarms and tension kept sailors alert aboard this guided-missile frigate in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> waited for signs of new Iranian attacks. Senior officers analyzed the tactical and technical data still flowing in on Monday's battles with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in the gulf. Meanwhile, a search was called off for a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> helicopter carrying a two-man crew that vanished hours after the day-long exchange of gunfire on Monday had ended. Officers on the <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, flagship for one of the three surface action groups of three ships each, said there was nothing to support <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s claim that the AH-1 Cobra gunship was shot down. It was the third <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> helicopter lost in the gulf since July 1987, when the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration began providing naval escort for 11 Kuwaiti oil tankers re-registered under the Stars and Stripes for protection from Iranian attack. The 200-plus crew members of the <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> were still putting things back in order _ cleaning equipment, weapons and passageways _ in the wake of Monday's action. In the course of it, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> fired five missiles at the <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and two destroyers sailing with it. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers said they were Chinese-made Silkworm missiles fired from anti-ship batteries along the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION> for the first time. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said it had not determined what type of missile was fired. All five missiles went awry, their guidance systems confused by aluminum chaff fired into the air by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ships. The 3,700-ton frigate, operating in the southern gulf, remained at Condition 1-Alpha, the second-highest level of alert in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, below General Quarters. The <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' skipper, Cmdr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, 42, of <LOCATION> Bucks </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> said: `` We can do this for a month if necessary, because we have trained, organized and planned to do it _ we came here ready for the long haul.'' An alarm sounded at midmorning Wednesday when the ship's radar picked up a signal that the <ORGANIZATION> Combat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> evaluated as a Sea Hunter radar system, one that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> is known to possess and that can be used to locate a missile target. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, said the radar twitch would be analyzed to determine where it originated. The missile destroyer <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> and the destroyer <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> are also part of Desron 22, the <ORGANIZATION> Destroyer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> aboard this warship. <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>'s home port is <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> is based at <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. Also Wednesday, the <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> warned off an Iranian C-130 aircraft, whose pilot at first ignored the ship's radioed challenges and then answered by saying: `` We are an Iranian warplane, doing our duty.'' A voice, speaking accented english, then said: `` Martyr, do your duty.'' Minutes after the C-130 landed at <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s nearby <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Musa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the frigate went to General Quarters as a precaution against the possibility that a canister of CS, a non-lethal type of riot control gas, had been dropped in the area. A team checked the ship, and found no indications any such canister had been dropped. The ship also received brief reports of Iranian speedboats attacking commercial vessels in the Strait of Hormuz and the discovery of two floating mines, apparently by the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> navy farther north. British and Italian minesweepers also were understood to be taking part in mine-hunting operations in international waters of the central gulf. Capt. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyer </PERSON>, commander of Desron 22, said the mines apparently were floating rather than moored, and were found 70 miles southwest of where the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> guided-missile frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was severely damaged last week. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of laying the mine that damaged the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> and retaliated by shelling two Iranian oil platforms. After that, Iranian attack boats went on a rampage and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval forces and neutral shipping. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces sank or damaged six Iranian warships. The <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> crew on Wednesday hashed over the events, the first combat experience for all expect the captain, Cmdr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, and Master Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. The crewmen, whose average age is about 22, appeared generally united in believing that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was proper. `` Nobody wants to kill people but you ca n't just let them run over everybody,'' said Petty Officer 2nd class <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>, 20, of <LOCATION> Zanesville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>, the ship's storekeeper, was a communications man on the bridge throughout those hectic hours, when missiles left the sky criss-crossed with trails and deck officers shouted `` Silkworm inbound!'' as the lumbering projectiles were spotted visually or by electronic means. Also on the bridge was <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON>, 25, who lives with his wife in <LOCATION> Mayport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, home port of the <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON>, who keeps a diary of everything that has happened on his frigate's gulf excursion, said the situation was scary. `` But the worst was when our own missile was fired and we did n't know it was going to happen. it took everybody by surprise,'' he said. Gunner's Mate <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Talbert </PERSON>, 18, said he was manning the <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' 76-mm deck gun during the excitement and found it `` the same as always when we're at General Quarters. `` But there's a helpless feeling in there _ not knowing what's going on is worse than something happening,'' said <PERSON> Talbert </PERSON>, whose class at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, will graduate in June Some sailors asked members of a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> news media pool aboard the frigate to let their relatives in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> know that they were all right. `` That's the most important thing, to let them know that,'' said <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>.
