<HEAD>House Of Commons Suspends Maverick Legislator For 20 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> barred a militant Scottish member from the next 20 working days of Commons business for damaging the 16th-century staff that symbolizes the speaker's authority Legislators voted 463-26 Wednesday night to suspend <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a left-wing member of the socialist opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> grabbed the ornate 5-foot-long mace in the Commons on Monday night and dropped it in front of the sergeant-at-arms in an angry protest over government cuts in welfare payments. The suspension vote followed <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s refusal Tuesday to read out a formal statement of apology for his behavior. Earlier Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> hierarchy voted to ostracize <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> from any role in party activities for three months. It is the first time in 21 years that Labor leaders have taken such action. The decision must be approved by a ballot of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s 229 elected representatives. Their decision takes effect only when <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> returns from any suspension agreed by the Commons. `` The whole thing is a storm in a tea cup,'' the 47-year-old <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> told reporters before the vote. `` I have a job of work to do, and I will still do it even if I am suspended.'' At the end of debate Monday night, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> marched from his seat in the back benches on to the floor of the Commons, threw papers in the face of a junior government minister, then picked up the 16-pound mace from its resting place at the foot of the table behind which Commons officers sit. What happened next is disputed. The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and other news media witnesses said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> threw the mace on the floor, causing an estimated $ 1,890 worth of damage to the silver-gilt staff, before storming out of the chamber. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> says he accidentally dropped the mace. The mace is officially part of the Crown Jewels. Its presence in the Commons indicates the legislative body is in session. News reports said Labor Party Leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> is exasperated that the antics of rebel Laborites are distracting attention from <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s attacks on government moves to reform the post-World War II welfare benefits system. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> and other militants have vowed to use `` guerrilla tactics'' to disrupt the Commons, in which Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s Conservatives have a comfortable majority of 102. Unruly legislators now routinely hurl insults at each other and shout down opponents, ignoring appeals for order from Speaker <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Weatherill </PERSON>. Last month, <PERSON> Weatherill </PERSON> banned a <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislator for five days for screaming abuse that caused an unprecedented suspension of budget day proceedings. The uproar was prompted by the government's announcement that it was slashing income tax for top wage earners from 60 to 40 percent.
