<HEAD>At Least 22 Die In Bus Explosion In Thailand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Paramilitary rangers accidentally set off a phosphorus bomb on a passenger bus in northeastern <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, killing at least 22 people and seriously injuring 20, police said today. Among the dead was a 2-year-old girl, they said. Col. <PERSON> Sittisak </PERSON> <PERSON> Intomya </PERSON>, provincial police commander, said five rangers seated at the rear of the bus ignored pleas from other passengers to put away the bomb as the bus traveled in <LOCATION> Nonsoong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, 200 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. He gave no details on how the bomb was detonated, but said the men were believed to have come from <LOCATION> Pakthongchai </LOCATION> ranger base. The colonel quoted witnesses as saying one ranger escaped after the explosion. He did not specify if the other rangers were killed in the blast. Phosphorus is poisonous and mixes easily with oxygen and ignites spontaneously at room temperature.
