<HEAD>Dollar Firmer, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar opened firmer against major foreign currencies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today and was holding steady in early trading, dealers said. Gold prices fell. European dealers said there were no fundamental reasons for the dollar's rebound, although they said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency was getting some support from fears that central banks would step in to stop any slide. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.40 yen to a closing 124.30. Later, it was also quoted at 124.30 yen in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday: _ 1.6682 West German marks, up from 1.6635 _ 1.3780 Swiss francs, up from 1.3745 _ 5.6660 French francs, up from 5.6490 _ 1.8715 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8630 _ 1,240.25 Italian lire, up from 1,234.50 _ 1.2302 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2283 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.8872, cheaper for buyers than $ 1.8930 late Wednesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 453.50 a troy ounce and at midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a slightly higher recommended price of $ 454. Late Wednesday's bid price was $ 456.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 454.80, down from 457.50 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 4.04 to close at a bid $ 454.90. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Thursday at a bid price of $ 6.43 a troy ounce, down from Wednesday's $ 6.46.
