<FIRST>r a PM-ShuttleTest     04-21 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Test,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Cautiously Optimistic About Booster Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An apparently flawless test-firing of the space shuttle's redesigned booster rocket has improved the odds of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> meeting its goal of resuming manned space flight in mid-August, officials say. Wednesday's two-minute firing of the 126-foot rocket went smoothly, but spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>, which manufactures the booster, say it will take a week to 10 days to verify the test was a success. A cursory inspection of the rocket afterward indicated the redesigned seals in the booster's joints prevented an escape of hot gases despite deliberately built-in flaws. `` It's a happy day for a lot of people,'' said <PERSON> Royce </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, solid rocket program manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` So far, it looks excellent.'' In a post-test briefing, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> vice president for engineering, displayed a graph on which nearly identical curves compared engineers' predictions with a preliminary test evaluation taken from electronic monitors. `` Unless you're about only eight millimeters away, you ca n't tell any difference,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said Barring discovery of problems as the rocket is dismantled, Wednesday's success means <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> must conduct only two more full-scale tests, in June and July, before <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> can proceed with an August launch of the shuttle Discovery. It would be <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s first manned space flight since the shuttle Challenger exploded 70 seconds after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986, killing seven crew members. `` It's like finally winning the quarterfinals of the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said of the test. The critical concern is whether super-hot gases escaped the flawed seals. A presidential commission blamed the Challenger disaster on a joint between segments of the booster rocket whose seals failed, allowing gases to escape and ignite the space craft's exterior fuel tank Since then, engineers have added a third O-ring to the seals and a metal lip, or capture feature, to contain gases that may leak around the joints linking the four segments of the rocket. The case-to-nozzle joint also has been strengthened with 100 radial bolts to prevent vibration during launch, part of a redesign planned before the Challenger exploded. This joint attaches the nozzle to the aft segment. In the middle joint, engineers left a gap one-tenth of an inch wide between two sections of insulation to see if it would seal itself, under pressure from the expanding gases, as it has in short-duration tests. A second flaw was placed in the adhesive binding insulation inside the case-to-nozzle joint. A tiny `` blowhole'' was created to allow gases to reach the `` wiper'' O-ring, which was installed as part of the new design to keep the adhesive in place. However, it also acts as an additional seal to protect the primary and secondary O-rings. In the short-duration tests, gases have hit the wiper ring but have not gone past it. <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON> said the flaws were more severe than anything likely to occur during manufacture or assembly. `` It is, indeed, a fail-safe. If at any time gas gets beyond the point we expect it to, the joint still is going to perform,'' he said.
</TEXT>
