<HEAD>Mexican Journalists Outraged By Killing Of Newspaper Columnist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mexican journalists say the shotgun slaying of a satirical columnist is part of a pattern of intimidation, and a colleague said he might ask <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s federal government to take over the investigation. <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON>, the 47-year-old co-editor of Zeta, was killed while driving to work Wednesday morning, said District Attorney <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Dominguez </PERSON>. Police said they had not determined a motive. According to a spokesman for the state prosecutor's office in <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>, a brown pickup truck with a camper shell pulled alongside <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>'s car. Shots were fired from an automatic 12-gauge shotgun. `` This cowardly act increases the climate of insecurity in which <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION> journalists live,'' said <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Garca </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, city editor of <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>'s oldest daily, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heraldo </LOCATION>. He said he would go to Mexican President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> if state investigators do not solve the case. Five Mexican journalists have been killed this year, and 35 have been killed in the past decade. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Zeta </ORGANIZATION>'s offices were sprayed with bullets from a passing car. No one was injured and police never found those responsible. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Baca </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicano </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday a letter asking for an investigation into the slaying was being sent to de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. `` This assassination poses the greatest threat to freedom of the press in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Baca </PERSON> said. `` There's been a large number of other journalists who have met a similar fate, and it's obvious that it has become a pattern to silence the independent press in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Blancornelas </PERSON>, who co-founded the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Zeta </ORGANIZATION> with <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> in 1980, speculated that the killing was an act of political revenge. `` The government said that it respects freedom of expression and that the police are among the most advanced,'' <PERSON> Blancornelas </PERSON> said. `` We hope that both those things might be demonstrated.'' <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>, known as `` Felix the Cat,'' wrote for the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Zeta </ORGANIZATION>, which has a circulation of 60,000 throughout <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. His column, `` A Little Bit of Something,'' often accused government officials and business people of arrogant behavior. `` He was a satirist. He was very well-known and popular here in the state,'' said <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervantes </PERSON>, a writer for <ORGANIZATION> Zeta </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Cervantes </PERSON> said <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> had no known enemies and called the shooting `` an act of cowards'' aimed at muzzling the press. <PERSON> Felix </PERSON>'s murder follows by two months the still-unsolved slaying of <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgueno </PERSON> <PERSON> Orduno </PERSON>, editor of the monthly political magazine Deslinde, in the <LOCATION> Baja </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coastal resort city of <LOCATION> Mazatlan </LOCATION>.
