<FIRST>r w PM-GroceryAds     04-21 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grocery Ads,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supermarkets to be Allowed to Offer Rainchecks, Substitutes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government is moving to legalize a common supermarket practice, giving out rainchecks or substitutes when a store runs out of advertised items. While an effective date has not been announced, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> voted 3-2 Wednesday to permit substitutes and rainchecks at grocery stores. Many stores of all types have been making such offers for years, of course. But technically, the practice was made illegal for grocery stores in 1971. In that year, the commission adopted a regulation requiring that grocers have enough stock on hand to meet `` reasonably anticipated demand'' for advertised items. Those that run out can be fined, though that has rarely happened in practice. Under the change approved Wednesday, grocers that do n't want to offer substitutes or rainchecks would be allowed to advertise items in limited supply if they clearly state in the ads that supplies are limited. The 1971 rule was adopted following studies that showed as much as 10 percent of advertised items were unavailable in markets in the 1970s. By 1984, however, that rate had dropped to between 3 percent and 5 percent, and the commission began to reconsider the rule. The commission staff at that time reported that the costs to supermarkets of observing the rule _ keeping added stock on hand and perhaps limiting advertising _ raised the cost of groceries more than the sale prices lowered them. In other words, the staff said, the rule was forcing consumers to pay an extra 1.4 cents to 3.3 cents a week in their grocery bill. On that basis, some commission staffers recommended abandoning the rule altogether, an approach that drew heavy negative public comment in 1984. Nonetheless, Commissioner <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Calvani </PERSON> pressed again Wednesday to have the entire rule repealed. `` I do n't believe there is a problem,'' he said, contending that supermarket managers strive to please their customers rather than injure them. In such a competitive business, if a market regularly failed to stock advertised items, customers would just stop shopping there, he said. Commissioner <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Strenio </PERSON>, though, contended that the rule `` simply requires retail food markets to honor the promises they make in advertising.'' <PERSON> Strenio </PERSON> added that he is skeptical of the statistics that show the cost of the rule to be more than the savings to consumers, and said he opposed any changes in the rule that has been in effect since 1971. Thus, <PERSON> Calvani </PERSON> and <PERSON> Strenio </PERSON> voted against the amendment to permit substitutions and rainchecks, but for opposite reasons. Voting for the new rule were Commissioners <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcuenaga </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> and Chairman <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> said he would prefer to join <PERSON> Calvani </PERSON> in eliminating the rule altogether, but since that option had been defeated on an earlier ballot, he would support the amendment permitting use of rain checks or substitutes in order to give grocers as much flexibility as possible.
</TEXT>
