<HEAD>Speakes Says Book Not `Kiss-and-Tell'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former presidential spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said today he made up quotes from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> out of loyalty to the president, and the adverse reaction to it has been a `` total surprise.'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said he disagrees with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that his book `` Speaking Out'', which covers his six years at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and reveals the quote-manufacturing, constitutes `` kiss and tell.'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, appearing on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show, also said he does not fault the president for forgetting he told him about the phony quotes while <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said in the book that a comment he provided as having been made by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was never said, and another quote he gave as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s actually was said by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. `` I did it on the spur of the moment. I did it in order to serve the president. I did it as an act of loyalty to the president, certainly not as an act of disloyalty to the president,'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said. The furor over <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>' confession led to his resignation last week as chief spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ a job he took after leaving the White House. Reacting to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s criticism of books written by a string of former administration officials, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said he does n't think any of the books, including his, falls into the category of `` kiss and tell.'' Such a book would `` have a little more juicy-type items in it that are a little bit more punchy,'' said <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>. As a former journalist, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> was asked if he did not know that making up quotes would be controversial. `` No, it was a total surprise,'' he said. `` A lot of people have told me that's done all the time in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, that you supply a few quotes.'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, who told a <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> forum on Tuesday that he had been `` overzealous'' and `` misguided'' in concocting the quotes, said today he did not know whether the sin was in the doing or in the telling about it. `` It's hard for me to decide what I'm being critized for,'' he said. <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> defended his book as an honest account that he hoped would `` contribute something to the long-term value of insights into the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration.'' He said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s presidency was a watershed because he has `` changed the way we think about government.'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said he was pleased with indications that the book is selling well and said he planned to continue giving public speeches and promoting the book. `` I'll just let the dust settle a little bit and look at opportunities in the future,'' he said.
