<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, convicted of being a brutal <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp guard despite his insistence that he was a victim of mistaken identity, admitted his guilt two years ago, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshal says. <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> autoworker who was found guilty Monday by an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> court of war crimes, said in the hearing of <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Koury </PERSON> and another marshal accompanying him from a federal penitentiary in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in February 1986: `` They do n't understand. It was war. I had to do it.'' `` The statement was made almost like he was thinking out loud,'' <PERSON> Koury </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` He was sort of looking out the -LRB- airplane -RRB- window. The statement was not made to the deputy or me. `` It was an admission of guilt. But I did n't think much of it at the time. I knew that <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> had fought losing his citizenship and being extradited. But I did not know that he had denied that he was who they believed he was.'' And Deputy Marshal <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said: `` It was clear to me that when he realized he was really going to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he was trying to justify to himself what he had done. He was trying to rationalize.'' <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> was convicted of being the <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION> death camp guard known as ` Ivan the Terrible'' for his brutality. <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> helped operate the gas chambers at the camp in Nazi-occupied <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, where 850,000 Jews were killed in 1942 and 1943. According to testimony at the 14-month trial, <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> often exceeded the atrocities ordered by his superiors, beating prisoners on their way to the gas chambers with a metal bar or bayonet. He is to be sentenced Monday and could receive the death penalty. Two days after their arrival in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Koury </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> marshal for the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> prosecutors interviewed him and <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> for four hours about <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s statement Both officers were listed as trial witnesses, though they were never called to testify. He said they also were asked by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the Israeli government not to mention the statement until after the case was resolved. <PERSON> Koury </PERSON> and <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> struck them as a man who knew his time was coming. `` I remember that when we landed in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, he turned and looked me square in the eyes and said, ` You've brought me here to be hanged,''' <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> said. `` He seemed a little apprehensive as we were handing him over to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities,'' <PERSON> Koury </PERSON> said. But the only emotion he showed, the marshal added, `` was when he made that statement: ` They do n't understand. It was war. I had to do it.'''
