<TEXT>
 A black businessman was hospitalized after he swallowed pieces of glass and part of a mouse at a restaurant he had been warned to avoid, he and his mother say. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> `` Sterling'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, 20, owner of a gift shop in a Holiday Inn, complained to <LOCATION> Anne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arundel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> police last week that he had received racist letters and an anonymous warning telling him not to eat in the hotel again. He lost consciousness after taking a bite of a crab dish Tuesday at the Holiday Inn restaurant. <PERSON> Maura </PERSON> <PERSON> Vonasek </PERSON>, a spokeswoman at <ORGANIZATION> Anne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arundel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> McCabe </PERSON> found scratches in <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s mouth and upper esophagus. More X-rays will be analyzed today, she said. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> was released Wednesday. A police report confirmed that pieces of a mouse and glass were found in food retrieved from the restaurant by <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Griselda </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, 44, of <LOCATION> Ellicott </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said her son had sent his crab dish back to the kitchen to be reheated. When the food was returned, <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> took a bite and they both heard a `` crunching sound,'' she said. He began to choke, stood up, grabbed his throat and vomited, she said. An official of the hotel said in a statement Wednesday he disputed <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s story. `` Our investigation of the matter and interviews with our employees gives us no reason whatsoever to believe that there is any truth to Mr. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s charges of either discrimination or contaminated food,'' <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorm </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Alexandria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the hotel and restaurant. `` No one on the property ever saw the contaminated food. The hotel staff did call the rescue squad when Mr. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> appeared to suffer a seizure in the restaurant. ... At this time we are not ruling out the possibility of a hoax,'' <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorm </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> last week filed a complaint with police over six letters filled with sexual and racist innuendo. He said he believed the anonymous letters came from a hotel employee. County police decided the letters did not constitute a threat under state law and referred the case to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> as a possible civil rights violation. City Councilman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Snowden </PERSON> demanded the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigate whether <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s civil rights were violated. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it would.
