<HEAD>Court Rules State Can't Execute Underage Killers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law prohibits the execution of murderers who were under the age of 17, the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled. The court's decision Wednesday prohibits the state from seeking a death sentence against <PERSON> Clinton </PERSON> <PERSON> Bankston </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who was indicted in <LOCATION> Clarke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> for two murders alleged to have been committed when he was 15 years old and for three slayings when he was 16. <PERSON> Bankston </PERSON> is charged with murder in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> in the April 1987 knife slayings of <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rachael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutton </PERSON>, two retired <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> professors; and the August 1987 hatchet slayings of <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON>, 59, her daughter, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON>, 22, and Mrs. <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, 63. His attorneys say <PERSON> Bankston </PERSON> will plead innocent by reason of insanity. At issue in Wednesday's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling was a statute dealing generally with capital cases which includes this provision: `` When it is shown that a person convicted of a capital offense without a recommendation for mercy had not reached his 17th birthday at the time of the commission of the offense, the punishment of such person shall not be death but shall be imprisonment for life.'' <PERSON> Bankston </PERSON>'s attorneys had filed a pre-trial motion to prevent the district attorney from seeking the death penalty, but it was rejected by the trial judge. The court said that the context of the statute did raise a question whether the Legislature intended only to block the the death penalty for those under 17 who were charged with capital crimes other than murder, such as rape, kidnapping and armed robbery. However, it said a 1977 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision effectively blocked the death penalty for all but murder cases.
