<HEAD>Christians and Shiites Clash, Two Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christian and Shiite Moslem militiamen battled with rockets and machine guns in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> today, and police said two people were killed and five wounded. Police said Shiite gunmen from various factions and Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> movement fought the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> militia for about an hour. A police spokesman said he did not know what sparked the clash, the second in four days between the Shiites and the Lebanese Forces. But it flared after the Syrian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> said it had thwarted a bizarre plot by the Lebanese Forces to assassinate <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>. The independent An-Nahar daily quoted an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> official as charging that the Christians had assigned a maid working at <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s home to assassinate him with an `` explosives-rigged jacket.'' An Amal official contacted by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> said the An-Nahar report was true. He refused to disclose the woman's whereabouts or say whether she had voluntarily informed Amal of the alleged plot. The Lebanese Forces declined comment. <PERSON> Berri </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s main ally in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The Lebanese Forces, led by <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Geagea </PERSON>, is at odds with <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, the main power broker in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. A strike called by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION> was partially observed today, reflecting disunity among workers on how to combat a severe economic crisis. Representatives of the 300,000-member confederation toured <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sectors and other cities trying to muster support for the strike. The unions seek a 300 percent pay raise. They rejected the government's offer of a 75 percent increase. The Lebanese economy, once the most flourishing in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, has been torn by 13 years of civil war. Inflation is rampant, unemployment growing and the Lebanese pound has collapsed. A police spokesman, who can not be named under standing regulations, said about 50 percent of Moslem and Christian areas were closed. Some schools, restaurants, movie theaters, gasoline stations and other businesses stayed open in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Union officials led supporters in two demonstrations urging the government to respond to their demands. `` We are hungry, we want to eat,'' the estimated 3,000 demonstrators chanted.
