<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> today proposed including blacks in the electoral college that chooses the president and possibly in the Cabinet. In a major speech to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> stopped far short of proposing full black voting rights or abolition of apartheid legislation. But he said his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> would stick to its widely criticized program of slow-paced reforms despite claims from the increasingly powerful far right that most of the 5 million whites oppose even modest concessions to the black majority. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s proposal to include blacks on the electoral college would, if implemented, mark the first time that blacks had a direct voice in the selection of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s president. He gave no details about how much strength blacks might be given on the college. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> also suggested that the Cabinet might be opened to people not serving in Parliament. This would clear the way for participation by blacks, who are excluded from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s initiatives appeared unlikely to ease international pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for an end to apartheid, which establishes racially segregated residential areas, health services and schools and deprives the 26 million blacks of a vote in national affairs. But domestically, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s message seemed to be that his government would not be intimidated by the success of the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in three recent parliamentary by-elections. `` I appeal to everyone to remain calm, to restore balance and to recognize each other's rights,'' he said. `` If we wish to live together peacefully in this beautiful land, the time has come to reflect on what unites us instead of emphasizing that which divides us.'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> reiterated his government's longstanding proposal for creating a national advisory council on which he and his top Cabinet ministers would negotiate with black leaders on drafting a new constitution that would bring blacks into the central government. `` We are not committed to the name, the form, the composition or the functions of such a body,'' he said. `` We are committed to the concept of a forum for deliberation.'' Most prominent black leaders have rejected <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s overtures to participate in the national council. They say the government first must free imprisoned black nationalist leaders like <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and lift restrictions on major anti-apartheid organizations. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> became <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s prime minister in 1978. That postition was abolished in 1984 with the adoption of a new constitution, and he was installed as president. In his speech, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> proposed that the office of prime minister be revived to handle day-to-day governmment affairs so the president could be freed to concentrate on major policy matters and ceremonial duties. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said political progress in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would be impeded by continued foreign pressure from the `` international brotherhood of persecutors.'' He also chided anti-apartheid clergymen, such as Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, for their increasingly vocal opposition to the government and their continuing calls for punitive sanctions. `` They take the lead in isolating the republic in economic and other fields, without caring in the least about the detrimental results,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. `` They accordingly play into the hands of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>. The outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is the major guerrilla movement fighting the government. The president said only a small fraction of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s Christians supported the anti-apartheid stance of <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> and other clergymen affiliated with the South African Council of Churches
