<HEAD>Kennedy Assassination `Polka Dot Dress' Story Was Lie, Witness
Said</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd-4th grafs, `Meanwhile, a ...,' with 2 grafs to
change reference to former prosecutor, CORRECT that Compton
interviewed by telephone from Washington home.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newly released police files reveal that the young woman who reported a `` girl in a polka dot dress'' running from the scene of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s assassination admitted two weeks later that she had lied. `` You know, I thought I was supposed to see more _ more than I did,'' the woman, <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>, says in microfilmed documents in the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that could lay to rest 20 years of controversy over the report. Meanwhile, a former prosecutor said he is certain no photographs or investigative matter important to the investigation of the June 5, 1968, assassination were purposely destroyed by police. `` There just was n't any reason for anyone to just deliberately destroy something that had any significance,'' the former prosecutor, now Judge <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Compton </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> 2nd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday by telephone from a home he has in <LOCATION> Lopez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash </LOCATION>. The files, opened at the state archives on Tuesday, contain a certificate that shows 2,410 police photographs were burned on Aug. 21, 1968. Chief archivist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> speculated the photos may have duplicated others still in evidence. But he said the files contain no such statement. A large portion of the documents deals with <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>, a college student who reported that she had confronted the woman on the night of <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s shooting at the Ambassador Hotel in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The files showed that Miss <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> first told her story to officers at 4 a.m. June 5 at police headquarters in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. She was one of hundreds of witnesses interviewed. Miss <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON>, who said she was chairman of the Youth for <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> chapter in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, said she came to the hotel that night to hear <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> speak but left the Embassy ballroom because it was too crowded. She recalled being seated on a step outside when `` I thought it was a backfire of a car. ... I thought I heard six shots, six backfires. `` About half a minute later this girl comes tearing down the stairs saying _ she said, ` We shot him We shot him.' And I said, ` Who did you shoot?' And she said, ` Senator <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.''' She said she had seen the same girl earlier in the evening and she was clad in a white voile dress with dark polka dots. She stood by her story for a time and even went with police to the Ambassador Hotel for a reenactment of her actions, the file showed. But on June 20, 1968, when she was reinterviewed by police after failing a lie detector test, she declared, `` The whole thing was a lie.'' She suggested that she and other witnesses who told police about the polka dot dress had created the story while waiting to be interviewed by police. She blamed the pressures and excitement of the event for her actions. And she indicated she almost began to believe her own fabrication. `` I do n't know why I said it. ... It just fitted. ... I really thought there was something behind it. I was conned,'' she said. The following day, June 21, police canceled an all-points bulletin for a woman in a white polka dot dress. However, the story did not die, and triggered years of controversy over whether <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>, the man convicted of killing <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, had acted alone.
