<HEAD>Foreign Press Comments on Outcome of New York Primaries</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> bureaus on how the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is what some newspapers and political commentators around the world had to say Thursday about the outcome of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Democratic primaries:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BRITAIN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ The Guardian of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -LRB- liberal -RRB-: `` It was the dirtiest, most dangerous race so far: and some of the details of the result are concomitantly disheartening The blacks of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> voted for <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The Jews -LRB- after particularly unpleasant broadsides from Mayor <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> -RRB- voted against him. There's a clear racial divide in the final primary accounting, with too much potential for bitterness left behind. Cheerfully, however, the winner and runner-up were in action yesterday stressing harmony and unity. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> have the opportunity to make something good out of something bad; and they see the need.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Vittorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Zucconi </PERSON> writing in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Repubblica </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> -LRB- left-leaning -RRB-: `` The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> of racial grudges, ... of too much money and too much misery, accomplished with brutality, perhaps with honesty, that which the rest of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> had not yet dared to do: it told <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and the black population that their challenge to the sky can not be accomplished `` The black Icarus of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> politics saw his wings melt when he got too close to the sun of victory. He will keep on flying, he might even score some victories in the remaining 50 days of primaries before <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> ... but the duel for the conquest of the White House seems a private affair between <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pasolini </PERSON> <PERSON> Zanelli </PERSON> in Il Giornale of <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> -LRB- conservative -RRB-: `` The anti-Jackson pact, upheld by nobody and actually denied by everybody, is already operative: the ` establishment' within the Democratic party has closed ranks behind <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.
