<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> today signed into law a bill that will make <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> `` the nation's laboratory'' in ensuring that health insurance is available to all residents by 1992. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who has cited the measure in his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, said the first-in-the-nation law will `` erase the uncertainty too many people face when they or a loved one becomes ill but lack the means to pay for the cure.'' In written remarks for an elaborate Statehouse signing ceremony, the governor said, `` We have good reason to rejoice today, as we again become the nation's laboratory.'' The proposal makes <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> `` the nation's pathfinder blazing a trail that leads to affordable quality health care for every man, woman and child.'' `` We have made a start here at home,'' he said. `` Now we must make it work. And then we must carry the message of health care for all across the country so that the other 49 states join us.'' Only <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, which has a federal exemption allowing it to mandate employer health coverage, currently has anything comparable to the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law. However, the new legislation, which <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> aides say has generated inquiries from more than 20 states, goes beyond <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s approach by offering health security both to working and non-working residents The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> proposal to make health insurance available to all by 1992 will cost the state $ 645.2 million over the next five years, according to figures released Wednesday by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The bill, the outcome of a nine-month legislative struggle, comes two years after <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> voters endorsed a non-binding referendum by a 2-1 margin urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to `` enact a national health care program -LRB- that -RRB- ... is universal in coverage.'' The thrust of the bill is to provide coverage to an estimated 600,000 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> residents under age 65 currently without health insurance _ about one out of every 10 people in the commonwealth. The plan is to do this in stages and through a variety of approaches _ from extending Medicaid benefits for disabled adults and children to state-brokered pooled insurance for small businesses and individuals. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> health policy adviser <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON> said she hopes the coverage will begin operations July 1, the start of the fiscal year. The plan passed the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> last week by narrow margins blamed on the deletion of some special interest amendments and lingering doubts about how much the law will cost. Although fully prepared to sign the law, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as late as Tuesday was telling reporters he did n't know the bill's ultimate cost. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> acknowledged Wednesday that there had been `` some confusion'' about health care costs. `` Sorry I did n't have the information yesterday. But I'm not a technocrat, I'm a leader,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said, joking about his national image as a dispassionate, hands-on manager. On Tuesday, the governor swept to victory in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s primary, solidifying his chances of becoming the party's nominee in next fall's presidential election. Even the chief drafters of the bill, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> and Means committees, were unable to agree on the measure's cost. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> placed the state's cost at about $ 550 million and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> estimated it as high as $ 1.2 billion. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> presented figures Wednesday showing the state's share of the plan would rise from $ 34.5 million this fiscal year to $ 195.4 million in fiscal 1991. The state's share is expected to drop to $ 162.7 million in fiscal 1992, according to the governor's figures. But <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON> said state costs beyond fiscal 1989 are hard to estimate because they will depend on how many employers decide to offer health plans as a result of the law.
