<HEAD>McMartin Mass Molestation Trial Enters Second Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The McMartin Preschool molestation trial started 368 days, 42 witnesses and $ 8 million ago, and attorneys say it is likely to last at least a year more. And that does n't include the 18-month preliminary hearing. `` Welcome to the year No. 2 of our trial,'' <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pounders </PERSON> said Wednesday. The judge and attorneys then spent an hour renumbering photographic evidence. Since jury selection started April 20, 1987, there have been 32,134 pages of transcript logged in Pounders' courtroom. Leap year added an extra day. The prosecution, taking testimony from its 42nd witness, is expected to rest its case late this summer. The defense has said it hopes to take less than a year to present its side. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON>, 29, and his mother, <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON>, 61, are charged jointly with one count of conspiracy and separately with 99 counts of molestation between them. The charges center on 14 children who were under their care at the <ORGANIZATION> McMartin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pre-School </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. Charges against five other teachers were dropped in 1986. In court, there have been allegations of satanic rituals, animal butchery, perjury, suppression of evidence and coaching of witnesses. One witness was jailed for failing to show up to testify, and another committed suicide the day he was to testify. Mrs. <PERSON> Buckey </PERSON> is free on bail but her son remains in custody, his bail set at $ 3 million. <PERSON> Pounders </PERSON> has been praised for his control of the trial so far. `` I think this judge has made a difference as far as recognizing and understanding the needs of the victims,'' said Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Lael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>. Six children testified during the first year of the trial. Defense attorneys claim many of their answers were coached. A 13-year-old was asked Wednesday whether the `` secret room'' where he said he was molested was actually a classroom. `` I'm leaving open the possibility, but I do n't remember it being a place where children are taught,'' the child answered. `` The kids appear to have been so prepped for trial, their testimony has been weakened,'' said attorney Dean Gits. `` There is little or no spontaneity.'' Seven children have yet to testify. The parents of the 14th alleged victim have refused to let their child take the stand.
