<FIRST>u a PM-DeepPockets     04-21 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deep Pockets,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>California High Court Says Limit on Damages Doesn't Apply to
Pending Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> dealt a multimillion-dollar setback to businesses and insurers today, ruling that the 1986 `` deep pockets'' initiative, which limited damages for pain and suffering, did not apply to cases pending when the measure passed. The 4-3 ruling was a victory for injury victims and their lawyers in cases where the harm had occurred but the lawsuits had not yet been completed by June 1986, when state voters approved Proposition 51 by a 62 percent majority. One class of cases particularly affected by today's ruling is asbestos lawsuits, many of which had been filed but not settled by June 1986. The court ruled that the initiative was constitutional, rejecting trial lawyers' claims that it discriminated unfairly against injury victims. But in the key portion of the ruling, the majority said the measure's new standards for determining non-economic damages applied only to injuries suffered after the initiative passed. The opinion by Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Arguelles </PERSON> cited `` the common-sense notion that it may be unfair to change the rules of the game in the middle of the contest.'' He also said new laws are generally presumed to apply only to future cases. Proposition 51, sponsored by businesses, insurers and local governments and opposed by trial lawyers, limits a defendant's share of non-economic damages _ pain, suffering and emotional distress _ to its percentage of the total fault Under the initiative, if a company that is 40 percent responsible for an injury, for example, has gone out of business by the time of suit, the victim can collect no more than 60 percent of the non-economic damages from the remaining defendants. Economic damages, such as medical costs and lost wages, are still covered by the longstanding `` deep pockets'' rule, under which one or all of the remaining defendants can be required to pay 100 percent of the costs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
