said the pictures were as much as 70 percent destroyed. Art restoration experts from <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Doerner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> rushed to the museum shortly after the 10 a.m. attack. The paintings will have to dry out for at least two months before the specialists can begin restoration work, said institute chemist <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Koller </PERSON>. The embittered pensioner was described by witnesses as a `` well-dressed gentleman'' who appeared to be just an ordinary museum visitor. A school group came upon him as he stood before the Duerer works, spraying the pictures with acid from a small champagne bottle. When a pupil cried out to stop him, the man calmly put away the bottle and turned himself in to museum officials, witnesses said.
