<HEAD>Leading Candidates Already Looking To Debate And Second Round</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, leading candidates in the first round of the presidential election Sunday, have piqued other hopefuls by arguing over terms of a one-on-one debate. As the official campaign entered its last two days Thursday, both the 71-year-old Socialist president and his 55-year-old conservative premier already were setting their sights on the May 8 runoff. That attitude did not sit well with former center-right Premier <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, 64, running third in the polls. `` The game is not over,'' said <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, adding he believed it was `` presumptuous, not to say curious'' for his competitors `` to set a date for a debate before the French people have decided.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> secretary-general, expressed the frustration of other candidates: `` The day before yesterday, yesterday and today, one question occupies the radio and television commentaries: the Mitterrand-Chirac debate between the first and second rounds.'' `` In other words, the first round is already over,'' said <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON>, whose party's candidate is <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoinie </PERSON>. French elections are run in two rounds. If, as expected, no candidate wins an absolute majority Sunday, the two top vote-getters face each other in a runoff. Under French law, no polls are allowed to be published in the week immediately preceding an election. The last polls showed <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> with comfortable lead at about 35 percent to 37 percent, followed by <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> with 22 percent to 24 percent. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> is third with about 17 percent and extreme right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> J