debate with the two men questioned separately by a panel of journalists. He wants a head-on confrontation. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> would prefer a less direct method. Analysts have called the presidential campaign lackluster and without any real discussion of the issues. Candidates have spoken about `` priorities'' and `` general orientations,'' but none of them has proposed any refreshing new ideas on how to tackle <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s economic and social problems <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> is seeking a second seven-year term in the <LOCATION> Elysee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who also served as premier from 1974-76 under President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing, is making his second run for the presidency. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, who replaced <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> as <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON>'s premier, is running for the first time. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> defeated <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> in the presidential election May 10, 1981. On Friday the two-week `` official campaign'' ends. During that period, each candidate has a specifically allotted amount of time on radio and television, and campaign meetings intensify. No political advertising is allowed on radio and television. On Saturday before the election, no campaigning is permitted. There are 38.3 million eligible voters.
