<HEAD>High Winds Blanket Beijing In Yellow Soil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The capital's worst dust storm in 36 years shut down <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s airport for several hours Thursday while pedestrians used surgical masks and scarves to protect themselves from the swirling yellow soil. The storms began April 2 and have continued intermittently since, sometimes limiting visibility to a few hundred yards and turning the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> sky, already gray from coal dust, to a chalky yellow. `` The last time <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> had such bad weather was 1952,'' said <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Tingfu </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meteorological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. High winds carrying tons of the soil called loess swirl into <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> every spring from the arid plateaus northwest of the capital. The storms have lessened in recent years due to anti-erosion measures, such as planting thousands of trees to form a `` green wall'' north of the city. But a lack of rain in <LOCATION> Inner </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gansu </LOCATION> province in northwestern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> aggravated the problem. The airport has been forced to close at least twice due to poor visibility. Cars, buildings and sidewalks were coated with fine dust, which also seeped into homes and offices.
