<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines urgent series</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said today he would suspend his campaign for the 1988 Democratic nomination and said he would do `` everything I can'' to elect a Democrat as the next president. In a graceful exit, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said he would technically remain a candidate to permit his delegates to attend the Democratic National Convention. But, he said in room crowded with supporters, `` I want no part of a stop <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or a stop <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> movement. The only man I want to stop is <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and we're going to stop <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> exited with a joke after a failed campaign that he said lasted 10 months and a million miles. `` I was doing great until I turned 40,'' the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s withdrawal leaves only front-runner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as active candidates for the Democratic nomination. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s campaign soared on Super Tuesday on March 8, when he scored primary victories in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> as well as his home state of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. But he was never able to capitalize on his Southern success when the campaign turned to the <LOCATION> Midwestern </LOCATION> and Northern states. When he got only 10 percent of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary vote on Tuesday, he decided to pull the plug. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> entered the race bidding to emerge as the type of moderate Southern candidate who could permit the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to capture Southern states in the fall election. <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> aside, virtually his only campaign success came in his native region. `` I lost this race and that is a disappointment,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said as his wife <PERSON> Tipper </PERSON> and other members of his family stood by his side. `` But some things matter to me more than winning _ helping my party, serving my country, knowing when to keep fighting and knowing when I've been licked.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> amassed 423 Democratic National Convention delegates during his campaign, according to a count by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. His decision to suspend rather than formally quit the campaign means they can attend the convention. Had he decided to withdraw, his delegates would have been divided between <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> spent his final hours as an active candidate trying to retire his huge debt. He went to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> on Wednesday for a $ 1,000-a-person fund-raiser to pay off some of the more than $ 1.5 million in debts the campaign has run up. Arriving in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> told reporters, `` I'm in the midst now of consulting with friends and supporters all over the country and asking for their advice on how we can best continue the cause for which I have been fighting.'' At the dinner, he did not say whether he would withdraw. But his speech had the sound of a last hurrah. `` I have learned from my opponents. I believe they have learned from me,'' he said. And he talked about turning attention to the general election. `` These next few weeks will be a time for unity and a time to look forward to the fall election,'' he said. The <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator praised both <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has `` reclaimed our party's passion for social justice'' and that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has `` shown a steady hand through a long and trying campaign.'' `` They are both good men and formidable candidates,'' he said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s strategy for winning the nomination was unusual and ultimately unsuccessful. He skipped the opening <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> caucuses, where his message as `` a raging moderate'' was not well-received. Then his campaign waffled on how much of an effort to make in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> _ where his issue positions found a receptive audience. By the time the money was poured into the <ORGANIZATION> Granite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, it was too late to affect the outcome and he finished fifth in a seven-man field. `` I always felt like, if anybody could pass up <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, he could,'' said <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Vick </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chairman. `` That he was an exception to the unwritten rule that you had to play in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> proclaimed that he would `` jump-start'' his campaign in his home region on March 8, the Super Tuesday when every Southern and border state but one held primaries. He did well that day, but so did <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, splintering the political benefits of the massive regional primary. After that, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> could not find a place to make a stand. He skipped <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, but then put a chunk of money into <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, where he once again finished behind the two front-runners. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was his last stand.
