<HEAD>More Health Workers' AIDS From `Unknown' Cause; Feds Say Risk
Still Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health care workers with AIDS are nearly twice as likely as other AIDS patients to have contracted the disease through `` undetermined'' means, federal health officials said Thursday. They added, however, that the occupational risk to such workers remains small. The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> reported that 2,586 health care workers are known to be among the more than 50,000 Americans who have contracted AIDS. Health care workers make up 5.4 percent of the known <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> AIDS patients and also make up a similar percentage of the population at large _ 5.7 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. But while only 2.8 percent of the nation's other AIDS patients are classified as having gotten the disease in an `` undetermined'' manner, nearly twice as many of the health care workers with AIDS fall into no known risk group _ 5.3 percent, or 135 in all. Reasons for the higher number of `` undetermined'' cases among health care workers are unknown, the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. Those reasons could include failure to disclose homosexual behavior, drug abuse or other risk factors, `` the occupational risk of -LRB- AIDS -RRB- infection as a result of blood exposure, or both.'' The disease most often strikes homosexual men and injectible drug abusers, and also is spread less frequently through heterosexual contact or blood transfusions. Failure to disclose behavior which might have put them at risk is something researchers consider when looking at `` all AIDS patients with undetermined risk ... both health care workers and non-health care workers,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamberland </PERSON>, a CDC AIDS specialist. `` Or, we may be seeing some occupational transmission in the health care setting,'' she said. `` It's difficult to establish with certainty how transmission occurred.'' Most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health care workers who have AIDS were infected outside their job, but `` a small number of health-care workers have been infected ... through occupational exposures,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted in its weekly report. More than a dozen health care workers are documented to have become infected with the virus that causes AIDS as a result of their work _ usually by accidentally being pricked by a contaminated needle. One health care worker is known to have gone on to develop the deadly disease itself after he was infected in such a manner. Scientific studies have shown that the chance of being infected after a needle-stick exposure to blood from infected patients is less than 1 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. `` That data has not changed at all -LRB- in continuing studies -RRB-,'' Ms. <PERSON> Chamberland </PERSON> said. `` The risk is still regarded as low, and it's most closely associated with inoculation with -LRB- tainted -RRB- blood, either in a needle-stick or in a cut with a sharp object. The number of cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is 59,491, including 33,280 cases in which the person has died, according to statistics this week from the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>.
