<HEAD>House Armed Services Chairman Says US May Have Overreacted</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` may have shot ourselves in the foot'' by overreacting with this week's military attacks on Iranian oil platforms and ships in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said in remarks released Thursday. `` There is good reason to suspect that the mines that prompted Monday's retaliation were not laid by <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> authorities, but by some Iranian radicals looking to start a fight,'' the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Democrat said. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> admitted that `` I can not prove this. No one at this time can prove who ordered the laying the of the mines _ or why.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>'s analysis was contained in a speech he will deliver Friday morning to the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Forum, a private group. A text of the speech was released Thursday evening. White House spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlow </PERSON>, asked for comment, said, `` I do n't usually engage in debates over speeches.'' At the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, officials said there would be no comment until they had read <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>'s speech. `` We may have shot ourselves in the foot,'' said <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>. `` Our restrained policy in the gulf worked superbly until now. We had shown sufficient force to convince <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to back off, without reacting so bloodily as to generate the ` martyrs' that the -LRB- Iranian -RRB- radicals use to inflame public passions.'' <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> forces on Monday destroyed two Iranian oil platforms in the southern <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> after a mine believed laid by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was struck by the frigate USS <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> on April 14. Ten sailors were injured and the ship suffered hull damage. After the platforms were destroyed, Iranian ships and planes attacked <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> forces and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> responded by sinking or damaging six Iranian ships. The action won wide praise and support on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, both from Republicans and Democrats. <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> had not commented, but he previously been a supporter of administration gulf policy. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, after the fighting, said, `` We've taken this action to make certain the Iranians have no illusions about the cost of irresponsible behavior. We aim to deter further Iranian aggression, not provoke it.'' But <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said more U.S.-Iran confrontations may lie ahead. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has been escorting 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships had previously destroyed Iranian oil platforms last Oct. 19 in retaliation for Iranian mine-laying efforts. Those strikes came after an Iranian ship, the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> Ajar, was caught by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> while laying mines. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said Monday that mines in the area where the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was damaged `` were from the same series of those found on the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> Ajar, leaving no doubt the mines were sown by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> asserted that the regime of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> `` re-evaluated its <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> policy in January'' and decided not to confront the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> any more. `` There is good reason to suspect that some irate -LRB- Iranian -RRB- radicals decided to light a fire in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It would not take more than a handful of Revolutionary Guards to drop some mines in the gulf sea lanes,'' he said. `` They could expect that if an American ship hit one, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would retaliate and they could return to the glorious confrontational days of yore.'' `` If this theory is correct, the radicals have won,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. `` With this week's shoot-up in the gulf, the regime's policy of declaring victory and then turning its back on the gulf has failed. It can not ignore the American presence now.''
