<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> signed an agreement on mutual cooperation Thursday, formalizing ties established during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. The memorandum was signed simultaneously in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. Describing the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as `` the friendliest <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has ever known,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said the five-year agreement formalized ad hoc arrangements developed in the past few years. The memorandum formalizes the two nations' consultative groups, which meet periodically to discuss joint military and security assistance as well as economic development issues. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON>, who attended the signing ceremony in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, hinted at disagreements between <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government over current <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> peace efforts. `` Peace is as vital for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security as military and economic strength and we will continue to work with all the states in this region to achieve that objective,'' he said. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> opposes a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> initiative to convene an international peace conference and speed up negotiations leading to <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> self-rule, and, later, a permanent peace settlement. Relations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> drew close after the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war, when <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> became <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s major supplier of arms after other Western arms-producing countries refused to sell weapons to the Jewish state. In 1973, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> airlifted weapons and ammunition to a beleaguered <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> caught off guard when <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> lauched a surprise attack. Under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, civilian and military aid to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has grown to $ 3 billion and ties have grown closer. In 1981, the two countries signed a secret agreement on strategic cooperation which included provisions for military trade and joint planning. In 1985, an economic accord was signed lifting trade barriers between the two countries. In recent years, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has become a port of call for ships of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mediterranean fleet and has provided the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with land for a transmitter to beam <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION> broadcasts to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
