 Mexican novelist <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuentes </PERSON>, a developer of the Latin American writing style known as `` Magic Realism,'' on Thursday received the 1987 Miguel de Cervantes Prize for Literature. King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> and Queen <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> presented the prize at the university in this town outside <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Fuentes </PERSON>' `` exemplary work of creation and thought'' and `` his insistent vocation to narrate our present problems and delve into our promising futures.'' In November, a jury of writers and critics named <PERSON> Fuentes </PERSON> the 1987 recipient of the award, considered the Spanish-language equivalent of the Nobel Prize. In his acceptance speech, <PERSON> Fuentes </PERSON>, 59, author of `` The Death of <PERSON> Artemio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>'' -LRB- 1964 -RRB- and `` Terra Nostra'' -LRB- 1975 -RRB-, emphasized the importance of the Spanish language. `` It has been converted into a universal language, spoken, written, read, sung, thought and sounded by a growing number of people,'' he said. `` It is the strongest link in our commmunity.. and the language of imagination, love and justice _ not of empire.'' The prize is named for the author of `` <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Quixote </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervantes </PERSON> and amounts to the equivalent of $ 90,000.
