<HEAD>President Proposes Expanded Black Political Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said Thursday he would push for black participation in Cabinet-level policymaking and on the electoral college that selects the president. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> aides called the proposals, outlined in a speech to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, a major reform initiative, but they fell far short of black demands for full voting rights and abolition of apartheid legislation. The increasingly powerful, far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which opposes any concessions to blacks, assailed the speech. The Conservatives' <PERSON> Koos </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Merwe </PERSON> urged <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to resign and said the president's `` colossal lack of political credibility'' had made him an object of ridicule among his fellow Afrikaners. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s proposals appeared unlikely to ease international pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for an end to apartheid, which establishes racially segregated neighborhoods, hospitals and schools, gives the 5 million whites almost total political control and deprives the 26 million blacks of a vote in national affairs. But domestically, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s message was that his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> would not back off from slow-paced reform despite the Conservatives' victories in three recent parliamentary by-elections. `` If the white people do not wish to follow my way, it is their responsibility,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. `` If they follow the way of confrontation, it is their problem.'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s proposal to include blacks in the electoral college would, if implemented, mark the first time that blacks had a direct voice in the selection of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s president. He gave no details about how many seats blacks might have in the college, which has 88 members, 50 of them from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> suggested that a Cabinet-level `` executive authority'' be opened to people not serving in Parliament. This would clear the way for participation in policymaking by blacks, who are excluded from <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> also reiterated his longstanding proposal for creation of a national advisory council on which he and top Cabinet ministers would negotiate with black leaders on drafting of a new constitution that would bring blacks into the central government. `` We are not committed to the name, the form, the composition or the functions of such a body,'' he said. `` We are committed to the concept of a forum for deliberation.'' He said black leaders were unhappy with the term `` national council'' and suggested that their reluctance might be overcome by calling the forum `` the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indaba </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Indaba </LOCATION> is a Zulu word for a tribal assembly. Most prominent black leaders have rejected overtures to participate in the council, saying the government first must free imprisoned black nationalist leaders such as <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> and lift restrictions on major anti-apartheid organizations. <PERSON> Mangosuthu </PERSON> <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON>, chief minister of the <ORGANIZATION> KwaZulu </ORGANIZATION> homeland and a leading black moderate, said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s electoral college proposal amounted to `` tokenism'' because the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> `` does not admit to the existence of a black majority in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' But <PERSON> Buthelezi </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> for finding the courage to confront the far right. `` Now that he has taken a first tentative step to defy the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ... let him be bold and be explicit about how far he is prepared to go.'' <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON>, veteran <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member for the liberal <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, criticized <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> for not setting a timetable for his proposals. She said he was evading the question of black participation in Parliament. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> became prime minister in 1978. That postition was abolished in 1984 with the adoption of a new consititution, and he was installed as president. In his speech, <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> proposed that the office of prime minister be revived to handle day-to-day government affairs while the president concentrates on major policy matters and ceremonial duties. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said political progress in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> would be impeded by continued pressure from the `` international brotherhood of persecutors.'' He stressed that white South Africans' `` values and principles ... may under no circumstances be compromised.'' `` Should they collapse, then <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will collapse,'' he said. He chided anti-apartheid clergymen, such as Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, for their increasingly vocal opposition to the government and their calls for punitive sanctions. He said they play into the hands of the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the major guerrilla movement fighting the government. The president said only a small fraction of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s Christians supported the anti-apartheid stance of <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> and his colleagues
