<HEAD>Japanese-American Expects Apology, No Reparations for Internment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Japanese-American living in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> said Thursday he expects to receive an apology for being interned in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> during World War II, but not to get reparations as approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Saiki </PERSON>, 68, a retired <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officer working in public relations in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, said reparations were justified because Japanese-Americans lost possessions and five years of their lives. `` I think we'll get the apology,'' <PERSON> Saiki </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. But he said he thought President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the bill that eventually emerges from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The chance that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would overturn a presidential veto was slim, he said, `` therefore the possiblity of getting the reparation is rather questionable.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a bill Wednesday to give an apology and $ 20,000 in tax-free payments to Japanese-Americans who were rounded up and placed in camps after the Japanese attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> on Dec. 7, 1941. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed a similar bill in September. The Japanese government had no official reaction to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> action because it was a domestic <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> issue, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Yoshifumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> told reporters. But <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> said he personally praised the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> action because he had been a consul general at the Japanese consulate in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and had worked on the issue. `` After many years, the justness and fairness are recovered through democracy,'' <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> said. `` This is the way of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> democracy.'' <PERSON> Saiki </PERSON> said he and his family were uprooted from their <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> home in 1942 like thousands of other Japanese-Americans who fell under suspicion after the attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. He had been about to graduate from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, but instead ended up in a camp in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> with his mother and two younger brothers. His father was sent to a separate camp for community leaders, he said. <PERSON> Saiki </PERSON> was inducted into the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in 1944 and was commissioned as an officer just as the war ended. His family was able to move to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> where they worked as farm laborers, living in the basement of an old house. After the war his family returned to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, again working as farm laborers. `` From the day they were evacuated in 1942, in 1947, five years later, they had n't gotten back to prewar status,'' <PERSON> Saiki </PERSON> said. `` They had lost everything they had acquired up to 1942. ... I very definitely feel it -LRB- reparations -RRB- is very justified.'' He said his own military career in counterintelligence brought him to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on four tours after the war, and he spent 10 years on military duty in this country. Then, after he retired as a lieutenant colonel in 1966, he returned here to work and has remained ever since. <PERSON> Saiki </PERSON> is a member of the board of the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, which has about 150 members. `` Some of us are not in such pressing need for money,'' he said, `` but there are others who are. Half the people have died, and every year the number is getting smaller. The people who deserved the money and who need it are gradually dying.'' Asked if he felt <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> had a role in the issue because its attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> led to the internment, he replied: `` It's an American problem. It's not because of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> that it happened.''
