<HEAD>CDC Study Says Many Cruise Illnesses Caused By Seafood Cocktail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Serious outbreaks of diarrhea aboard cruise ships have become rare, but the most frequent known culprit is a common delicacy: seafood cocktail, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> suvey. Of 45 outbreaks investigated from 1975 to 1985, the most frequently detected source was the seafood cocktails or salad, according to a study by the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> presented at a conference Wednesday in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. Two-thirds of all cruises during those years docked in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> ports. `` It's a real popular food on cruises, and seafood is one food which can be contaminated if it's not handled properly,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Addiss </PERSON>, medical epidemiologist and author of the report. Water was the second most common source of the outbreaks during that 10-year-period, but <PERSON> Addiss </PERSON> noted that structural changes in the ships' water systems have all but eliminated that problem. In 25 of the 45 cases, the cause could not be identified. Ship captains must radio to shore a day before they arrive at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> port and report the number of passengers complaining of diarrhea. It is labeled an outbreak if more than 3 percent of the passengers are affected.
