<FIRST>r w AM-ChildCare     04-21 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Opposes ABC Child Care Bill, But May Endorse
Alternative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration opposes a proposed $ 2.5 billion child care bill, but may endorse other ways of helping families with preschool children, Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said that while the administration does n't like the Act for Better Child Care -LRB- ABC -RRB-, another bill giving a child care tax credit to any taxpayer with preschoolers _ whether they are cared for at home or elsewhere _ meets a series of principles he outlined in testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on human resources. It is not yet clear whether the administration will propose its own tax credit or support other federal initiatives to make day care more affordable or available, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. Current tax law allows a credit for children cared for outside the home. `` It's a matter of debate and discussion within the administration right now,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill is backed by the Democratic leadership in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and scores of organizations representing children, women, labor, churches and medical personnel. It is sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Kildee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>., and Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION> Three-quarters of the $ 2.5 billion in <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> money would help pay the child care bills in families making up to 115 percent of a state's median income. The rest would go for training and salaries for child care workers, renovation of facilities and referral programs for parents. A national advisory panel would develop minimum federal child care standards. Conservatives including <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlafly </PERSON> complained Thursday that the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill is too expensive and cumbersome, promotes institutional care and discriminates against parents who stay at home with their children. And they said the income cutoff in the bill would let some families earning $ 40,000 get financial help. Another controversy centers on whether religious groups that provide child care would be eligible for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> grants. <PERSON> Kildee </PERSON> said he is working for changes to make sure they qualify for money, but the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said the bill as it stands violates the wall between church and state. `` This is one big new federal trough for churches,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, legislative counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION>. `` Too many of them want it and they're not willing to recognize the serious constitutional issues here.'' Another tax credit bill introduced by Rep. <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-La </LOCATION>., appears to meet the objections of both conservatives and civil libertarians It simply would give all families a credit of $ 150 to $ 400 per preschool child. `` It offers more assistance and more choice to more families with less cost to the government,'' <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON> told the subcommittee. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he personally favors the <PERSON> Holloway </PERSON> approach even though some families might use the money for purposes other than child care. He said the tax credit meets the administration criteria of strengthening the family, treating stay-at-home mothers fairly, not promoting any particular type of care, targeting funds to those most in need and helping people without setting up a new bureauracracy. Reflecting statements submitted for the record by <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> and assistant <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Sydney </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said the federal government should not regulate day care centers, although `` I certainly see the need for some kind of standards so the public and individual families can have some security.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> have endorsed the gist of a middle-ground proposal sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, and Rep. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>. Their Child Care Services Improvement Act would give states $ 250 million in grant money for day care expansion and scholarships and $ 100 million to start risk pools to limit liability Another $ 25 million would be available to help home providers meet state licensing requirements.
