<TEXT>
 Heart surgeon <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> DeBakey </PERSON>, along with actors <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Randall </PERSON>, spoke out on Thursday for continued use of animals in medical research, arguing that animals will play a major role in the search for a cure for AIDS and heart disease. <PERSON> DeBakey </PERSON>, who was first to perform a successful coronary bypass and the first to successfully use a partial artificial heart, recalled that when he was in medical school more than 30 years ago, `` not a single cardiovascular disease could be treated effectively.'' `` Now, we have patients who are living reasonably normal lives for 20 or 25 years after surgery,'' <PERSON> DeBakey </PERSON> said. `` The only means by which we can do these things is in working in labs with animals.'' <PERSON> DeBakey </PERSON> and the others said they chose this week to state their case to counter <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Week </ORGANIZATION> protests by animal rights activists who oppose all use of animals in medical research. Barring that, some are pushing for stricter controls on the care and feeding of laboratory animals. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Starzl </PERSON>, a transplant surgeon at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>, said he, like the animal rights activists, abhors cruelty to animals and said any incidents of poor treatment of research animals are the exceptions rather than the rule. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> began the news conference by saying he has worked with the <ORGANIZATION> Myasthenia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for about 20 years. Although great strides have been made in treating the disease, a cur