<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tennis star <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> on Thursday won a major battle in his fight to play for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic team this summer when a skeptical <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee voted to give the Czech native immediate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship. The measure, which even proponents had given little chance of passage earlier this year, was approved without opposition and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Subcommittee approval likely will lead to easy passage by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn., a member of the panel and chief sponsor of the bill But the legslation still would face serious obstacles in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, is wary of Olympic exemptions The subcommittee voted to speed up the citizenship of <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> and two lesser-known Olympic hopefuls by removing the five-year waiting period permanent residents are required to go through. Rep. <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON>, D-Ky., the panel's chairman who regularly opposes Olympic bills, said he was `` sympathetic'' to arguments that preventing <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> from participating in the Olympics would be a `` true hardship'' because an athlete's prime years are limited <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON> said, however, that he was concerned by the testimony of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> officials who said citizenship would not automatically make <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> eligible for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team. `` We're in kind of a Catch-22 in a way that we have to take action without actual assurance that these people would compete despite their world-class caliber,'' <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON>'s consideration of the <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> measure reflects a change of attitude on Olympic citizenship bills. Last year, <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON> outlined a new rule of his Judiciary subcommittee on immigration, refugees and international law that viewed private immigration bills as an `` extraordinary remedy available only to assist aliens with unusual problems and where extreme hardship ... can be demonstrated.'' It noted that the panel would be `` extremely reluctant'' to consider bills for Olympic athletes. But <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> supporters led by <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> redoubled their efforts this year when <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, pushed through a special citizenship bill for a 21-year-old Canadian-born swimmer living in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON> said one of his concerns has been that the few athletes who won citizenship from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in past years have been unsuccessful in the international games. `` The one ski guy is still completing the course,'' <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON> said. But this year, for the first time, the subcommittee called in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic Committee officials who vouched for the quality of <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON>, along with <PERSON> Jens-Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Burntd </PERSON>, an East German swimmer who defected in 1985 and is living in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Gagik </PERSON> <PERSON> Barseghian </PERSON>, an Armenian wrestler who moved to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in 1986. The Olympics, which will be held Sept. 17-Oct. 2 in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, will include tennis as full sport for the first time since 1924 It was a trial sport in 1984. Modified Olympic rules will allow professional tennis players such as <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON>, the world's No. 1 ranked player, to compete. But <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, general counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said under <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> rules, a player first must represent his country in the Davis Cup before the Olympics. Federation rules also say <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON> needs a special waiver to play for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the Davis Cup since he previously has represented his native <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> in those games. The next Davis Cup is in July. `` They need the citizenship to argue on behalf of the waivers and we create the citizenship without the knowledge that these people will ever compete,'' <PERSON> Mazzoli </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> rejected criticism that lawmakers are favoring athletes such as <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON>, pointing to dozens of other special immigration bills approved for non-athletes. `` We are put in the position of looking like we are taking care of a few famous people, when what we're trying to do is balance one arbitrary rule against another arbitrary rule,'' he said. <PERSON> Lendl </PERSON>, 28, moved to <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> in 1981 and received his permanent resident status last year. Immigration law requires a five-year waiting period before a permanent resident can become a citizen.
