<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American troops guarding <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facilities in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> detected two groups of intruders his week and in one case drew gunfire, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman, said the latest incidents occurred on Tuesday and Wednesday nights near bases on the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> end of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. They followed two other incidents last week, in which one Marine was killed accidentally and a group of Marines fired on what they described as a group of 40 to 50 armed intruders. The incident Tuesday, the more serious of the two this week, occurred around midnight near an ammunition storage depot next to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Station-Panama, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. An Army sentry stationed there spotted three men who had crossed `` inside the perimeter of the site,'' he said. `` The guard's report indicated that the intruders wore berets and carried small arms and bags. An intruder fired shots at the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- guard. The guard returned the fire, remained at the sentry post and requested assistance. `` The intruder then fired again. A Marine quick-reaction force -LRB- of 12 men -RRB- was sent to reinforce and assist in the search of the area. A security sweep of the area was completed during darkness with negative results, but the investigation continues. There were no casualties during the incident,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> added. The second incident occurred around 8 p.m. Wednesday when three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sentries manning an observation post to the west of <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> detec