<HEAD>Dukakis Signs Universal Health Care Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said `` today we make history'' Thursday as he signed into law <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' first-in-the-nation proposal to provide health insurance to all residents by 1992 `` What we do here today can and must be done all over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' the Democratic presidential front-runner told an estimated 2,000 supporters crowded onto the Statehouse steps for the signing ceremony. `` Today marks the day when working families, the unemployed, the disabled, students and children with special needs do n't go sick because they ca n't afford to stay well. Those days in the commonwealth are over,'' he said as the crowd applauded. `` From now on, when the sick land at the doorstep of our health care system, the first question of them will be: ` Where does it hurt?' Not, ` How will you pay?''' Only <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, which has an exemption to federal law allowing it to require employer health coverage, has anything comparable to the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law. However, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> legislation, which <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> aides say has generated inquiries from more than 20 states, goes beyond <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s approach by offering health security both to working and non-working residents. In his speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did n't specifically mention whether he would seek similar federal legislation if he became president, but he did say: `` Today we make history. But there is more history to be made.'' `` As an American, I do n't want my country to stand alone with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> as the only two industrialized nations that do not provide basic health security for their citizens.'' The bill was the outcome of a nine-month legislative struggle and comes two years after <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> voters endorsed a non-binding referendum by a 2-to-1 margin urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to `` enact a national health care program ... universal in coverage.'' The narrowly passed the legislature last week. `` The doubters said a lot of things,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` And they were wrong.'' But doubters remain. Dr. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> U. </PERSON> <PERSON> Himmelstein </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and spokesman for Physicians for a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> called the health care bill a first step but said it was `` a Band-Aid approach when major surgery is needed.'' And House Minority Leader <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, a Republican, described the bill as `` short-term gain and long-term pain. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has managed to pick up some short-term political gain at the expense of long-term fiscal pain for the commonwealth.'' On Wednesday, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> estimated that the law's cost to taxpayers would be $ 645.2 million through fiscal 1992, minus about $ 22.5 million in projected cost-cutting in Medicaid. Other estimates put the cost to the state government in the next four years as high as $ 1.2 billion. The thrust of the law is to provide coverage to about 600,000 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> residents under age 65 currently without health insurance, roughly one of every 10 people in the commonwealth. This would be done in stages and through a variety of approaches, from extending Medicaid benefits for disabled adults and children to state-brokered, pooled insurance for small businesses and individuals. By 1992, all employers with more than five full-time employees must offer health insurance coverage or pay an unemployment surcharge to help the state provide this coverage to the uninsured.
