<HEAD>Adams Seeks Triggering Of War Powers Act In Persian Gulf Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., seeking to force a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate on the issue of `` war and peace'' in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, said Thursday he will introduce legislation to authorize the continued presence of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces in the gulf and set rules for their use <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said he will also seek congressional action to trigger the War Powers Act, which requires the removal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces from hostile areas within 60 days unless their continued presence is specifically approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` In the last year we have deployed dozens of American ships in the gulf,'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said. `` We have spent tens of millions of dollars. We have asked Americans to sacrifice their lives. `` But <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has never authorized the deployment, never appropriated any money, never clearly stated its support for the policy that is being followed.'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said a number of individual senators have offered the administration specific suggestions on changes or modifications in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> policy and some are being considered seriously. But he said that is not enough. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as an institution has to give some guidance to the administration,'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said. `` ... <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has a right and a responsibility to debate the policy being followed by the administration as well as the right to consider alternatives. `` Only by engaging in a full and frank debate, only by working with our colleagues and having the administration work with us, can we refine our approach to the problem and strengthen our national commitment to solve it,'' he said. The War Powers Act is a post-Vietnam attempt to apply a congressional brake to unilateral presidential decisions to expose <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces to possible hostilities. It has been resisted by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as an encroachment on the president's authority as the nation's military commander in chief <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said he realizes an attempt to invoke it will be challenged but said the act should be implemented because it remains `` the law of the land.'' `` I am not trying to force the withdrawal of American forces from the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said. `` We have a right to be there and a mission to perform there.'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said he is only seeking to protect the constitutional right of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to be involved in decisions to deploy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces into areas of hostility.
