<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> gave up his 1988 White House bid Thursday, offering the strong suggestion that he harbors hopes of a future campaign and moving to protect the delegates he has won so far. `` It hurts to have come so far and have fallen short,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> office room crowded with supporters. `` But there will be other days for me and for the causes that matter to us.'' The <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator ended the race deeply in debt after waging a long-shot campaign that challenged the traditional dominance of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>. It succeeded in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, where he won favor as a moderate, but fell flat elsewhere. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said he would technically remain a candidate to permit his delegates to attend the Democratic National Convention. In suspending his campaign, he delivered some of the most eloquent lines of his campaign, praising each of his opponents, excoriating Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and pledging support for the eventual nominee. `` I want no part of a stop <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or a stop <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> movement,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. `` The only man I want to stop is <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I will not be the Democratic nominee for president in 1988,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. `` The nominee is going to be <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> or <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. I'm going to do everything I can to help them do what I set out to do, and that is to put a Democrat in the White House.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> exited with a joke after a failed campaign that he said lasted 10 months and a million miles. `` I was doing great until I turned 40,'' he said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> amassed 423 Democratic National Convention delegates during his campaign, according to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> count. His decision to suspend his campaign rather than quit the race means the two remaining active candidates can not pick up delegates he has already won, but who have not yet been chosen. Under party rules, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> would have gained 34 of <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s delegates immediately, while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would have gotten 29 <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s decision to suspend his campaign denied <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> another 47 delegates he would have inherited in this manner. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said he spoke with both <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and that both were `` comfortable'' with his decision to hold onto the delegates. He said the move would protect <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders who backed him in states where delegates had not yet been chosen, naming <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> as an example. He said he planned no endorsement and repeated his oft-stated contention that he has `` no interest'' in the vice presidential nomination, though he left that door open. `` I'm not trying in any way to broker a convention that is not going to be brokered anyway,'' he said. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s withdrawal was assured by his dismal third place showing in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a 10 percent finish that capped six weeks of frustration for <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> since his six-state victories on Super Tuesday in the South. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> had become his last chance to get back into contention. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> is saddled with a debt of more than $ 1.5 million, run up in borrowing for his campaign in Super Tuesday states and after that in an effort to break through outside the South. His debt is the largest of the 1988 presidential candidates who have departed the race, although as a senator he is in a position to raise money to retire the debt. He spent the night before his announcement in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, raising money to repay the debt. Facing little support in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and an appeal not in sync with that state's left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> activists, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> challenged the assumption that candidates must do well in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s caucuses. He bypassed the state and blasted its process as a distortion, and concentrated on the South. But <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s campaign was marked by internal disorganization and division, and a tendency to postpone decisions. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> often made the decisions himself from the road. One result was that <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> spent nearly the maximum amount allowable in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> _ over $ 400,000 _ but did it late and without an accompanying commitment of time and campaign staff to campaign full force. The result was he was neither fully in nor fully out there, and finished fifth in a seven-way race. He broke through with wins in six states in the South. But then he went through the succession of Northern states, beginning with <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, largely an unknown figure and unable to make any progress.
