<HEAD>Judge: Jury To Decide Conspiracy Claim In Cancer-Liability Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Evidence in a closely watched cigarette liability case is sufficient for a jury to consider whether three cigarette manufacturers conspired to cover up the dangers of smoking, and the trial should continue, a judge said Thursday. `` The evidence presented ... permits the jury to find a tobacco industry conspiracy, vast in its scope, devious in its purpose and devastating in its results,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>. At the same time, <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> dismissed a claim that the three companies sued in the liability case _ <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ caused <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s lung cancer by not marketing a safer cigarette. The judge's comments came in a 33-page opinion requested by the cigarette makers, who asked for dismissal of the case and an end to the trial that began Feb. 1. The companies are being sued by Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Lakehurst </LOCATION>, whose wife died at age 58 in 1984 after smoking for 40 years. Attorneys for <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> completed their case two weeks ago, alleging that Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> was a victim of a campaign by the cigarette makers to undermine warnings about the dangers of smoking. In the opinion that was quite pointed at times, <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> said the jury should be allowed to consider the conspiracy and punitive claims in the case. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> said evidence indicated the companies conspired to conceal and misrepresent information on the dangers of smoking and to `` refute, undermine and neutralize information coming from the scientific and medical community.'' He said the evidence also indicated the companies tried to `` confuse and mislead the consuming public in an effort to encourage existing smokers to continue and new persons to commence smoking.'' `` The jury may reasonably conclude that defendants were members of and engaged in that conspiracy with full knowledge and disregard for the illness and death it would cause, and that Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> was merely one of its victims,'' the judge said. As for punitive damages, <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> said: `` If the jury accepts the plaintiff's version of the facts as to the conduct of the defendants, it is difficult to envision a more compelling case for an award of punitive damages.'' <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s attorneys said they were pleased with the opinion. `` The judge says we have a case for the jury,'' attorney <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said. `` If a case should be won, this is it,'' she said, adding that her side introduced as evidence secret internal cigarette company documents never before made public. They included memorandums that spoke of a public relations `` war'' against health-related charges involving cigarettes. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION>, took exception to the tone of <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>'s opinion. `` I do think there were flourishes there from the judge's pen that went beyond the plaintiff's evidence,'' he said. Wall also said he believed the heart of <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s case was gutted by <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>'s opinion. `` The conspiracy claim is very tenous at best,'' he said. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> dismissed a claim that the companies were liable for Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s death on the basis they knew how to design a safer cigarette but failed to. The judge said <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s attorneys could not prove Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> would have smoked the safer cigaratte had it been marketed. Ms. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said the dismissal of that claim, which the defense contended was the heart of the case, was not a critical blow. `` We thought it was an important theme, not so much for this case but for the broader implications in future cases,'' she said. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> also dismissed a claim that the companies failed to do enough research on the dangers of smoking. While there was ample evidence that the research was inadequate, the judge said, <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s attorneys did not prove that this directly harmed Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>. Another claim, that the companies failed to warn smokers of the dangers of cigarettes, was also dismissed against <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION>, but the judge said the jury will be able to consider that allegation in the case of <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> began smoking cigarettes made by <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> after 1966, when the federal government began requiring warnings on cigarette packs. However, she smoked cigarettes made by <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> prior to 1966 and there is evidence `` from which the jury could infer that, prior to 1966, ordinary consumers were not adequately informed of the health risks of smoking,'' he said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearney </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>, said the company was `` confident we will prevail on the basis of evidence that comes out during our presentation.''
