<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Streamlines Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new federal government with fewer departments and a drastically reduced staff was appointed Thursday in a move to tighten the belt on <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s bureaucracy The official <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the new 20-member government was appointed by President <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>. The changes, however, were proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leadership at a recent meeting. The previous 26-member government resigned Wednesday, one day after <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> rubber-stamped a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> decision to merge five ministries into two. In <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, changes in government are decided by the party leadership. <PERSON> Lubomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON> remains premier in the new government, which has six deputy premiers instead of ten. There had been some speculation that Strougal might be replaced. The new government now has ten ministries, three less than previously. `` Times were never easy for governments,'' <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON> said. `` But these are the most difficult times. `` We know what we want ... but at the same time we must count on many unexpected phenomena which we shall have to solve both in economic and social development as well as in internal and foreign policy, where more activity and initiative is needed on our part,'' <PERSON> Strougal </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> has adopted the rhetoric of reform over the past year, but has proceeded cautiously in making changes like those carried out in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>, who was replaced as party leader in December by <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON>, said each minister is to `` look critically at the area he is responsible for.'' The governments of the Czech and Slovak republics also were reorganized, reducing their ministries by four and three, respectively. The shuffle apparently is designed to streamline government bureaucracy and spur the country's economy. The Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said the staffs of the federal and <ORGANIZATION> republican </ORGANIZATION> governments are to be cut by about 30 percent. Rude Pravo said `` thousands of people'' would be fired through the reorganization of state administration. However, it said no one would be left without a job. `` The process must be aimed primarily at ensuring the growth of quality and performance of the managing aparatus and at a good and effective use of the released workers primarily in places and professions where manpower has been lacking so far,'' <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Rude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pravo </PERSON> as saying. Former deputy Premier <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerle </PERSON> now heads a newly created ministry of metallurgy, engineering and technology, which merges three separate ministries. The ministries of communication and transport were combined under <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Blazek </PERSON>, the former minister of transport. The only new member of the government, according to sources in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, is <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Calfa </PERSON>, minister without portfolio, who is in charge of government coordination.
