<HEAD>5,000 Workers Said to Protest Wages in Southeast Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 5,000 factory workers in southeast <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> rallied Thursday, chanting `` Solidarity, Solidarity!'' and demanding pay raises to offset recent price increases, an opposition spokeswoman said. Activist <PERSON> Ewa </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubema </PERSON> said the rally took place in front of management headquarters of the sprawling <LOCATION> Stalowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wola </LOCATION> heavy machinery plant, 95 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. It employs 18,000 people. <PERSON> Wieslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojtas </PERSON>, chairman of the factory chapter of the outlawed Solidarity trade union movement, read a speech listing workers' demands, including across-the-board pay raises of $ 50 a month, she said The average wage in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is about $ 90 a month. She said another demand was an end to harassment of union activists. The union threatened a strike at an undefined date if its demands are not met, she said. The union had called for the demonstration in leaflets distributed over the past two weeks, said Ms. <PERSON> Kubema </PERSON>. It began at 2 p.m., the end of the first shift, with a whistle from the factory's locomotive repair shop, she said. At that time, there were about 10,000 workers at the plant. After <PERSON> Wojtas </PERSON>' speech, she said, workers chanted `` Solidarity, Solidarity!'' and sang the national anthem, holding up their hands in V-for-victory signs. She said there were no arrests at the rally, but lawyer <PERSON> Wladyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Liwak </PERSON>, secretary of the Solidarity committee at the factory, was detained at his home. Solidarity was banned after the 1981 martial law crackdown in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, but local units continued to function clandestinely at many factories. In a shift of union strategy last year, new units were organized publicly, and dozens of them have unsuccessfully gone to court seeking legal registration under a 1982 labor law. Government price increases of 40 percent took effect this year, part of the government's program of economic reform. At the same time, workers in socialized enterprises received an automatic $ 15 monthly pay raise. Authorities expressed concern that factory managers, under worker pressure, will be too generous about awarding additional wage increases. They warned managers they could lose their jobs unless wage increases are merited by higher productivity.
