<HEAD>FCC Fines Two Dial-A-Porn Companies $1.2 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Retransmits a0842 to CORRECT cycle designation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> dial-a-porn operators were fined $ 600,000 each by the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday for transmitting obscene material across state lines and for not restricting access to their messages to children and non-consenting adults. `` Some so-called dial-a-porn providers are blatantly disregarding the law which required that access by minors be restricted pursuant to commission regulation,'' <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said in announcing the fines. `` We intend to enforce this law.'' The companies, <ORGANIZATION> Audio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intercambio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, were fined for interstate transmission of obscene material and failure to restrict such transmissions from minors and non-consenting adults. The maximum fine is $ 50,000 for each day of violation. `` The ultimate in sleeze deserves the ultimate ... penalty,'' <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quello </PERSON> said. `` They need to know we mean business.'' <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> common carrier bureau, said the $ 600,000 fines were based on the amount of money the companies made during the commission's monitoring process. In an 11-month period, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T received $ 5.5 million from calls made to one <ORGANIZATION> Audio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> line, <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said. Of that amount, <ORGANIZATION> Audio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> received $ 650,000, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Intercambio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> received $ 297,000 from its operation. The decision was the result of an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> investigation triggered by complaints alleging that unimpeded access to the sexually explicit messages resulted in the molestation of one 10-year-old girl and so disturbed a 16-year-old boy that he had to enter weekly psychiatric theraphy. The companies have 30 days to pay or seek reduction of the fines. Current FCC regulations direct the dial-a-porn companies to restrict their messages through access codes, message scrambling or use of credit card numbers. Upon being notified last December of the complaints, both companies said they did not have the capacity to provide access screening and denied that the messages were obscene. <PERSON> Intercambio </PERSON> also argued that it had not violated the regulation because it never intended to transmit to minors or on an interstate basis. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> said its policy was `` to terminate service at the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s direction for any customer found in violation of laws concerning minor access to pornographic messages.''
