<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: His biggest, to CORRECT figure to
$31,264</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> paid $ 86,684 in 1987 income taxes on a total income of $ 308,396, according to a tax return released by his office on Thursday. That compares to the $ 115,486 that the Bushes reported paying for 1986 on total income of $ 348,594. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s tax bill amounted to 28 percent of his total income in 1987, down from the 33 percent he paid in 1986, showing that he, as President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and many other Americans, benefited from the sweeping tax-law changes that took effect for 1987 taxes. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s income included his $ 112,633 salary as vice president and $ 2,048 in additional reimbursment from the government. His biggest chunk of outside income came from the blind trust he and his wife set up when he took office, totaling $ 169,600 _ including $ 26,075 in capital gains, $ 31,264 in interest and dividends and $ 112,261 in supplemental income. Precisely where this money came from was not detailed, under terms of the blind trust agreement. Aides have said previously that the trust is valued at about $ 1 million. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also reported $ 20,773 in `` passive income'' from his interest in a liquefied natural gas barge. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s salary was up from the $ 97,900 he received in 1986, reflecting a general raise in federal salaries. The main reason his total income was lower was because he had a much lower level of capital gains _ income from sales of assets, property or stock. In 1986, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reported total capital gains of $ 430,165, apparently reflecting a decision by the trustees of his blind trust to sell off assets before the new tax law changes took effect and increased the tax on such gains. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has made returning to a lower rate of taxation on capital gains a prime campaign theme, saying the decision to tax capital gains at the same rate as other earnings stifles business investment. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed a capital gains tax of 15 percent. The Bushes claimed total deductions for 1987 of $ 53,314, including $ 12,225 in contributions to 35 charities. The contributions included $ 1,000 gifts to the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alumni </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Negro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had made $ 89,588 in tax payments, including $ 32,588 withheld from his salary _ suggesting a refund of $ 2,904. However, the vice president elected to have the money held and applied to his 1988 taxes. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also reported $ 1,575 in royalties in 1987 on his book, `` Looking Forward,'' published by <PERSON> Doubleday </PERSON> last September. The vice president claimed $ 3,574 in deductions for business meals and entertainment and $ 6,880 in miscellaneous business deductions. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has released his tax returns annually. In January, he also released 14 years of previous returns in a challenge to then-rival Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> to do the same. Those returns showed that 1986 was his biggest income year, and that over the 14-year period he paid taxes ranging from 3 percent to 41 percent of his annual income. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s interest income included $ 66 from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> credit union. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> released his tax return earlier this month. It showed that he and his wife <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> paid $ 86,638 in taxes on total income of $ 345,359 _ down from their $ 92,460 tax bill on 1986 total income of $ 336,640. The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> estimates that by next year, when the tax-law changes are fully in place, about three-quarters of all Americans will have smaller tax bills than they had in 1986.
