<HEAD>Lawyer Argues That KAL Crew Were Negligent In Making Doomed Flight</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs first 2 grafs to clarify who lawyer represents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crew of the <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> plane shot down by Soviet fighters in 1983 negligently made the flight knowing the navigation system was not working, a lawyer for the victims' relatives argued Thursday <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Madole </PERSON>, lead counsel for a committee that represents the relatives of those killed in the Sept. 1, 1983 crash of Flight 007, said there was abundant evidence to show that the crew chose to continue the flight even though it determined in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> that the navigation system was not properly set before takeoff from <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. A total of 269 passengers and crew died when the flight, which originated in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, was shot down over the Sea of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> after straying off course into Soviet air space. The plane `` ended up 320 miles off course'' because the inertial navigation system -LRB- INS -RRB- had been improperly set during a fueling stop in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. `` From the moment that airplane took off it was never, never on course,'' he told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` The crew deliberately attempted to conceal their failure to either properly stabilize the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> or set it up properly,'' <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. The pilot and crew knew the journey without navigation guides would lead the plane into a dangerous area where it could be shot down without warning if it strayed into Soviet airspace, <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. `` Obviously the crew knew the danger and chanced it anyway,'' he said. But KAL attorney <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> said these allegations were based on `` opinion, surmise, conjecture'' rather than evidence. `` There is no need for a trial in this case,'' <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> told <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, who has presided over five years of litigation arising from the crash. <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said the plaintiffs should be given a chance to press their claim of punitive damages at a trial. Even before the flight had left the coast of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> for the long journey across open seas, the crew had violated a number of aviation regulations, <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. The plane should have flown directly over the radio beacon at <LOCATION> Bethel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> to check its position when the crew determined it was 15 miles off course, <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. But the crew members ignored their duty and did n't fly the plane over the radio beacon because they knew the navigational system was not functioning. Once the plane passed over the coast, `` there is no white highway line across the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. The pilot, Capt. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Byung-in </PERSON>, wanted to avoid returning to <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> to reset the nevigation system because such an emergency landing would force him to dump 100,000 pounds of jet fuel. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> knew this costly and time-consuming detour would anger airline officials and passengers, <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. He cited the deposition testimony of former <ORGANIZATION> KAL </ORGANIZATION> pilot <PERSON> Park </PERSON> <PERSON> Yong </PERSON> <PERSON> Man </PERSON> who said he and <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> had spoken the night before the ill-fated flight about four other incidents that year in which <ORGANIZATION> KAL </ORGANIZATION> crews had made emergency landings to reset navigation systems. <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> had told Park `` if it happened to him he would go on'' to avoid losing face with his superiors and friends, <PERSON> Madole </PERSON> said. `` It would be a terrible disgrace in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> if they have to come back.'' Authorities have not been able to determine exactly how the plane ended up 320 miles off course because the cockpit and flight data recorders were never recovered. But aviation experts theorize that incorrect data was punched into the computerized navigation system before the plane took off from <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. If the judge dismisses the case, the airline would only be liable for $ 75,000 per passenger under international aviation conventions. But the plaintiffs are seeking to collect far greater amounts by holding the airline liable for punitive damages.
