<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> thanked <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> for negotiating a peaceful end to the hijacking of one of its jetliners, but critics led by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> said the hijackers should not have been allowed to go free. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s official news agency <ORGANIZATION> KUNA </ORGANIZATION> said the nine <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> hijackers _ who had killed two <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> hostages _ were promised safe passage to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. It said the gunmen departed from <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> shortly after freeing the 31 remaining hostages in the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 before dawn Wednesday. Throughout the ordeal, which began April 5, the hijackers demanded that the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> sheikdom free 17 pro-Iranian extremists imprisoned for the 1983 bombings of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French embassies there.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> says he may appoint an acting deputy while the search continues for someone to fill the No. 2 slot in his embattled <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> after two people have rejected the post. The position is being vacated Friday by Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>, who resigned in protest March 29 out of concern that the nearly year-long criminal investigation of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> was hurting department operations. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s latest choice, former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepherd </PERSON>, said Wednesday he was concerned with the `` personal and financial sacrifices'' required of him and his family for the brief appointment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government statistics may be signaling the beginning of the end of a mid-1980s trend that saw booming growth in coastal states outstrip the rest of the country, economists say. Residents of densely populated coastal states like <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachussets </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> continued to have the highest average incomes in the nation last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. States like <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> that are dependent on farming, mining or oil were at or near the bottom. But, <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> DePass </PERSON>, an analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, says the figures show growth is accelerating in the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> regions and slowing elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is likely to join the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in approving major changes in the nation's welfare system, despite the near certainty that a presidential veto lies at the end of the long road to congressional consensus. The 25-year drive to overhaul welfare took a significant step forward Wednesday when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 17-3 to send a comprehensive reform measure to the floor. The five-year, $ 2.8 billion `` Family Security Act'' reflects a hard-won bipartisan consensus that welfare parents should work to support their children, that the goverment should help make this possible and that government aid should be a last resort.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PUNTA DE TRALCA, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A volunteer program backed by the local <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> has been launched to prepare Chileans for their first election in 15 years and, organizers hope, calm the country's stormy political waters. However, the effort already has stirred up controversy of its own, drawing fire from backers of the right-wing military government which charges that it favors the opposition. Leaders of the program, called the Crusade for Citizen Participation, say they hope to recruit 200,000 volunteers across the country for a door-to-door campaign starting in July. They say the aim is to promote voter registration and to provide electors with non-partisan information about their options.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A minor, everyday stress like public speaking can be as damaging to the heart as strenuous exercise in people who have cardiac disease, and even can trigger heart attacks, according to research published today. The researchers found that the common stresses can cause silent ischemia, a painless but ominous disruption in the flow of blood to the heart's own muscle. The study, published in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, shows that `` previously unrecognized mental activities have very important consequences,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepine </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a state where thousands of empty miles promise little more than highway hypnosis, and today's culinary special may be a bowl of truck-stop chili, relief is in sight for the culturally bereft. A new guidebook takes some of the mystery out of the seemingly endless ribbons of roadway in the Lone Star state by detailing motels, restaurants, gas stations, convenience stores and bank machines at every <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> freeway exit. `` Just gathering the information was a monumental effort,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cima </PERSON>, who probed the delights of 2,400 exits during a four-month, 7,000-mile jaunt to assemble `` Sunset Highway Services Directory, Exit-By-Exit.''
</TEXT>
