<HEAD>Emotive French vs. English Debate Flares Anew in Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic Cartoon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For three centuries, language has divided <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s two founding cultures. The novelist <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLennan </PERSON> prophetically called it the `` Two Solitudes'' of English and French. Despite some progress toward bilingualism at a federal level as promised in the 1982 constitution, language tensions have flared anew from French-speaking <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> to the western prairies, where English is dominant. A fluently bilingual Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, about to start his re-election campaign, has suddenly found himself diverted into quelling anglophone and francophone unrest. Three issues have converged to create the new turmoil: _ The province of <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION> has repealed an 1886 act requiring it to issue laws in both English and French <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION> is expected to do the same. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is about to rule on <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s controversial ban on English signs Quebec is 81-percent French but the vocal English minority in `` la belle province'' claims the ban violates freedom of speech and is unconstitutional. _ <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> faces opposition from members of his own <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in the west over a proposed new Official Languages Act that would strengthen bilingualism in federal courts and institutions `` The populace will be seething and smarting as it pays for bureaucrats who communicate with one another in a language -LRB- French -RRB- which close to four out of five Canadians can not understand,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Byfield </PERSON>, publisher of Western Report magazine. Trying to balance historic sensitivities in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> with the need to keep his base of support in the west, <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s first prime minister in 1867 had to handle the linguistic rift `` and I'm sure it will be the case 120 years from now.'' `` Language issues will always be there to trouble and upset us and even to divide us,'' he said. At stake for <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> Meech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accord </ORGANIZATION> he negotiated with all 10 provinces last year, bringing <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> into the constitutional fold as a `` distinct society'' and purporting to protect the rights of linguistic minorities elsewhere. Several provinces have balked at ratifying the deal and now complain that the accord reached at <LOCATION> Meech </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> rings hollow when put to the test. Premier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> came in for particularly harsh criticism during visits in mid-April to <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>, neighbors on the prairies. He refused to condemn the provinces for not honoring a Feb. 25 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that said their laws should be issued in both English and French under an 1886 statute. The historic failure to provide laws in French had prompted a French-speaking priest, the Rev. <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercure </PERSON>, to contest a <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION> speeding ticket. He died before the case reached the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, but it was a pyrrhic victory for the province's 25,000 francophones since the court suggested that <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION> could repeal the old law and replace it with an English-only policy That's exactly what Premier <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION> has done, arguing that the province can not afford to re-enact all laws in French. In the province of just over 1 million people, only 25,000 speak French, and they also speak English. Pressed to intervene, <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> told reporters: `` I am not a federal politician. I was not elected to represent <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ares </PERSON>, a francophone leader in <LOCATION> Saskatchewan </LOCATION>, blasted the premier as `` a traitor'' to the French cause outside <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>. `` He's backpedalling,'' added <PERSON> Aurele </PERSON> <PERSON> Theriault </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francophones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Outside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quebec </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Federation des francophones hors <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> -RRB-. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> chose to praise <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> for pledging to translate some laws into French and permit use of the language in the courts and <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, while setting up language classes for civil servants. <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>, meanwhile, told <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> that his actions had national implications and offered federal funds for expanding bilingualism in the province. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> is also under pressure at home, where he pledged in his 1985 election campaign to lift the ban on bilingual signs. But when an English department store, <PERSON> Zeller </PERSON>'s, was firebombed last year after adding English to its signs, <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> retreated for the sake of what he termed `` social peace.'' With the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling on signs pending, federal Languages Commissioner <PERSON> D'Iberville </PERSON> <PERSON> Fortier </PERSON> stirred the controversy by accusing the French in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> of `` humiliating'' their English neighbors. <PERSON> Royal </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, president of the English-rights pressure group <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quebec </ORGANIZATION>, maintained that a new language crisis could prompt the exodus of 100,000 Quebec English speakers, who are a major economic force in the province. `` Frankly, I do n't think <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> can sustain that kind of loss.'' On another front, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s culture minister, <PERSON> Lise </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacon </PERSON>, proposed new film distribution laws tightly restricting the number of English-language movies that can be screened in the province. Meanwhile, the government insists that its new Official Languages Act is merely an attempt to comply with the constitution, not a means of enforcing compulsory bilingualism in regions where it's not wanted. But opponents claim every federal court and agency will be required to have bilingual judges and staff, and those unable to speak French will be bypassed for jobs and promotions. `` It's a tragedy,'' said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Kindy </PERSON>, a Conservative member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Calgary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION>. `` I think <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> is moving more and more towards unilingualism and the rest of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> is going to be forced to be more and more bilingual.'' To French-Canadians, whose ancestors arrived in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> before the British, language preservation is their birthright. `` If the rights of francophones had been respected since the last century, maybe there would n't be so few of us now,'' said <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Cyr </PERSON> of the Acadian Federation of <LOCATION> Nova </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Scotia </LOCATION>, which has about 31,000 French speakers. `` Francophones have just as much right to be here as anglophones. We founded the country too.'' Ironically, all three major political parties support bilingualism as do major newspapers. But in the world's second most spacious country, the language issue falls victim to demographics. Of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s 25 million people, about 6.2 million speak French. But 5.3 million of those live in one province, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, where French is the sole official language and a majority never speak English. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, the province bordering <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, is one-third French and the nation's only officially bilingual province. Of <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>'s 9.3 million people, 425,000 are francophones West of <LOCATION> Winnipeg </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Manitoba </LOCATION>, however, not even one in 10 of the area's 6.7 million people lists <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> as their native tongue. Former Prime Minister <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Trudeau </PERSON> promoted bilingualism to defuse the separatist movement in his native Quebec, and English and French were declared the official federal languages in 1969. Federal documents are issued in both languages, government departments have bilingual names, and unilingual civil servants are paid to take language classes. In cities such as <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, anglophone parents have enrolled 200,000 children in French immersion schools, the most promising sign of real change. But in most regions, from <LOCATION> Newfoundland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, bilingualism has been slow to take root. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Levesque </PERSON>, the late premier of <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, once said <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> speakers in the rest of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> were `` dead ducks'' who would inevitably lose out to the English majority.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs April 25</NOTE>
