<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Greek Music, Adv 26,0725</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, April 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Little Greek Music From an Irish Cellist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> was a shaggy-haired Irish cellist when he left <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on a musical journey that followed the hippy trail to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Eighteen years later, he's an internationally acclaimed performer of traditional <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> music _ the plaintive kind that <ORGANIZATION> Westerners </ORGANIZATION> used to call `` weird'' and `` outlandish.'' `` It was n't enough, being in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and learning the sitar in a vacuum,'' the 36-year-old musician said. `` I wanted to find out how Eastern music really worked. That meant exploring, and it took a long time.'' On the road, <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> took lessons from traditional musicians wherever he could find them _ in workers' cafes or at Moslem weddings, even at the whirling dervishes' monastery at <LOCATION> Konya </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. `` There's a kind of camaraderie among musicians. They'd show me things, maybe not all the tricks, but enough to get me started on playing in an authentic way,'' he said. <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> performs and composes on a dozen exotic stringed instruments, from the stubby Turkish `` oud,'' a member of the lute family, to the resonant Afghan `` rambaba'' and his favorite old-fashioned Cretan `` lyra.'' His two latest albums, one solo and another with an international group he formed and called <LOCATION> Lavyrinthos </LOCATION> _ the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> spelling for `` labyrinth'' _ received first-rate reviews both in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and abroad. `` <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> is important for what he does to preserve the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> musical tradition ... and because he does n't just imitate, he innovates as well,'' said <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Duran </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> musicologist who heads <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archive </ORGANIZATION>, in an interview. A childhood spent in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> gave <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> what he said was `` an eclectic approach to music that meant I was n't stuck in the Western classical groove.'' His American music school training was useful for studying the structure of Oriental music and then dissecting its regional variations. `` We talk about Greek music being different from Turkish, or Syrian from <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION>, but in fact they're all part of a common musical tradition that stretches all the way from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and goes back centuries,'' he said. That's what <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> and his group _ which includes Turkish, Armenian, <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> musicians _ tries to illustrate in performances that attract sell-out audiences in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> clubs and cultural centers. Their music strips down traditional Oriental themes to reveal haunting, melancholy melodies or mesmeric rhythms. `` We do n't use amplifiers and we like to play to no more than a couple of hundred people. ... That means we ca n't really be considered a good commercial proposition for a mass market,'' <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> said. But after a dramatic rise in record sales over the past six months, <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> is preparing another album and also working on a documentary feature about traditional east Mediterranean music for British television. His time is split between performances and recording sessions in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, a home on the island of <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION> and concert trips to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. But he still travels in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> several months a year to work on his repertoire and add to his collection of several hundred Oriental instruments. Among Greek composers and instrumentalists, who regret the loss of skilled techniques as the local music-making tradition declines, <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> is admired for his performing talents as well as his original work. `` He's a tremendously sensitive musician who's developed a deep feeling for our music. He extracts its essence in his compositions,'' said composer <PERSON> Manos </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadjidakis </PERSON>, who won an Academy Award for scoring the film `` Never on Sunday.'' In <LOCATION> Crete </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> sometimes puts on a traditional black shirt to play the lyra at a village wedding which may last for 24 hours of feasting, drinking and dancing. He is famed for his ability to extract a rich, melodic tone from the pear-shaped, toy-size instrument which has three-strings and is played with a bow. `` People think the lyra is a peculiarly Cretan instrument but I've found it all over <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minor </LOCATION> and it must have been around since Byzantine times. I fell for it as soon as I heard it,'' <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> said. End Adv PM Tues April 26
