<HEAD>`Tour Of Duty' Struggling in Jungles of Hawaii _ and the Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> signed on to play Sgt. <PERSON> Zeke </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> in CBS' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> war series `` Tour of Duty,'' it sounded like a dream job _ a starring role in a network show shot on location in beautiful <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. `` It's not what it's cracked up to be. It's work,'' said <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> on a recent visit to drizzly <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I hasten to say that what we go through is nothing compared to what the veterans went through in real warfare, but I can at least appreciate it a little bit, at least a Peeping <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>'s perspective on being away from home in a hot place where it rains a lot and where you do n't really see civilians.'' `` Civilians'' for <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> and the rest of the cast and crew are the tourists who stay at the same <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> hotel. There is no fraternizing. `` People come in waves of like two weeks in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, so there's no meaningful relationship to be struck up here,'' joked the young and single <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> `` Especially when people are in a zany kind of get-a-tan-in-two-days mentality. I mean, you ca n't even seduce anyone when they're thinking about a suntan.'' A typical 14-hour shooting day is often spent crawling around in dusty tunnels or muddy swamps. Sometimes across the island, the CBS detective series `` Magnum, P.I.'' would be filming, in a decidedly more genteel atmosphere where series stars do n't have to worry about being killed off in the name of authenticity. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Conroy </PERSON> was the first casualty among the regulars on `` Tour.'' `` None of us is immune. I'm glibly sitting here munching french bread in a restaurant today, but we'll see,'' said <PERSON> Knox </PERSON>, whose job is presumably safe since he has top billing. <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> is deeply dedicated to the series, and frustrated by the lack of audience. `` Tour'' premiered last fall with a sophisticated, film-quality style, good writing and fine performances. But it has not prospered in the ratings. It spent most of the season opposite `` The Cosby Show'' on Thursday night at the unseemly early hour of 8 p.m. Eastern time. Its ratings improved somewhat in its new Saturday 9 p.m. time period. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> executives, who will announce the network's fall schedule in May, say they remain confident in the show. `` I still believe that if you work hard enough at something, it deserves a shot,'' <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> said. `` You just wo n't believe how hard some of that stuff is to do and how dangerous _ nothing compared to what the real veterans went through. The technical advisers come out there who are veterans _ without exception before the end of their episode, they come up and say, ` We had no idea you guys worked this hard.''' The way <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> plays him, Sgt. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> is a no-nonsense guy who has re-upped for the second time after finding a kind of success on the battlefield he could n't find in civilian life. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> has no interest in politics, he just wants to get his men out alive. Veterans groups praised <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> when it announced plans for `` Tour of Duty'' last year. The response from viewers who are veterans has been `` overwhelmingly positive,'' <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> said. He said the show gets a lot of mail from veterans who say they were unable to talk about their experiences until they saw `` Tour of Duty.'' `` CBS did n't undertake this show as therapy for anybody,'' <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> said. `` It was entertainment, going to be quality entertainment, and it has remained that. But in addition, it has become a great bringing together of these forces, people who had never talked about it -LRB- the war -RRB- before.'' Before `` Tour,'' <PERSON> Knox </PERSON>'s best-known role was Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` St. Elsewhere,'' a role he thought would be a six-episode shot. But it developed into one of the most popular subplots on the critically praised series, when <PERSON> White </PERSON> turned out to be a rapist. He was later killed off. `` It made life hell in the singles bars for awhile,'' <PERSON> Knox </PERSON> said with a laugh. Before `` St. Elsewhere,'' he said, his biggest role was in a minor film `` starring a $ 70,000 <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> truck and myself _ and the truck was better than I was.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: NIGHT OF MANY GUEST STARS _ There'll be a lot of resume-updating after the final, two-hour episode of `` Magnum, P.I.'' which <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> will air May 1. There are 18, count'em, 18 guest stars, among them biggies <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdon </PERSON>. Most, including <PERSON> Verdon </PERSON>, are reprising roles from the show's eight-year run. They are, in alphabetical order: Brandon Call, <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elisha </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>, <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Dobb </PERSON>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> LeGault </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON>, <PERSON> Patrice </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Regalbuto </PERSON>, <PERSON> Shavar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gwen </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdon </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Yasbeck </PERSON>.
