<HEAD>TEHRAN: luxuries, however.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Private wealth has been widely left untouched by <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s Islamic revolution and free enterprise is encouraged by the Koran, the Islamic holy book. The black market has become so much a part of the economy that the `` free'' exchange rates are regularly quoted by the national news agency, <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION>. And although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remains the `` Great Satan,'' the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar is the preferred currency and at the free-exchange rate one dollar fetches 1,165 rials, 17 times the official rate. `` I know of a woman who still flies to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> every spring to buy a new collection of clothes, spending perhaps $ 15,000 or more,'' said one European resident at a dinner party replete with whiskey, rock music and dancing _ all forbidden _ in <LOCATION> Shemiram </LOCATION>, the elegant section in northern <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. Shemiram has been spared by <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> missiles so far. But even there, some villas and apartments are empty because their owners have fled to <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> resorts or the <LOCATION> Elburz </LOCATION> mountains, where Islamic rules require men and women to ski on separate trails. The Shemiram section also includes the residence of the 86-year-old <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, who looks in relatively good shape, according to diplomats who recently saw him at his mosque. Growing popular discontent with the unequal sharing of the war's financial burdens may have been at a root of his recent Fatwa, or binding religious guideline, that strengthened the hands of the government Up to now, key economic reforms have been blocked on religious grounds by the Council for the Protection of the Constitution, a watchdog body dominated by Islamic fundamentalists. Tax collection has been sluggish. Deputy Finance Minister <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Majedi </PERSON> said recently taxation capacity was twice that currently collected. A Western diplomat termed his estimate a gross understatement. `` God knows that even the filthy capitalist system in the West is not like that,'' a legislator, <PERSON> Sahed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Tahaili </PERSON>, recently complained in the Majlis, the 270-seat parliament. He was referring to a huge tax debt run up by one of the various foundations controlled by religious authorities. `` When someone moves to another state in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, all his records are checked to make sure he has paid all his taxes,'' the legislator added. The new parliament formed after the April 8 general elections is widely predicted to step up pressure for reforms, with the position of its pragmatist speaker, <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, strengthened further. Reformers may face an uphill battle. Official figures cited by the newspaper Etela'at suggest that black market trends are determined by speculative money worth tens of billions of dollars. There is little doubt, however, that the role of the mullahs, the religious dignitaries, will be reduced by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s Fatwa. The Fatwa says the government may even prevent <PERSON> Hadj </PERSON>, the annual Moslem pilgrimage to Mecca in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, if the national interests demand a temporary suspension. Iranians already have noticed a certain relaxation in the enforcement of religious laws. Women wearing make-up or nail polish or who let part of their hair peek out from under a headdress are normally no longer stopped on the street by the Pasdaran, the revolutionary guards. But the chador, the all-encompassing outer garment, remains a must for women, even when skiing. `` When they come downhill, they look like bats,'' said the wife of a European ambassador.
</TEXT>
