<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Exhibit of Ancient Egypt's Last Great Pharaoh To Open In Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Generations of workers and slaves transported granite blocks 600 miles down the <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to erect the 57-ton Colossus of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>. Nearly 3,200 years later, sophisticated engineers at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s Museum of Science were perplexed about how they would handle the giant statue honoring <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, the last great Pharaoh of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and the empire's most prolific builder While preparing for an exhibit of artifacts from his 66-year reign, engineers grappled with methods to bring the 27-foot structure into the museum. Proposals to demolish a wall or cut a hole in the roof were deemed infeasible and too costly. `` So we decided to put it outside,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Dussault </PERSON>, a project coordinator for the `` Ramesses the Great'' exhibit, which opens April 30 and runs for four months. `` I have to say it looks pretty majestic.'' Exhibit directors use the preferred translation of the Pharaoh's name _ Ramesses _ instead of the more accepted anglicized version, <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> The giant statue depicts Ramses wearing the cone-shaped crown of upper <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> royalty and a pleated skirt. Jewels adorn his neck and wrist, as he strides forward, left foot first. The colossus was uncovered by crews digging the foundation for a building in 1962 near <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. It was broken into three large pieces and many fragments. About 30 workers began to reassemble the statue in 1985, doing the reconstruction in the area where it had been discovered. The Colossus of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> will stand outside the museum, encased in a 40-foot wood and steel structure resembling an ancient Egyptian temple. The monument is the centerpiece of the 72-piece exhibit, the largest collection of antiquities from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s Golden Age ever on display in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The Ramses show is larger than the 55 artifacts seen by more than 8 million people in the Tutankhanum exhibit, which toured the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> in the late 1970s and generated more than $ 50 million. Priceless antiquities from the reign of Ramses the Great were first seen in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in October 1985 at <ORGANIZATION> Brigham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. That show went on to be displayed at the World's Fair in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tenn </PERSON>. The three sections of the colossus and dozens of crates containing other artifacts from <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>'s Egyptian Museum arrived in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> last week from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The exhibit, insured by <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for $ 40 million, was designed to depict the grandeur as well as the simplicity of life under <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON>. Ornate jewelry, including a 19-pound gold necklace with braided collar and 14 tassels, are displayed along with such prosaic items as a cosmetic case, a bronze razor and senet, a board game popular at the time. There's also the lid from the mummy coffin that contained <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON>' remains; the elaborate burial chamber of <LOCATION> Sannedjem </LOCATION>, a respected painter and artisan; and several statues of baboons from the temple at <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Simbel </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> left a rich legacy of monuments and buildings, including his mortuary temple at <LOCATION> Thebes </LOCATION>, the temple of <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Simbel </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Nubia </LOCATION>, two obelisks in front of the Temple at <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION>, his palace city at <LOCATION> Zoan </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Karnak </LOCATION> with the largest columns in the world _ they measure roughly 11 feet in diameter. Architects still marvel at the precision of <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Simbel </LOCATION>, where sunlight streams 160 feet into the temple on certain days to illuminate an inner chamber. <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON>, reported to have sired 90 children, waged a long and successful battle against the Hittites of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> and is believed by some biblical scholars to be the Pharaoh of the Book of Exodus. Like his prodigious family and his mammoth projects, tales of his life ring on a grand scale. Ancient records say <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> claimed his birth was signaled by the emergence of the star <ORGANIZATION> Sirius </ORGANIZATION> on the same day as Egyptians' began their religious and civil new years, a convergence which occurs once every 1,461 years. He ruled from 1279-1213 B.C. No one is quite sure when he was born, but he was in his 80s when he died. <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> <PERSON> I </PERSON>, his grandfather who founded the 19th dynasty after Akhnaton and <PERSON> Tutankhamen </PERSON>, ruled for one year. Seti I, <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON>' father, waged war against Libyans and <PERSON> Hittites </PERSON> and extended the boundaries of the Egyptian empire. <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> continued war against the <ORGANIZATION> Hittites </ORGANIZATION> _ an ancient people of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minor </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> _ in <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. The Battle of <LOCATION> Kadesh </LOCATION> was one of the last battles with the <ORGANIZATION> Hittites </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> later signed a peace treaty with the <ORGANIZATION> Hittites </ORGANIZATION>. Although <PERSON> Ramses </PERSON>' mummy remains in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> exhibit will feature Padihershef, a 2,500-year-old mummy owned by <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. Last month, Padihershef, a stonecutter, was transported from the hospital in a plastic bubble stretcher designed for victims of nuclear accidents. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, director of traveling exhibits at the museum, said negotiations to bring the exhibit to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> were launched several years ago by museum director <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, who died in December. After the Ramses exhibit returns to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, the colossus will remain in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, for six more months. Each city sponsoring the exhibit guarantees a minimum $ 400,000 payment to the Egyptian government to help construct a new national museum.
</TEXT>
