<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 24, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>To Build or Not to Build?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-New Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEASIDE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For 20 years <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> has talked architecture, taught architecture, delineated architecture, designed architecture. Everything but built architecture. `` I do not build because I am an architect,'' he once wrote, meaning he would not compromise his principles and build in a world being rendered uninhabitable by industrialization, technology and modern architecture. When his plan for a school in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> came in 200 percent over budget, <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> gave up the commission rather than change his design. But now this consummate purist is building _ a wood cottage for vacation time in this new <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> panhandle resort. `` He finally took a deep breath and plunged into the abyss,'' says <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, Seaside's developer. `` I'm honored he's willing to make an exception for Seaside.'' `` Seaside comes along at just the right moment,'' <PERSON> Krier </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> native, said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` There's nothing new like it.'' As far as <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> is concerned, all the problems of architecture were solved before the Industrial Revolution; modern architecture and technology have served mainly to ruin the world's cities. Seaside, on the other hand, reflects his preference for small settlements, human scale, pedestrian activity and traditional buildings. Although <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> has no track record, `` his plans have been influential far beyond their unexecuted state for the way in which they have re-established a lost vision'' of a romantic past, according to architectural critic <PERSON> Ada </PERSON> <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Huxtable </PERSON>. <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> also is a bit of a gadfly. At an architects' conference three years ago, <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> pointedly questioned <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, dean of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> architects, about a skyscraper he'd designed in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The building, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> admitted, was `` 2 million square feet of space that should not be in this part of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.'' Implicitly acknowledging <PERSON> Krier </PERSON>'s purity, he added, `` I am a whore and I am paid very well for high-rise buildings.'' In return for helping to lay out Seaside's plan and design the town tower, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> gave <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> a building lot. But he attached one condition: <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> had to build on it. The three-room cottage, designed to resemble a classical temple, should be ready this summer. <PERSON> Krier </PERSON> wants to see how it turns out before completing his design for the tower. After years of designing on paper, he joked, `` I want to see how many mistakes I've made.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 24</NOTE>
