<HEAD>Markets Distressed Over Evidence of Higher Inflation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with Commerce Department report on March durable
goods orders, due at 8:30 a.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Rising consumer prices are contributing to worries in the financial markets that inflation is accelerating. The government said Wednesday that consumer prices jumped 0.5 percent in March, reflecting a record increase in clothing costs and higher food and gasoline prices that triggered the biggest inflation jump in 14 months. Analysts said the sharp increase in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Consumer Price Index, which translated into a 6.4 percent annual growth rate, demonstrated that the weak dollar and unexpectedly strong consumer demand were threatening to ignite a new bout of spiraling costs They speculated those pressures soon would prompt the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to nudge interest rates higher. The bond market, a good indicator of inflation sentiment, reacted negatively to the CPI report. Bond prices fell and the yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s key 30-year bond rose to 9.05 percent, although prices later recovered somewhat. Stocks also fell Wednesday, pushing the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average down 14.09 points to 1,985.41, its third straight decline. The financial markets first were jolted last week when an unexpectedly high <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for February sent the dollar plunging. A government report that wholesale prices jumped in March intensified investor worries. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, which is counting on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to keep the economy growing through the November election, contended Wednesday that the inflation fears were overblown. `` Despite large increases for consumer and producer prices in March, the smaller increases in prices in previous months ... indicate that inflation remains under control,'' said presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. Some private economists disputed that view. `` The CPI rise reflects an increasingly widespread inflationary environment,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The good news on inflation is over for this year and the question now really is ` how high will prices go?''' The March CPI increase followed a modest 0.2 percent February rise and was the biggest monthly gain since a 0.7 percent increase in January 1987. In another economic report, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deparment </ORGANIZATION> said Americans' average weekly earnings, after discounting for inflation, fell 0.3 percent in March, the second consecutive monthly decline The changes left Americans' inflation-adjusted earnings 1.2 percent below a year ago.
</TEXT>
