<FIRST>r f PM-Japan-EconomicBoom Bjt   04-21 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Economic Boom, Bjt,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Economy Booming, Surprising Economists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s economy is riding one of its biggest booms of the past five years, surprising many economists who just last year were predicting a recession. Economists say the boom _ fueled by low interest rates, tax cuts and massive public spending _ will continue for at least two years. Further into the future, they say, annual growth in the gross national product likely will exceed the government's 3.75 percent forecast for the next five years. `` The speed of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s recovery has surprised most commentators. This is really a remarkable pace,'' said <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Jerran </PERSON>, an economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benson </ORGANIZATION> investment firm. `` The domestic economy is roaring.'' During the past 11 months, manufacturing output shot up 14 percent, a figure that took twice as long to achieve during the boom years of the 1970s, economists say. Government officials report that corporate profits rose 27.2 percent during 1987, while household savings rose by 11.8 percent. Inflation-adjusted consumer spending rose a near record 5.8 percent in February alone, second only to a 5.9 percent rise recorded in November 1975. According to the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>, sustaining the current economic pace over the rest of 1988 would mean gross national product growth of 5 percent, corporate profit growth of about 18 percent and retail sales growth of 13.8 percent. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON>, senior economist for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s 1987 growth alone could keep the economic boom rolling for the rest of this year _ making it a fertile market for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other nations wanting to boost their exports. A drop in Japanese exports because of the rising yen _ which makes Japanese products more expensive overseas _ cooled the economy somewhat last year, but exports affect only 17 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s GNP, <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said. `` The other 83 percent is not exports, and that did very well,'' he said. <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said the current boom is the best of the past four or five years, although the officially projected GNP growth rate of 3.75 percent is low compared to the 8 percent to 10 percent a year <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> achieved during the 1960s and part of the 1970s. Just last May, economists were saying <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was headed for an economic downturn, with the yen's rapid rise inflating prices for the nation's export-driven economy. Industrial production fell to its lowest rate in years, and unemployment rose to a record 3.2 percent. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s unemployment rate is artificially low, because it counts as employed members of the armed forces and people who work more than one hour during the last week of the month. `` There was a lot of pressure to stop the yen from going up'' in 1986, <PERSON> Jerran </PERSON> said. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> achieved this by cutting interest rates, fueling a domestic housing boom that contributed about one-third of the GNP growth.'' <PERSON> Jerran </PERSON> said the government also injected $ 48 billion into the economy through public works spending and tax cuts. At a news conference on Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> said he was pleased with the economy's performance and said one of his biggest concerns is maintaining stability. <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> said that without a sudden appreciation in the yen or a rapid rise in prices, economic growth was unlikely to slow. Although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will benefit somewhat from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s prosperity, <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> said the effect would not be that great Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports rose by 55.8 percent last month from a year earlier, exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> still accounted for less than 1 percent of gross national product. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needs to export not only to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> but everywhere else to get out of the problems it is in now,'' he said. One downside to the Japanese economy might be in housing starts and the relative prosperity <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has enjoyed for the past year: things have been so good, economists say, there is bound to be a slowdown. The cost of housing has reached the point where it takes eight years of a worker's gross income to purchase a small condominium, which costs about $ 500,000. Four years is considered normal in most other countries. <PERSON> Jerran </PERSON> also says there is a danger of the Japanese economy overheating. `` Because of the rapid rise over the past year, industry is running out of capacity and labor,'' he said. `` This raises the danger that prices will climb upwards.'' In turn, the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> may decide to push interest rates higher _ possibly by this summer _ to help curb inflation, he said.
</TEXT>
