<HEAD>Aeromexico Strike and Bankruptcy Raises Tourism Concerns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prospects for a banner year in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s crucial tourism industry may have been grounded by the bankruptcy of the government's <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> airline A federal judge declared <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> bankrupt on Monday and ordered it into receivership, leaving its more than 9,200 workers jobless. The airline already had canceled most of its flights because of a strike triggered by <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION>'s plans for a cost-cutting restructuring. `` The disappearance of <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> will affect negatively the tourism sector and will hinder -LRB- it -RRB- from reaching the estimates of transportation of foreign visitors to the different national destinations,'' Tourism Secretary <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Enriquez </PERSON> <PERSON> Savignac </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday night. Tourism vies with the `` maquiladora'' assembly plant industry _ in which foreign companies set up factories in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to take advantage of cheap labor _ _ as the nation's No. 2 source of foreign exchange after petroleum. Estimates had been that tourism would bring in as much as $ 2.4 billion this year, the highest since 1982, when the peso's drop in value against the dollar started a slide in tourism revenue. <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> filed for bankruptcy after ground and technical workers went on strike April 12 in protest of management plans to reduce the fleet and route system to bring the money-losing airline into the black. <PERSON> Enriquez </PERSON> <PERSON> Savignac </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Mexicana </PERSON>, the other state-run airline which is unaffected by the bankruptcy or strike, carry 57 percent of the foreign tourists arriving by air. <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> was the only carrier serving 15 Mexican cities. Representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technicians </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 7,250 striking workers, announced plans to seek a meeting with President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. `` We will ask the president for a restructuring of the company,'' <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Mejorada </PERSON>, the union's secretary for internal matters, said in a phone interview. He said the union still had not received formal notification of the judge's bankruptcy decision, which had been announced by the federal Communications and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The airline's 2,000 pilots and cabin attendants have their own unions that did not support the strike, which forced cancellation of all 223 daily flights to 42 domestic and international destinations. The union has charged that the decision to seek bankruptcy was politically motivated and not made on economic grounds. No plans have been announced for a replacement for <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION>. Mexicana on Tuesday started accepting <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> tickets for routes in which they operated with parallel service. <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> started business in 1934 and has been owned by the government since 1957. Mexicana has been controlled by the government since 1982.
