<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Lifts No-Smoking Assignment From Ad Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is putting another advertising agency in charge of creating commercials for its smoke-free flights to relieve tobacco industry pressures on the agency that created the first ads for its program. <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DFS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Compton </ORGANIZATION>, a huge New York-based agency, created the first ads for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s no-smoking program and remains the airline's agency for other general advertising. The commercials showed passengers applauding <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to ban smoking on nearly all its domestic flights. Shortly after the ads started airing last month, <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> was fired from its longtime job making cookie and candy ads for <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which also makes cigarettes. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it was moving the no-smoking program assignment to the <PERSON> Kolesar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hartwell </PERSON> agency, based in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. The agency already handles <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s ads in media aimed at the travel trade. The job involves about $ 2 million of the estimated $ 50 million in Northwest billings handled by <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> had cited `` philosophical differences'' for pulling its cookie and candy assignments from <LOCATION> Saatchi </LOCATION>, but those familiar with the decision said privately that <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> executives were troubled <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> had created the no-smoking ads and failed to tell them about it. `` We are extremely disappointed that a reactionary faction of the tobacco industry continues to put literally dozens of <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> professional careers in jeopardy,'' A.B. <PERSON> Magary </PERSON>, executive vice president for marketing for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, said in explaining why it moved the no-smoking assignment to another agency. He said that while the <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, Minn.-based airline was happy with <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON>'s work, it wanted to make sure that <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> `` can continue to serve us with total objectivity and enthusiasm.'' <PERSON> Magary </PERSON> declined in an interview to be more specific about what pressures <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> was under from the tobacco industry, but said the airline had been told the agency continued to feel pressured. <PERSON> Magary </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> offered to reassign the no-smoking job to another agency `` in hopes of solving their problem and they accepted our offer to do it.'' He said it was up to the agency to elaborate on whatever pressures they feel they continue to be under. But agency spokesmen declined the opportunity to do so. `` We understand <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s decision with regard to the no-smoking assignment,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeshan </PERSON>, executive vice president and management director in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> account at <LOCATION> Saatchi </LOCATION>. But he declined to say whether <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> supported or solicited the action, adding only that, `` We are anxious to put this matter behind us.'' <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> also is the advertising agency for <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s True cigarettes. <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ridgway </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION>, said the cigarette company was not putting any pressure on <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> in the wake of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> no-smoking ads. She said <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> was happy with <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON>'s work and planned to retain its relationship with the agency.
