<HEAD>AT&amp;T Profit Up 10.6 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AT&amp;T-Affirmative Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX2 of April 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newly elected Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has a `` new sense of urgency'' and is committed to sustaining its strong first-quarter profit increases. `` No officer of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T is feeling content and complacent,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> told shareholders Wednesday at the company's annual meeting. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, 53, was elevated to chairman and chief executive by the board of directors late Tuesday, a day after the death from colon cancer of his 62-year-old predecessor, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>. Also on Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T announced a 10.6 percent increase in its first quarter earnings. Its earnings per share rose 15 percent because of a redemption of preferred shares that lessened the amount that had to be skimmed off for preferred dividends. Asked at a news conference whether <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T could keep up the 15 percent growth in earnings per share for the rest of 1988, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said: `` That's our firm commitment.'' At the meeting, shareholders rejected a white supremacist group's resolution that sought to phase out <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's affirmative action but also rejected a proposal to expand affirmative action. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who was president and chief operating officer, is a thoughtful, soft-spoken contrast to the forceful <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>. But the two men were close and <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> had groomed him as a successor. `` This is a bittersweet moment for me,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> told shareholders with a slight quaver in his voice. `` I sincerely wish it were under different circumstances.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> tackled questions about whether he had the steel to continue <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>'s legacy. He said he was proud of his style of developing trusting relations with colleagues. `` First and foremost, I'm a team player,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> told reporters. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> said its profit rose to $ 492 million, or 46 cents a share, from $ 445 million, or 40 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 2.8 percent to $ 8.35 billion from $ 8.12 billion. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's earnings statement indicated continuing difficulties in selling computers and office equipment. Revenue was flat in the category of data products, network equipment and business communications products. In contrast, revenue from services, mainly long-distance, was up 8.2 percent. While noting that <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T had done a good job of cutting costs, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the company must work harder on increasing sales. `` No business can live by cost control alone. It must grow,'' he told reporters. <PERSON> Rawleigh </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, the retired chief of <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and an <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> director, told shareholders that <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> spoke with him by phone two weeks ago and said that `` should anything happen to him, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> was his natural successor.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> had served as president and chief operating officer since 1986. Before that he had held top finance jobs in the company and had a long career in the Bell telephone companies. The resolution against affirmative action was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, a white supremacist organization based in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Poinsett </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norcross </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, spoke on its behalf, contending that blacks are less intelligent and affirmative action hurts the morale of whites The resolution earned votes of 8.6 percent of the shares. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T considered the proposal `` highly objectionable'' and tried three times to get the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to keep it off the ballot. The resolution calling for more affirmative action was introduced by <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tillman </PERSON>, a black manager at <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Murray </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J </LOCATION>. He said taking better advantage of the talents of minorities and women made good business sense for <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T. It earned votes of 6 percent of the shares.
