<SECOND>PM-Auto Talks, Bjt,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Wants Japanese-Style Pay For Japanese-Style Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> would consider <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s bid to adopt corporate-wide Japanese-style production methods if its executives accept a less lucrative Japanese-style pay system, a union official says. Workers and union officials joined <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> on Wednesday in sharply criticizing the multimillion-dollar wages received by top <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> executives, particularly Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>, as the union and No. 3 automaker continued talks over a new labor contract. `` What we're wanting is what's fair and equitable for all of our members in relation to the standing of the corporation,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Local 1413 in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION> `` When we hear the type money these guys are making, then that indicates the standings of the corporation.'' Negotiations entered their fourth day today over a contract to replace the one expiring Sept. 14. The pact would cover 66,000 active and laid off workers in 15 states and 65,000 retirees. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>, the union's chief negotiator, targeted <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> the day after <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> disclosed the chairman received $ 17.9 million in 1987 in salary, cash and stock bonuses and money earned exercising stock options. <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> in 1987 was the highest-paid auto company executive for a second straight year. In 1986, when he earned $ 20.6 million, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> also was the nation's highest-paid executive. `` Executive compensations have gotten completely out of hand,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. `` It makes it extremely difficult for us to sit down in a rational manner and try to negotiate a decent contract.'' Word of <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s pay prompted calls from workers demanding that union officials seek higher pay or other benefits in their contract, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. Under the Japanese system cited by <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>, managers earn six to eight times more than workers. American managers earn about 18 times more and, in <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON>'s case, 27 times more, <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers earn $ 14.43 an hour including cost-of-living adjustments, or gross base pay of about $ 30,000. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> also said that before Japanese workers are laid off or their pay is cut, Japanese managers take a pay cut. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> raised the pay comparisons a day after <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s chief negotiator, said the automaker has asked union leaders to support its efforts to adopt so-called Modern Operating Agreements at all plants. <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s Local 1413 is one of six plants where MOAs are in effect. The Japanese-style MOA production system organizes workers into teams, uses them in a variety of jobs instead of a single defined task and reduces the number of workers needed to cover for absentees, inspect products and correct mistakes. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> also asked for a committee comprising union, company and outside representatives to study the effectiveness of job security provisions in the new contract. The committee also would look at ways to increase productivity and improve quality, another weapon in the push for MOA adoption. <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said the union would consider that proposal if the committee also could study and adjust top executives' compensation to bring it into line with the Japanese managers-to-workers pay ratio. `` We think it is only fair that since they ask us to go to a Japanese production system such as MOAs and team concept ... it is fair for them to go to the Japanese system in terms of compensation,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
