<HEAD>GM Wants Healthier Workers, Plans Expansion of Fitness Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> plans to expand a program aimed at improving the health and fitness of workers, especially those who suffer from obesity, high blood pressure, mental stress or substance abuse. `` It's already in place in some areas right now. It will be intensified in July,'' said Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s health director. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union will run the program, which will cover roughly 450,000 workers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON> said Wednesday. The No. 1 automaker decided to push the program after reviewing the results of pilot projects that began in 1985 at four auto plants. <PERSON> Mackey </PERSON> said the plants were in <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Livonia </LOCATION>. Screening and counseling could cost up to $ 24 million if all employees participate, says <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Erfurt </PERSON>, a researcher for the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> and Industrial Relations at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s potential savings, however, could be much greater. <LOCATION> Erfurt </LOCATION> estimates 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s workers suffer some type of health problem. The first step will involve blood pressure checks and a review of each employee's medical history. Employees can either enter classes for fitness, losing weight or stoping smoking; adopt self-help programs, or choose one-on-one counseling. Six months later, health care workers will contact employees to check progress. In the pilot program, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> paid the entire cost of initial screening and two-thirds of the follow-up programs, with employees paying the remainder. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s share amounted to roughly $ 53 per worker each year, <LOCATION> Erfurt </LOCATION> said. The results of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s pilot project were mixed. In two plants, less than 10 percent of the workers entered the health classes, he said. In the other two factories, nearly half the employees did so, but those workers could choose among self-help programs, counseling or full-scale classes _ unlike employees in the other two plants. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has supported various health programs for years, mostly on a plant-by-plant basis, but this one is broader and more ambitious, <LOCATION> Erfurt </LOCATION> said.
