<HEAD>Another Two-Seater Dies; Ford to Discontinue EXP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will eliminate its two-seat Escort EXP model late this summer, making way for increased production of two - and four-door cars, the company said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> recalled 50 workers who had been indefinitely laid off from the <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> assembly plant after announcing the production change Wednesday, said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 900 </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 3,100 hourly workers at the plant. The elimination of the EXP will allow increased production of the Escort, the Escort wagon and the Escort GT, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> told the <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> workers it could make more money by building more Escort GTs, which are high-performance cars based on the Escort economy car, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said. The move follows a decision earlier this year by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to cease production of the <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fiero </LOCATION>, a rear-engine, plastic-body, two-seat sports car. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s decision will result in the elimination of 1,109 jobs in <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 54,502 EXPs in 1981, its best year for the model. In 1987 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold 24,427 EXPs out of 392,360 Escorts.
