<HEAD>Gillette, Coniston Square Off at Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of shareholders turned out for <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting today, where the consumer products giant squared off against <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in a highly visible takeover battle. The two companies waged a proxy war at the meeting, held at <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s manufacturing center in this town 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> sought four seats on <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors, but <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> hoped a coalition of loyal shareholders and last-minute support from large institutions would render enough votes to repel the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> group. Results of the election are expected later this month. Since <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> went public Feb. 11 with plans to seek control of <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>, the two rivals have traded barbs in the press and the courts. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>'s board candidates have pledged to support the divestiture of the worldwide empire <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> built around personal care products in an effort to increase profitability and boost the company's stock price. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> contends <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> is still mired by the nearly $ 580 million paid to <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 to abandon its repeated takeover attempts. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>, however, has pointed out to its nearly 27,000 shareholders a steady rise in earnings since the company laid off 2,400 workers and the sale of several unprofitable divisions after signing a 10-year no-takeover pact with <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> in 1986. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> said it might close some North American plants to further streamline operations. The takeover contest will likely be decided by institutional investors, which own between 60 percent to 65 percent of the 115.5 million <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> shares outstanding. <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION>, which has run newspapers ads attacking <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>'s `` greenmail'' payment to <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION>, claims to have the support of several major shareholders, including two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> pension plans with about 2.1 million shares and a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state retirement plan with nearly 2 million shares <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> proxy solicitor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilcox </PERSON> declined to name supporters, but he suggested many large shareholders will wait until the last moment to make a decision. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Fausch </PERSON> said that since the <ORGANIZATION> Coniston </ORGANIZATION> bid does not seek a complete change in control, some large shareholders may be willing to take a risk for greater profits. `` They look at the short-term gains,'' said <PERSON> Fausch </PERSON>. `` This is only four people on a 12-member board saying they'll push for a sale. It's not a complete switch in management.''
