<HEAD>Schlumberger Posts 19.2 Percent Quarterly Income Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Schlumberger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its first-quarter earnings jumped by 19.2 percent over the same period last year, boosted by an almost two-thirds growth in revenue from its oil exploration services. The world's largest oilfield services company reported a profit of $ 101.01 million, or 37 cents per share, on sales of $ 1.3 billion in the three months ended March 31. That compared with $ 4.99 million, or 2 cents per share, on $ 1.1 billion in revenue during the same period of 1987. Strong world economies helped increase sales, despite weakness in oil prices during the quarter, said <PERSON> Euan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baird </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Schlumberger </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman `` In particular, <ORGANIZATION> Schulmberger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, the electronics and metering businesses, posted record profits, revenue and orders,'' he said. In addition, <PERSON> Baird </PERSON> said the company benefitted from a 24 percent gain in sales by the company's oilfield services division, and a 61 percent revenue gain by another division that provides services to locate and evaluate oil and gas. Schlumberger is controlled by the founding French family. It is based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and incorporated in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antilles </LOCATION>.
