<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Editions of Monday April 25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Huge American Market Continues to Draw Foreign Retailers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the 1800s, the story goes, immigrants coming to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> believed the streets were paved with gold. Nowadays, it is foreign retailers who are arriving on these shores in search of their fortunes. They are lured by the size of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market and the American passion for foreign styles and goods. Several are already reporting success. `` We could get a large slice of the apple'' by selling in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirman </PERSON>, who helped introduce the <ORGANIZATION> Sock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shop </ORGANIZATION>, a chain of British hosiery stores, to this country. The most prominent of the new arrivals is <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The Canadian concern bought out <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 and is in the process of taking over <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. To help finance its purchase of <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> is selling Allied's <ORGANIZATION> Brooks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> chain to another foreign retailer, Marks and <ORGANIZATION> Spencer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> Meanwhile, the Australian developer <ORGANIZATION> Hooker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> moved into retailing with the purchase last year of the Bonwit Teller, <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Altman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sakowitz </PERSON> chains. Buying an American company is not the only way to get here. Some smaller companies are striking out on their own. Sock Shop is among them; so are Fil a Fil, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweaterie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tricots </PERSON> <PERSON> Caroll </PERSON>, apparel retailers from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. A foreign presence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailing industry is nothing new. In 1973, <ORGANIZATION> Batus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arm of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, swept in with the purchase of <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> and the now-closed <LOCATION> Gimbels </LOCATION> chain. And the fashionable streets of cities like <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> have been graced for years by names such as <ORGANIZATION> Gucci </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Courreges </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yves </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurent </PERSON>. But what is different about many of these latest arrivals is they are appealing to a larger and different market segment. Many offer moderately-priced merchandise, giving more consumers a chance to buy and wear clothes with foreign labels. With such prices, the new transplants `` have enormous development potential in this market,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Aug </PERSON>, whose company, <ORGANIZATION> Garrick-Aug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Store </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, scouts foreign retailers and helps them set up shop here. Many of the retailers are drawn to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in hopes of equaling the success of the Italian retailer <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION>, Aug said. <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> has grown to 760 stores in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ out of more than 4,500 worldwide _ since the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> store with its now-familiar bright green sign opened in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> in 1979, said <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the Italian retailer. Said Aug: `` The rapid growth of <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> generated the interest of the other European merchants to come over here and start moving.'' <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> stores are operated under licensing agreements with the Italian company. The stores sell only <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> fashions, and buy the clothes from <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. Other retailers break into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market through franchises, in which they can profit from an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> operation without having the expense and problems of opening and managing stores. Printemps, a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> fashion retailer, is a franchisee of Au Printemps, a French department store chain. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> store, which opened in November, operates autonomously of its namesake, but turns over to Au Printemps a percentage of its sales, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, president of the American company. The Denver store sells French fashions, but is `` Americanized for practicality,'' said <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>. `` We've used the name, but -LRB- the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> store is -RRB- not a reflection of the store in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>.'' Some retailers own their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> outlets. Sock Shop opened three stores in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> in December, and `` we're delighted with the way they're going,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Mirman </PERSON>, chairman of the company. Because of its size, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was one of several markets Sock Shop wanted to explore, Ms. <PERSON> Mirman </PERSON> said. The company hopes to open nine more outlets this year and eventually expand beyond <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The retailers generally get some assistance from American advisers or brokers before setting up shop. Ms. <PERSON> Mirman </PERSON> said Sock Shop's entry into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was facilitated by a minority stockholder who lived in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweaterie </PERSON> was brought into the American market through a joint venture with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Genser </PERSON>, the company's president here. Unlike many other foreign retailers, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweaterie </PERSON> did not try <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> first, opening instead in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area, where <PERSON> Genser </PERSON> lives. The retailer now has 29 stores in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, including several in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The weakness of the dollar since 1985 has helped some foreigners, Aug said, explaining, `` Installation costs would be a fraction of what it would have cost them a few years ago.'' But the lower dollar can be a double-edged sword. `` It's cheaper to set up shop, but that's offset by the fact that the market for goods at these price points does not grow ... when the dollar is buying less,'' said <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Garelick </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Rodier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, the American arm of the French clothing chain <PERSON> Rodier </PERSON>. <PERSON> Genser </PERSON> agreed. `` It has hurt us,'' he said of the dollar's decline `` All of our clothes are made in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>,'' and become more expensive as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency slides. One way to fight the impact of currency fluctuations is to become a more American company. <ORGANIZATION> Benetton </ORGANIZATION> has started manufacturing some of its merchandise in <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> said. `` But the style will remain something that's Italian and French _ what <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> companies have to offer,'' she said.
</TEXT>
