<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who scored a public relations coup over City Hall by rebuilding the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> skating rink, today offered the same deal for repairing the closed <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>. The real estate mogul took a tour of the decaying, 85-year-old span, then said he would be willing to put up an estimated $ 250 million, which the government would repay, for repairs. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> rebuilt the Wollman Skating Rink under a similar arrangement. `` An easy solution is to spend a lot of money but if you can spend a little money and get the same results for it, or a better result, that's what I'd be here for,'' <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said. The bridge was closed last week when city transportation officials found cracks in its beams. An inspection is under way to determine the extent of the damage, and officials have said the bridge will be closed at least three weeks. <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> DelliBovi </PERSON>, head of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, had invited <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> to examine the bridge, and joined him for today's tour. In a letter to <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dellibovi </PERSON> lauded him as a builder whose projects come in `` on time, under budget and built to last.'' In 1987, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> showed up the city bureaucracy when he took over repair of the skating rink and finished the job in five months and under budget. The city had spent 7 -LCB- years and $ 12 million on what was supposed to take 2 -LCB- years and $ 4.5 million.
