<HEAD>GM First-Quarter Earnings Up 18.4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its first-quarter earnings rose 18.4 percent, helped by a change in accounting methods. The nation's largest automaker said it earned $ 1.09 billion, or $ 3.11 a share, on sales of $ 26.44 billion. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 922.5 million, or $ 2.62 a share, on sales of $ 26.1 billion in first-quarter 1987. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> was the first of the Big Three auto companies to report its earnings for the first quarter. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which outearned <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 and 1987, and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> will report earnings next week. First-quarter results were fattened by $ 224 million, or 70 cents a share, by a Jan. 1 accounting change, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. Without the change, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s first-quarter earnings would have been $ 868 million, down 5.9 percent from a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday earnings rose for two of its subsidiaries, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, but fell for the third, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acceptance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> because of low interest rates to consumers. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s worldwide vehicle sales were down 5.2 percent from first-quarter 1987, but its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of domestic and imported cars rose more than 12 percent. Quarterly truck sales jumped 24 percent. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said its share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car market grew 4.1 percentage points in the first quarter from the final quarter of 1987 and it gained 2.2 points in truck market share. Overseas sales rose 15.5 percent in the first quarter, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. The automaker's operating earnings fell 4.3 percent to $ 657.6 million in the first quarter from $ 687.4 million a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said it made improvements in manufacturing efficiency and engineering, but the gains were not enough to offset lower sales, <ORGANIZATION> GMAC </ORGANIZATION>'s lower earnings and other cost increases. `` We're going to continue to cut costs and improve the efficiency of our plants and the quality of our products,'' the company said in a statement attributed to company Chairman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON>. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> trimmed $ 3.7 billion from its costs under the first phase of a four-year plan that calls for $ 4 billion in cost cuts in 1988. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said it cut $ 1.3 billion from its costs in first-quarter 1988. The company said it was encouraged by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales, which rose against year ago figures for each month of the third quarter. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s lineup includes its new mid-size siblings, the Pontiac Grand Prix, Buick Regal and <ORGANIZATION> Oldsmobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cutlass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said it had record truck sales during the quarter.
