<HEAD>Profit Up at Time, Times Mirror; Loss Reported at Houghton Mifflin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday its first-quarter profit jumped 43 percent while another publishing and broadcast concern, <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said its earnings climbed 29 percent from a year earlier. Meanwhile, the publisher <ORGANIZATION> Houghton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mifflin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said normal seasonal sluggishness in educational book orders produced a wider loss for the company in the first quarter. Time, which is based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said its magazine, books, programming and cable television operations each turned in improved results. It reported a profit of $ 66 million, or $ 1.13 a share, for the three months ended March 31, compared with earnings of $ 46 million, or 76 cents a share, a year earlier. First-quarter revenue rose 13.4 percent to $ 1.07 billion from $ 939 million a year earlier. Time said the pretax operating profit from its magazine group rose 19 percent to $ 70 million because of a rise in advertising sales that was attributed in part to the Olympics and an increase in circulation revenue. Time publishes Time, Life, People, Sports Illustrated, Money and Fortune magazines, among others. Time's books group broke even in contrast to an operating loss of $ 3 million a year earlier. The group's results reflect a seasonal loss at the Scott, <PERSON> Foresman </PERSON> educational book subsidiary, improved profits at the <ORGANIZATION> Oxmoor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and Little Brown units and a smaller profit at Time-Life Books. Operating income from the Time programming segment rose 8 percent to $ 39 million, as <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported subscriber growth and the release of several successful HBO videocassettes, including the film `` Platoon.'' In cable television, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s operating profit from its 82 percent-owned <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> unit rose 24 percent to $ 42 million, mostly due to new subscribers and price increases. Times-Mirror, which is based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said its results were boosted by strong cable television perfomance and sales of assets. The company reported net earnings of $ 75.1 million, or 58 cents per share, up from $ 58.2 million, or 45 cents per share, in the first quarter of 1987. Revenue for the quarter ended March 27 was $ 797.1 million, up 11.4 percent from $ 715.8 million in 1987. Operating profit improved 17 percent, paced by a 20 percent rise in cable television revenues, absence of losses at the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, which was sold in December 1987, and sales of timberlands and the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Times-Mirror publishes the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times, <ORGANIZATION> Newsday </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newsday </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION> Courant, the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Sun Newspapers and others. It has interests in broadcast and cable television, book, magazine and other publishing. <LOCATION> Houghton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mifflin </LOCATION>, which is based in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said its loss widened to $ 10.3 million in the first three months of 1988 from $ 6.7 million a year earlier. Revenue for the quarter fell 4.7 percent to $ 37.8 million from $ 39.7 million a year earlier. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive, said the loss reflected the normal seasonal ordering pattern of educational institutions, and said he expects the sluggishness to continue through the second quarter. Educational publishing sales were off 9 percent in the quarter, while early book returns pushed down net sales in the college division by an unspecified amount. General publishing sales were up 3 percent, led by strong sales of juvenile books.
