<HEAD>Judge Orders `Cigarette Trial' to Continue; Cites Evidence of
Conspiracy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts and removes word ``ruled'' from lead to clarify this
not a final judgment; graf 2 picks up into graf 3 pvs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Evidence presented in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>'s closely watched `` cigarette trial'' indicates tobacco companies conspired to hide the dangers of smoking, and the jury trial should continue, a federal judge declared today. At the same time, however, Judge <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> dismissed a claim that the three companies sued in the liability case _ <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ caused <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s lung cancer by not marketing a safer cigarette. Attorneys for Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> argued that the companies knew they could develop a safer cigarette that had less potential of causing cancer. Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>, 64, of <LOCATION> Lakehurst </LOCATION>, died in 1984 after 40 years of smoking. But the judge said the attorneys for Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s estate, carrying on a lawsuit filed before she died, had not presented evidence to support that claim. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, said the jury trial will continue over whether the three manufacturers conspired to misrepresent and conceal facts regarding the dangers of smoking. He also said Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON>'s estate could continue seeking punitive damages. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> said that the evidence indicates that the cigarette industry `` entered into a sophisticated conspiracy. `` The conspiracy was organized to refute, undermine and neutralize information coming from the scientific and medical community and, at the same time, to confuse and mislead the consuming public in an effort to encourage existing smokers to continue and new persons to commence smoking,'' the judge said. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> also said `` a jury might reasonably conclude ... that the defendants in particular, and the industry in general, intentionally and willfully ignored the known health consequences to consumers from the sale of their products.'' `` The evidence presented also permits the jury to find the tobacco industry conspiracy vast in its scope, devious in its purpose and devastating in its results,'' the judge said. But <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> dismissed claims that <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> failed to warn Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> of the dangers of cigarettes. The judge said Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> did not start smoking cigarettes manufactured by those two companies until she was a veteran smoker and the companies had no duty to warn her about any dangers until she became a consumer of their products. Similar claims against <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION>, however, were allowed to continue. The trial, which began Feb. 1, is viewed by both the industry and smoking opponents as critical in the tobacco companies' efforts to defend against future liability cases.
</TEXT>
