<HEAD>URGENT
^Eds: New with bill passing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House today passed sweeping trade legislation, ignoring fresh veto threats from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and defiantly upholding the measure's embattled plant closings provisions. `` Our future is not in the past,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said as he urged approval of the bill with the plant closings feature intact. `` We can regain our competitiveness ... We can be No. 1 again.'' The bill passed by a vote of 312-107. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, on the road in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, said he would veto the legislation if it arrived on his desk with the plant closings provision included in it. He also sent a letter to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., saying, `` I want a trade bill. `` I will work vigorously to secure one,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` And I will urge the leadership to schedule prompt action on a bill immediately after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sustains my forthcoming veto'' of the current trade bill. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected 253-167 a move by <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> to return the trade bill to a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee with orders to drop the plant closings provision. Critics of the provision warned that it would not only trigger a veto but that if it went into law it would cripple American business by drying up capital for investment, frightening off customers and causing other problems. The measure would require all but the smallest employers to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. The provision completely overshadowed the centerpiece features of the legislation which would streamline the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import curbs to aid industries threatened by foreign competition and retaliate against international trade violations. Scores of other features range from repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies to billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies. Republicans portrayed the measure as doomed to a veto with the plant closings provision still part of it. `` I'm more interested in plant openings than plant closings,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. `` We can exorcise this demon,'' said Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>. The legislation would overhaul the system under which the government retaliates against international trade violations and uses import curbs to aid American industries hurt by surging foreign competition. These provisions have figured little in battles over the bill in recent weeks, however. The White House has issued numerous threats of a presidential veto if the plant-closings provisions remain. Efforts to whisk the bill through the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday were stalled for hours over Democratic concerns that <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> would muster the strength on the floor to send the measure back to the committee. `` It is my hope that through this motion we will be able to get a trade bill that can actually be enacted into law,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> said after the <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> cleared the way for him to go ahead with his plan. The idea of a veto over plant closings is proving less than appetizing to lawmakers with a host of narrow election-year items tucked into the trade bill, ranging from repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies to billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> on Wednesday to try to rally <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members to oppose the measure if the measures on plant closings remained in. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday the administration was `` pessimistic'' about chances that lawmakers would send the president legislation he would sign. `` I would say we are not too optimistic at this point,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` The indications have been that the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is not going to relent on plant closings as well as some of the other provisions, so I would say that we are pretty pessimistic that we will get a bill that we could sign.''
