<HEAD>Soybean Futures Fall With Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Soybean futures prices fell sharply Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as rain dampened the dry fields of the western Corn Belt and the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soybean harvest accelerated. Grains also finished lower. On other markets, energy futures advanced; stock-index futures plunged; precious metals were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Rain in western <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, where spring planting has just begun, melted fears that dry conditions would delay germination of seeds, analysts said. Soybean prices came under additional pressure from the Brazilian soybean harvest, now more than 50 percent complete, and the beginning of the Argentine soybean harvest, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Loewy </PERSON>, senior grain and oilseed analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` They should be 80 to 85 percent finished in May,'' he said of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> harvest. `` Then our crush and export rate will tail off, and you do n't get as much domestic meal feeding anyway as we get into the warmer weather.'' Further pressure on the soy complex came from an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> statement that it did not expect the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to offer the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> 170,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean oil under its Export Enhancement Program, <PERSON> Loewy </PERSON> said. Wheat settled -LCB- cent to 1 cent lower with 