 <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s profit rose 132 percent and its revenue rose 108 percent in the latest quarter, the mushrooming maker of personal computers said Thursday. Among other technology companies, semiconductor maker <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> said its profit fell 4.9 percent and minicomputer maker <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Westboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said it made a profit in contrast to a year-earlier loss. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> announced separately that <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Junkins </PERSON> will take on the title of chairman upon the retirement of <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepherd </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, which was previously announced. <PERSON> Junkins </PERSON> is already president and chief executive. <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>, which reached the Fortune 500 and the $ 1 billion annual sales mark faster than any other company, continued to skyrocket in the first quarter. The Houston-based company attributed the gains to international market growth, a strong brand image and sales of its top-of-the-line products, including the Deskpro 386-20. <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>'s profit rose to $ 47 million, or $ 1.21 a share, from $ 20 million, or 56 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $ 439 million from $ 211 million. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION>, which makes computer chips, defense electronics and other products, said its profit fell to $ 85.5 million, or 95 cents a share, from $ 89.9 million, or $ 1.12 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 15.4 percent to $ 1.47 billion from $ 1.27 billion. Data General said net income for its second fiscal quarter totaled $ 17.2 million, or 57 cents a share, a reversal from a $ 42.6 million loss in the same period last year. The computer maker reported revenues of $ 349.7 million, a 10.9 percent increase over last year's $ 315.2 million. The company attributed part of the rise to the $ 5.9 million sale of a company facility in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, during the quarter. For the six-month period ending March 26, <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 29.6 million, or $ 1.01 a share, compared with a net loss of $ 39.3 million in the same period a year earlier. Revenue rose 10.2 percent to $ 692.5 million from $ 628.5 million.
