<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn syrup maker <ORGANIZATION> Staley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> rejected as inadequate a $ 1.33 billion takeover bid from a British company Thursday but indicated it might entertain a better offer. <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Lyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, which made the $ 32-a-share cash tender offer April 8, declined comment on <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s decision but one analyst said he expected the British sugar refiner to increase its bid. <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> did announce it has arranged a $ 1.3 billion loan agreement wiht a group of 14 banks to finance a takeover. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> stock rose 75 cents to $ 37.50 a share in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>, the nation's second-largest refiner of corn sweeteners, said it would consider various alternatives for enhancing shareholder value. The options include a financial restructuring or recapitalization, issuing stock to a third party, selling all or part of the company, a joint venture or a leveraged buyout, <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordlund </PERSON> said in a letter to stockholders. Spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Satterfield </PERSON> said <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> had held discussions with at least one other party but added that the company wanted to remain independent. `` I think the board has asked management to look at all the various alternatives because as part of its fiduciary responsibility they've got to be able to make the best judgment possible for shareholders,'' <PERSON> Satterfield </PERSON> said. One option likely to present itself is a higher offer from <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I think they officially put the ` for sale' sign on the company,'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said. `` But from a shareholder's point of view, they said all the right things: That they're contemplating alternative moves designed to enhance the value of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s stock beyond the $ 32 that <PERSON> Tate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> offered.'' <PERSON> McMillan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> probably was worth about $ 40 a share. But he said he doubted a bidding war would develop. `` I do n't think there's a line of bidders that want to get into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sweetener industry,'' he said. `` It's a competitive market and it takes special managerial skills.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> is <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s second-largest sugar refiner. An acquisition of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> would give it a foothold in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn sweetener market and make it the only supplier of all three types of sugar _ corn, beet and cane _ in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON>'s owns nearly 5 percent of <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>'s 30.4 million outstanding shares of common stock and is offering to buy all outstanding shares of all classes of