<HEAD>House Passes Trade Bill by Wide Margin Despite Veto Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: The bill, to show it is a product of
House-Senate conference committee</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Thursday passed a sweeping trade bill, delivering a sharp blow to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as supporters of the hotly disputed measure piled up enough votes to override his threatened veto. `` Our future is n't in the past,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, declared as he fought a move to return the bill to a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> and drop a plant-closings provision that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he could not approve. `` We can regain our competitiveness. ... We can be No. 1 again. The final tally, 312-107, contradicted numerous forecasts that the bill's sponsors would fail to produce the two-thirds vote needed to override a veto. But many lawmakers, even if they had their doubts, appeared to have no taste in an election year for going on record against a measure billed as a plan to upgrade American competitiveness. The bill was a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> compromise on two competing measures that passed both chambers last year. The measure now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, planned to begin debate He was shooting for a vote on final passage early next week. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the measure after defeating, 253-167, a move by Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., to throw the bill back to the conference committee and drop the plant-closings provision <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, on the road in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, said he would veto the bill if it came to him with the plant-closings provision intact. He also sent a letter to <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, saying, `` I want a trade bill.'' `` I will work vigorously to secure one,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` And I will urge the leadership to schedule prompt action on a bill immediately after the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sustains my forthcoming veto'' of the current trade bill. Controversy over the plant-closings provision overshadowed central features of the bill, which would streamline the way the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import curbs to aid <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries and retaliate against international trade violations. Scores of other provisions ranged from repeal of the windfall profits tax to billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies. Dueling over plant closings provision went on almost to the last minute. `` I am more interested in plant openings than plant closings,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. However, Rep. <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif., said it would be a mistake to allow such an important measure to become hung up on one provision `` It is so modest, so watered down, so full of exceptions'' that it probably will not have as much effect as lawmakers intended, he said. Debate focused heavily on the provision that would require all but the smallest employers to give 60-day notice of upcoming plant closings and large-scale layoffs. The measure contains a number of exceptions for companies that sudenly find themselves in an emergency. The centerpiece provisions would streamline the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import curbs and other means to aid industries threatened by foreign competition and retaliate against international trade violatrions. Scores of other provisions range from repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies to billions of dollars in new agricultural subsidies. <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., said the bill for the first time `` establishes a policy that will make <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> a winner in international competitive markets. But Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., whose amendment to roll back Japanese trade surpluses was dropped earlier, said the measure did not go far enough in forcing open foreign markets Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., said that with the ink barely dry he had discovered that the 1,000-page bill would increase the amount of <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> ethanol allowed in duty-free `` I thought we were going to try to create jobs, I thought we were going to create markets,'' <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON> said. `` But here we are trying to give away some of our own jobs and give away some of our own markets, just exactly the oppsosite of what we said we were trying to do.'' But Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., said `` This bill will put pressure on our trading competitors to open up their markets and play fairly and squarely with the trading system that we already have. Republican critics of the plant-closings provision cited business fears that plant-closings notice would reduce credit, frighten customers, cut productivity and perhaps lead to sabotage among disappointed employees facing layoffs. They also said it had no direct connection with the trade issue.
</TEXT>
