<HEAD>NBC Employee Survey Finds Anxiety About GE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A majority of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> employees are skeptical of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment to continue ownership of the network, according to results of a survey conducted by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and described in a letter sent to employees by <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> on Thursday. `` GE is viewed with skepticism and uncertainty. More employees feel that <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> will not continue its <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> ownership, even with <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> performing well, than believe GE will be around for the long haul,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. He said even more employees believe <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> will not allow <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> to operate independently, and many do n't like the effect the new corporate owner has had on their working environment. GE, which is based in <LOCATION> Fairfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, acquired <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 as part of its purchase of the <ORGANIZATION> RCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was a <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> executive before taking over as <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> president and chief executive officer. A `` high percentage'' of employees do not feel their jobs are secure, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. Nevertheless, he said, they feel better off than people in similar jobs in other areas of the industry. `` While almost half of the employees say they are not encouraged by the direction they see <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> taking today, a majority of employees say they are not likely to leave the company because of dissatisfaction,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said in the letter. `` All of this anxiety is understandable,'' he wrote. `` Change is always stressful and the vast changes that are taking place in the broadcasting business have understandably resulted in considerable employee anxiety and insecurity. The survey clearly reflects this.'' Nonetheless, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said most employees said they were happy with their jobs and a majority were felt their salaries compared favorably to the rest of the industry. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> concluded the letter by assuring employees that `` you have been heard.'' He said next month employees would be asked to participate in discussions of problems mentioned in the survey. `` Creating an atmosphere in which we can go forward with far less doubt about <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s goals and intentions is the first priority of our management team for the coming year,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said.
